<FIRST>r p PM-AndrewYoung     11-29 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Andrew Young,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Andy Young: Playing Down Race in Campaign for Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Young doesn't play up the milestone
victories of two black candidates in New York City and Virginia,
but he does share one strategy in his quest to become governor of
Georgia _ he rarely mentions race.
   There's little doubt race will be a factor in many voters' minds
next summer as they size up Young, who is finishing eight years as
Atlanta's mayor. Some pundits already have predicted he will fail
in his bid to become the state's first black governor.
   But others are talking about momentum from the successful
campaigns of Virginia Gov.-elect L. Douglas Wilder and New York
Mayor-elect David Dinkins.
   Young isn't jumping on that bandwagon.
   ``I think it feels good to be a respectable candidate, and
that's all I think I am at this point,'' he said.
   Young says he doesn't have much in common with Wilder and
Dinkins ``other than the fact that we all went to the same college,
Howard University, and we all happen to have the same skin color.''
   But lately, he has done at least one thing both Dinkins and
Wilder did: dismiss race as a factor.
   His campaign chairman is Griffin Bell, a former U.S. attorney
general and federal judge who is white and conservative. Bell was
U.S. attorney general in Jimmy Carter's administration; Young was
ambassador to the United Nations.
   Young also is aggressively pursuing the white vote in mostly
rural and conservative south Georgia, pushing his record for
business development and economic expansion. His campaign manager
is a white former small-town south Georgia mayor, Hobby Stripling
of Vienna.
   ``I would suspect that the Young organization has been studying
carefully the Wilder campaign,'' said Merle Black, a political
science professor at Emory University.
   But unlike Wilder, Young has stuck to his bent for the off-beat.
His latest escapade came last week, when he ate dinner in a rustic
juke joint where two racially offensive songs are featured on the
jukebox.
   ``I'll go anywhere and talk to anybody,'' Young said. ``The
world is made up of different people, and the only way we're going
to survive is to learn to co-exist and respect one another.''
   While there, he played down race in an obviously racially
charged situation and took the opportunity to give the restaurant's
owner a Ray Charles record for the jukebox.
   Political watchers say Young is taking pains to put himself
forth as a racially palatable black candidate.
   ``The fact that Douglas Wilder now has won shows it can be done.
To that extent, it helps Andrew Young be seen as a more credible
and realistic candidate,'' Black said. ``It would have been a
setback for Young's campaign if Wilder had lost.''
   Wilder said his campaign was successful because it appealed to
mainstream values. Although his candidacy was closely watched by
black leaders, Wilder deliberately kept liberal two-time
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson at arms length and did not
invite Jackson to campaign for him.
   Young also will not include Jackson in his campaign, Stripling
said Tuesday.
   ``We don't have any plans to ask Mr. Jackson for any help,'' he
said. ``Our campaign is a Georgia-based campaign, and we will
handle it from within the state.''
   Young was booed loudly by Jackson supporters at the 1984
Democratic National Convention in San Francisco; the Jackson
forces, frustrated over their failure to win concessions from the
Walter Mondale camp, yelled at Young when he rose to speak on
behalf of a Mondale position.
   Young was stunned, his wife cried and a press aide collapsed.
Still, Young and Jackson have remained cordial.
   Atlanta political pollster Claibourne Darden predicts Young's
campaign will be troubled by race, whether he likes it or not.
   Young could come in first in the first round of the Democratic
primary on the strength of his name recognition and the black vote;
24 percent of Georgia's voting-age population is black, Darden
said. But Young wouldn't get the 50 percent he would need to win,
Darden said.
   ``He will be in the runoff regardless'' Darden said. ``But we
are still at a place where a tremendous number of white people in
Georgia are not willing to vote for a black candidate.
   ``It's not like Virginia. You're in the Deep South here, and the
black population is significantly larger. That's unfortunately a
pretty good correlation for prejudice. The larger the (minority)
group, the more prejudice there is.''
   Young, however, discounts that.
   ``I always felt that white folk in Georgia are way ahead of
white folk in New York or Virginia already,'' he said. ``I used to
kid Dave Dinkins that if he could get 30 percent of the white vote
in New York, I know I can get 45 or 50 in Georgia.''
   In the Democratic primary, Young faces Lt. Gov. Zell Miller, two
powerful state legislators, Sen. Roy Barnes and Rep. Bubba
McDonald, and a wild-card entry, former Gov. Lester Maddox.
   The front-runner for the Republican nomination is state Rep.
Johnny Isakson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
