<FIRST>r a PM-TripleSurprise     11-29 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Triple Surprise,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Vasectomy, Man Fathers Triplets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam and Julie Morter thought their family
was complete after having three sons, so Sam had a vasectomy.
   Then came the Morters' daughters _ triplets.
   ``We just tell everybody we hoped and prayed for a little girl
and we must have prayed too hard, because now we have three,'' said
Morter, a technical sergeant stationed at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base.
   The Morters always wanted a girl.
   Their first-born was a boy, Jeffy. Then came Johnny, then Jimmy.
   The Morters decided three was enough, and in July 1987, while he
was stationed in Korea, the vasectomy was performed.
   Morter, 29, said a follow-up test performed by an Air Force
surgeon confirmed that the vasectomy was successful.
   Then came Samantha, Stephanie and Sarah, who celebrated their
first birthday Nov. 19.
   Last year, before prescribing birth control pills as treatment
for an ovarian cyst, Ms. Morter's doctor gave her a routine
pregnancy test, even though Mrs. Morter insisted she couldn't
possibly be expecting.
   ``They said, `Not only are you pregnant, you're very pregnant,'
'' Morter said. ``We didn't know what that meant.''
   ``We found out, though,'' his wife said.
   After the pregnancy was confirmed, Morter had his vasectomy
re-examined. A test showed that his sperm count was 30 percent of
normal, instead of zero.
   Doctors aren't sure why the vasectomy failed, Morter said.
   ``They said they'd have to go back in and look,'' he said. He
told them not to bother.
   After the triplets arrived, Mrs. Morter, 28, had her Fallopian
tubes tied. Dr. Jan Bernie, a Dayton urologist, said vasectomy
failure is ``not very common at all. I've done them for 20 years
and maybe one or two in all that time (has failed). It's a very
effective method of birth control.''
   In Morter's case, one of the tubes that carry the sperm from the
testicles probably grew back together, Bernie said.
</TEXT>
