<FIRST>r a AM-FishermenLost 1stLd-Writethru a0660 11-29 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fishermen Lost, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Focuses Southeast of Nantucket</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with second flare spotted, quotes,
search continuing; picks up 4th graf: `Of Friday ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second night in a row, Coast Guard
searchers spotted a flare Tuesday in their hunt for five lobsterman
who disappeared a week ago off the Massachusetts coast.
   The sighting, about 250 miles south of Nantucket, is in a remote
area where Coast Guard rescuers believe a life raft might have
drifted.
   ``The flares are coming from somewhere,'' said Lt. Paul Wolf of
the Coast Guard office in Boston. ``There are no other boats out
there except the Coast Guard.''
   ``We're going to search as long as there's a reasonable
possibility that someone is alive and needs help,'' said Coast
Guard Petty Officer Elizabeth Brannan.
   The 72-foot Heidi Marie, out of Stonington, Conn., was reported
missing by its owner on Nov. 22. The boat's last transmission was
the previous day, the same day officials received a distress signal.
   The jet that spotted the flare Tuesday night continued
searching. Two Coast Guard cutters were also sent to the scene.
   A red flare had been spotted in the area Monday night. Both
orange and red flares are used to signal an emergency, Wolf said.
Flare lights last about two minutes.
   The jet that spotted the second emergency flare was due to
return to land for refueling at about 10 p.m., Wolf said. But a
second aircraft was sent to the area to take its place.
   ``We're so far off shore that it's difficult,'' Wolf said.
   On Friday, rescuers turned up a floating radio beacon and
fishing markers bearing the Heidi Marie's name. The fishing boat
was equipped with a life raft big enough for the entire crew.
   On Tuesday, three aircraft and two cutters searched an
8,000-square-mile area, some of which had been covered before.
   Brannan said the search concentrated around the area where a red
flare was seen Monday night. Coast guard officials said the person
who lit the flare could have been anywhere from 6 to 30 miles from
where it was spotted.
   ``Where the flare was seen is where our trajectory was
predicting the raft would be,'' Brannan said.
   The manufacturer of the boat's life raft told Coast Guard
officials that the craft contained three orange smoke flares, three
red distress flares, plus an unspecified number of parachute
flares, such as the one seen Monday.
   Brannan said she could not speculate about whether the crew
members could survive a week at sea in the life raft.
   ``It depends _ were there provisions? Were they wearing survival
suits?'' she said. The lobster boat carried survival suits for
seven people.
   Seas last Tuesday were reported to be 26 feet high with wind
gusts to 45 knots in the area where the Heidi Marie was lobstering.
   But fishermen in Stonington said it was not unusual for a boat
to stay out in rough seas.
   ``That boat has weathered worse weather,'' said fisherman Skip
Babin.
</TEXT>
