<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     11-29 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's `Roseanne' Gets Thanksgiving Ratings Boost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC-TV's ``Roseanne'' was back on top of the
Nielsen ratings because of the Thanksgiving holiday as NBC's
Thursday night shows got the turkey leftovers.
   ``The Wonder Years'' placed second for last week as all of ABC's
Tuesday night comedies landed in the top 10. None of NBC's Thursday
shows made it into the top rankings because of a 20 percent
Thanksgiving tune out.
   ABC's ``Whose the Boss?'' was fourth and ``Coach,'' in its
premiere appearance in place of the canceled ``Chicken Soup,'' tied
for eighth. Its other Tuesday show, ``thirtysomething,'' tied for
36th.
   NBC had only two shows in the top 10, ``The Golden Girls'' in
fifth place and ``Empty Nest'' tied for sixth.
   The highest-rated NBC Thursday show was ``Cheers,'' in 13th
place. A rerun of ``The Cosby Show,'' first in recent weeks, was
14th. ``L.A. Law'' tied for 17th, ``A Different World'' tied for
22nd, and ``Dear John'' tied for 25th.
   NBC still won the week with a prime-time ratings average of
13.8, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co. The previous week, NBC had
an average of 16.0.
   ABC was second last week with 12.9 and CBS had 12.3. Each
ratings point represents the percentage of the nation's 92.1
million television households tuned to a show.
   The top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne,'' ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' CBS'
``60 Minutes,'' ABC's ``Who's the Boss?,'' NBC's ``The Golden
Girls,'' NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote'' tied,
CBS National League Football Sunday and ABC's ``Coach'' tied, ABC's
``America's Funniest Home Videos'' and ABC's NFL Monday Night
Football tied.
   NBC is ahead in the season-to-date ratings and in the November
sweeps, which are used to help determine local advertising rates.
In the first 10 weeks of the season, NBC has averaged a 15.0 rating
to ABC's 13.5 and CBS' 12.4.
   The ratings for the sweeps: Arbitron for 26 days, NBC 15.0, ABC
12.8, CBS 12.0. Nielsen for 25 days, NBC 15.1, ABC 12.6, CBS 12.1.
   ABC and CBS tied for first place among the evening news shows,
although ABC had a slightly higher audience share. Each had a
rating of 10.0, which also represents a slight viewer tune out for
the holiday week. NBC was third with 9.3.
</TEXT>
