<FIRST>r w PM-SummitExpectations Bjt   11-29 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Expectations, Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Planning for the `Summit With No Agenda'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was to be a casual ``feet up'' meeting with
neither expectations nor an agenda. But since this weekend's
superpower summit was first announced, the White House is gradually
defining items it expects to broach at Malta.
   The administration is seeking to shape an agenda that seems
guaranteed to keep the feet of both Soviet and U.S. leaders firmly
planted _ even as President Bush insists his shipboard summit with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will yield no deals and no
surprises.
   ``So the surprise will be, if you're looking for a surprise,
there won't be a surprise. That may come as a surprise,'' Bush told
reporters Tuesday.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater recently observed
that the Soviets tend to overplay advance expectations for summits,
Americans tend to minimize them; and that the truth lies somewhere
in between.
   So, a week after Bush told a Providence, R.I., audience the
summit would be ``historic,'' the president complained to reporters
during an Oval Office picture-taking session Tuesday about ``all
kind of hyped speculation.''
   Bush insisted he would cut no deals with Gorbachev on arms
control nor do anything else that would give allies pause. And he
said the meeting remains ``without a fixed agenda.''
   Still, in an effort not to be caught off-guard as the United
States was at the 1987 Reagan-Gorbachev summit at Reykjavik, the
Bush administration has been compiling a list of subjects that Bush
is prepared to discuss.
   It also has suggested ground rules on how some of the subjects
will be handled.
   That looks an awful lot like an agenda.
   For one thing, the president has made clear he will confront
Gorbachev on the issue of continued Soviet bloc arms shipments to
rebels in El Salvador, by way of Nicaragua and Fidel Castro's Cuba.
   The administration has said the continued shipments threaten
improved U.S.-Soviet relations in other areas.
   ``I'm not the sort of man that will go there and not raise it,''
Bush said.
   Bush also has vowed to ``seek his (Gorbachev's) active
cooperation in cleaning up the world's environment.''
   ``A world solution can begin with the United States and the
Soviet Union,'' the president told a Republican fund-raising
audience several days ago.
   The unraveling of the Soviet Union's East European dominion, of
course, will set the tone for the Bush-Gorbachev talks and dominate
any agenda-setting efforts.
   Bush has said he intends to discuss the upheaval in detail with
the Soviet leader and will delve into such issues as U.S. trade
with Soviet bloc nations.
   But he has been careful to assure the United States' European
allies that he and Gorbachev will not discuss any future European
boundaries, that the fate of Eastern bloc nations should be theirs
alone to decide.
   White House officials also indicated this week that Bush is
prepared to talk with Gorbachev about arms reductions in Europe,
even though the administration earlier played down this aspect.
   U.S. officials have suggested that the breakup of the Warsaw
Pact could provide a golden opportunity for deep cuts in U.S.
defense spending _ much of which is earmarked for waging a war in
Europe.
   Fitzwater said that ``certainly the two presidents in Malta will
talk about arms control and military force structure.''
   But Bush emphasized Tuesday that he would not ``enter into an
arms control agreement'' at the summit, and would not catch U.S.
allies off guard. Bush is to brief allies in Brussels at the
conclusion of the summit.
   If the low-key projections issuing from the White House this
week follow an old mold for summitry, they also adhere to a pattern
Bush has set in his political life.
   Bush and his lieutenants did their best to lower expectations
about Bush's 1988 acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention; and yet the intensely practiced speech he gave was one
that many analysts viewed as the best of his career.
   The Bush camp sought to play down expectations of the
candidate's performance potential before both of his campaign
debates with Democratic contender Michael Dukakis.
   And, more recently, Bush and his lieutenants voiced low
expectations before May's NATO summit in Brussels that the session
would produce anything dramatic or lead to a resolution of the
alliance's intramural dispute over short-range arms based in West
Germany.
   However, Bush produced a breakthrough compromise that unified
NATO on the arms issue.
</TEXT>
