<FIRST>r w PM-US-Poland     11-29 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Aid Plan for Poland and Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, while telling a Poland-bound
delegation of prominent Americans ``dollars alone won't make the
difference,'' is sending nearly $1 billion in U.S. aid to Poland
and Hungary.
   Bush used a Tuesday evening sendoff reception for the U.S.
mission to sign legislation providing $938 million for the two East
bloc nations over the next three years.
   In addition, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, who heads
the mission, said he will announce a new $20 million installment in
U.S. food aid on Thursday in Warsaw.
   Bush told the presidential panel, as it prepared to leave
Washington on its four-day tour of Poland, that it should give him
an initial report by phone while he is in Malta this weekend for
his shipboard summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``I want to know how this goes. I'd like to hear it there, in
Malta. It will give me flexibility in my talks with the general
secretary,'' Bush said.
   He said the upheavals sweeping Poland and other Soviet bloc
nations would be ``high on our agenda'' at the summit.
   Bush signed the legislation, which provides more aid than he had
sought, at a reception for the presidential mission at Blair House,
the official guest residence across the street from the White
House. The mission left Washington later Tuesday night and was to
return on Saturday.
   The legislation, which Bush called ``a major and positive step
in bipartisan foreign policy,'' includes programs for Poland with a
value of $846.5 million. Hungary would receive benefits with a
total value of $91.5 million.
   He said both nations had ``stirred the imagination of the
world.''
   ``We are nearing the end of a year that future generations will
remember as a watershed, a year when the human spirit was lifted
and spurred on by the bold and courageous actions of two great
peoples, the people of Poland and Hungary,'' Bush said.
   However, he said that ``we've got to recognize the fact that
dollars alone won't make the difference.''
   He said the ``economic miracle'' of Western Europe came only
after ``full engagement of our private sector in shaping the free
market system that has generated unprecedented prosperity across
Western Europe.''
   ``That lesson holds true for Poland today,'' Bush continued.
``Our aid must be seen as seed money for free market reform and for
the involvement of our private sector.''
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., chief sponsor of the Poland aid bill,
said in a statement after the bill-signing, ``Now we're a partner
with the forces of freedom in eastern Europe. We're giving
Solidarity a fighting chance to succeed.''
   Yeutter voiced some pessimism on short-term prospects for
improved conditions either in Poland or in its fast-changing East
bloc neighbors.
   ``Economic reform is not an overnight proposition. It will take
time. It would be tragic indeed if all the magnificent emotion of
the moment is channeled into frustration,'' he told a White House
news briefing.
   The delegation includes Yeutter, Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole,
Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, chief White House economist
Michael Boskin and 20 representatives of business, labor and
academia.
   Another two dozen government officials also were expected to
accompany the delegation.
   Bush named the delegation last month to ``focus on those
economic sectors where U.S. expertise and experience can be of
greatest assistance.'' He said other missions, targeting more
specific areas, would follow.
   Mrs. Dole, who with her husband Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole
visited Poland in August, predicted a period of ``some pain'' as
Poland moves from a state-owned economy to a market economy.
   ``There'll be a loss of jobs for some people. Also, as subsidies
are removed from certain areas, there will be an increase in
prices,'' the labor secretary said.
   She said the U.S. government could help the new Solidarity-led
government ease the pain by establishing some form of social safety
net to ``help workers make it through the inevitable dislocations.''
</TEXT>
