<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Drugs     11-29 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Planned Into Handling of Barry Drug Allegation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia investigators plan to
question police officials who in 1983 reviewed allegations that
Mayor Marion Barry was hospitalized for drug overdoses, a published
report says.
   Barry released a statement Tuesday night calling the allegations
``outrageous'' and adding, ``I went to the hospital because I had a
sharp pain across my chest ... I wasn't using illegal drugs then or
at any other time.''
   The Washington Post today quoted unnamed police sources as
saying that Police Chief Isaac Fulwood Jr. has ordered an internal
investigation into the handling of the allegations.
   WUSA-TV reported Monday that Barry was hospitalized for cocaine
overdoses at Howard University and D.C. General Hospital in 1983,
according to allegations made to police nine months later by Dr.
Alyce Gullattee, a Howard University drug abuse specialist.
   On Tuesday, former police chief Maurice T. Turner said Gullattee
came to him with the allegations and he turned them over to the
department's Internal Affairs Division, which was then unable to
verify her account.
   ``Basically the investigation revealed it was unsubstantiated
allegations,'' said Turner, a Republican who is an unannounced
candidate for mayor in next year's election.
   Turner confirmed that Barry was not treated by Gullattee in
either instance. He also said Gullattee's information came from her
patients and she had no firsthand knowledge of the mayor's medical
treatment.
   Donald C. Thomas, a physician who was then the director of the
D.C. General Hospital's emergency room, said Barry underwent a
checkup for several hours before he was released and was told to
take it easy. Thomas, who supervised Barry's care, said there was
no indication that Barry had been using drugs.
   Turner scoffed at suggestions that either he or the police
officers handling the case might have muddled the investigation to
protect the mayor.
   ``Why waste 32 years (on the police force) to cover up something
like this?'' Turner told WRC-TV. ``It's just not worth it.''
   At the time, officials said Barry had been hospitalized for
flareups of a hiatal hernia problem.
   A spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office said Tuesday there
was insufficient evidence to open an investigation.
   Barry's activities already are under federal grand jury
investigation in connection with convicted drug dealer Charles
Lewis, who said in open court that he bought drugs for Barry.
   Turner said he has known Gullattee for about 12 years. He told
WUSA-TV on Tuesday that she told police investigators she knew a
7-year-old boy who was a drug addict. That story was the subject of
a Washington Post article by Janet Cook, which won a 1981 Pulitzer
Prize. The newspaper was forced to return the award when Cook
admitted that the boy was fictional.
   Police ``exhausted a lot of resources'' trying to find the boy,
whom Gullattee said she knew, Turner added.
   Gullattee did not return several telephone calls to her office
on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
