<FIRST>r a PM-People-Kissinger     11-29 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Kissinger,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Disrupt Comments From Former Secretary of State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators protesting U.S. policy in El
Salvador drowned out much of former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger's comments at a news conference in which he focused on
Eastern Europe.
   ``Go to Washington and argue with the people in Washington,''
Kissinger told one protester who had gotten into Tuesday's news
conference.
   Kissinger, in town for a speech at the University of Minnesota,
refused to discuss El Salvador, except to say that protesters don't
have ``the foggiest idea of what I support.''
   About 30 student protesters chanted ``Stop the killing. Stop the
war. U.S. out of El Salvador'' outside the hall where Kissinger was
speaking.
   Protester Jennifer Leazer of Minneapolis said Kissinger's
appearance was being opposed because of his ``history of
involvement as an architect of American policy.''
   At the news conference, Kissinger called the recent reforms in
Eastern Europe ``one of the most important and, in many ways,
pregnant moments'' since the end of World War II.
   ``Now we are in a world in which major parts of what was under
communism can join and overall international order which is going
to be less dangerous, more peaceful and maker a greater
contribution to progress,'' he said.
   ``That sort of opportunity comes along only once in a century.''
