<DOCNO> AP891129-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     11-29 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Will Visit Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter says
he'll be looking for ways to make Poland a paying customer for
American goods as he leads an economic assistance mission there
this week.
   ``A lot of the focus on Poland has been on aid and assistance,''
Yeutter said Tuesday. ``But that kind of help is transitory.''
   The U.S. delegation arriving in Poland today will look for ways
to keep the country from becoming overly dependent on others, said
Yeutter, adding that Poland should be helped to ``stand on its own
two feet.''
   If all goes well, Poland and other East bloc countries that are
opening to the West will be better customers, Yeutter said.
   Congress has approved a $533 million aid package for Poland and
Hungary, $125 million of which is food aid.
   Yeutter's remarks came at Outlook '90, an annual conference
sponsored by the Agriculture Department to examine farm policies
and factors that affect them.
   He left Tuesday night for four days in Poland with a delegation
of 20 private-sector representatives, Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher, Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Michael Boskin,
chairman of the White House Council of Economic Advisers.
   Boskin, who also spoke at the conference, was asked if the
changes in the East bloc will affect the U.S. economy.
   ``The United States has a $5 trillion economy with a very small
amount of trade with Eastern Europe,'' Boskin said. ``We believe we
will be able to help with restructuring their economies.''
   He said the outlook for the U.S. economy was strong, predicting
that interest rates would decrease, thereby helping the
agricultural sector.
   Questions also were raised about progress of international trade
talks, known as GATT. Yeutter said the United States had submitted
its final proposal and received positive reaction, except from the
European Community.
   However, he said that didn't bother him because he expected the
United States would reject the European proposals as well. He said
a negotiated agreement would be reached eventually.
   Yeutter and U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills emphasized
that the United States is not trying to remove all subsidies
internationally.
   ``The question is how those supports are designed,'' Yeutter
said. ``They ought to be designed to minimize distortions in
trade.''
   Hills said the United States was working to open roadblocks to
free trade worldwide. In response to a question, she criticized
Japan for its closed trade policies.
   ``No one has gained so much from an open market system as the
Japanese,'' Hills said.
   She praised Japan's expertise in exporting and investing, but
said other countries could begin to shut out Japan if it doesn't
increase its imports.
   As for the effect of GATT on the 1990 farm bill, Yeutter and two
members of Congress said legislation could be passed and then
revised to accommodate agreements stemming from the trade talks.
   Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., said that while Congress would not
be willing to change its subsidy policies without reciprocation, it
might pass legislation calling for adjustments ``if other countries
were to embrace the U.S. proposal'' at GATT.
   ``It remains to be seen what we are handed after the GATT
talks,'' said Rep. Tim Johnson, D-S.D.
   Yeutter said he didn't think Congress' debate on the 1990 farm
bill would effect the GATT talks.
   ``I see it working out just fine as long as Ambassador Hills can
convince our trading partners we can take back the agreement and
get it approved (by Congress),'' Yeutter said.
   Meanwhile, a paper presented at the conference predicted next
year's food prices would rise at a slower pace as farmers continue
expanding crop production.
   James R. Donald, chairman of the Agriculture Department's World
Agricultural Board, said record meat production, bigger crops and
slowing inflation will hold the retail food prices increase to 3
percent to 5 percent.
   Food prices this year are rising nearly 6 percent, the sharpest
annual increase since 1981. Part of the reason for this year's
runup _ prices gained 4.1 percent on the average in 1988 _ were the
lingering effects of last year's drought.
   ``World crop production is recovering from last year's reduced
level,'' he said. ``But for most crops, production (in 1989) will
not match continued high levels of use.''
   Next year, Donald said, world commodity consumption will reach a
record level ``in response to larger output, continued economic
expansion and population growth.''
</TEXT>
