<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings     11-29 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Study Says Base Closings Won't Save As Much As Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government won't realize as much as
originally estimated in annual savings from closing or realigning
15 U.S. military bases, a lawmaker says.
   Rep. James Saxton, R-N.J., said Tuesday that a study by the
General Accounting Office found that the shutdown or scaling back
of 15 bases will result in $453 million in savings instead of the
$622 million per year estimated by a federal commission.
   Among the bases are Fort Dix in New Jersey, Chanute Air Force
Base in Illinois and the Presidio in California.
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, was scheduled to
release the report today.
   ``The incredible fact of the matter is that we are even farther
away from realizing the $2 billion to $5 billion a year that
Congress was looking for when it started this base closing
process,'' Saxton said in a statement.
   Overall, the congressionally established Commission on Base
Realignment and Closure recommended in January closing 86 military
bases and scaling back five more, a proposal accepted by
then-Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   Congress overwhelmingly backed the plan but a handful of
lawmakers complained that the commission had used faulty data in
the cases of some of the bases. The closings and realignments are
to be completed by Sept. 30, 1995.
   Members of Congress asked the GAO this summer to determine the
cost and long-term savings of closing or realigning 15 of the bases
and moving military personnel. Congressional efforts to stop the
closings if the GAO found that the savings will not exceed the
shutdown costs failed.
   Saxton, whose district includes Fort Dix, said the GAO
determined that the elimination of basic and advanced training at
the base will result in only half of the $84.5 million savings
estimated by the commission.
   He also said that the GAO found that the changes at the base
would eliminate only 54 percent of the 2,167 jobs projected by the
commission. Fort Dix will lose 613 military personnel, not the
1,306 originally estimated, and 554 civilian jobs, instead of the
861 anticipated by the commission, Saxton quoted the GAO as saying.
   ``To the GAO's credit, it has been able to account for some
savings of taxpayers' dollars from the realignment of Fort Dix,''
Saxton said, noting, however, that the GAO study underscored his
contention that earlier estimates were flawed.
   ``The GAO's work indicates that inaccurate data was used and
that personnel cuts and savings were grossly exaggerated,'' he said.
   Pentagon spokesman Glenn Flood said Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney ``stands by the work that was done'' by the commission.
   ``The GAO had pretty much already hinted that their report would
say something like that,'' Flood said. ``There was more than one
criterion that the commission looked at, not just the payback in
savings. We looked at many different things.''
   The 15 bases are the Presidio, George Air Force Base, Mather Air
Force Base, Norton Air Force Base and Hunters Point Naval Station,
all in California; Pease Air Force Base in New Hampshire; Fort
Sheridan and Chanute Air Force Base in Illinois; Jefferson Proving
Ground in Indiana; Fort Dix in New Jersey; Lexington Army Depot in
Kentucky; Fort Meade and Fort Holabird in Maryland; Fort Devens in
Massachusetts; and Fort Huachuca in Arizona.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CivilRights     11-29 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing Looks at Civil Rights Enforcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government civil rights officials say they
will respond by mid-December to complaints that the Bush
administration is not committed to ensuring equal education
opportunities.
   ``I come here proud of this record,'' William Smith, temporary
head of the Education Department's civil rights efforts, told the
House Education and Labor Committee on Tuesday.
   ``I believe that (the Office of Civil Rights) has done a good
job of enforcing these civil rights statutes and ensuring an equal
educational opportunity for all Americans.''
   But Smith conceded that he had failed to respond to committee
queries, some dating to late October. He promised written responses
by Dec. 16.
   ``After almost one year in office, there seem to have been no
substantive efforts to improve the Office of Civil Right's dismal
enforcement record, and there has not even been a nomination for
permanent assistant secretaries of civil rights enforcement in
either the Department of Education or the Department of Justice,''
said Rep. Major R. Owens, D-N.Y.
   Members of the committee cited a year-old staff report that
found ``an apparently deliberate and very effective system'' by
which civil rights laws were not enforced.
   Although the reporting period was during the Reagan
administration, panel members insisted the Bush administration had
done little to correct the situation.
   ``Apparently ensuring equal education opportunity for all
American children is not very high on our education president's
list of priorities,'' Owens said.
   ``Many black people and organizations have given up on OCR,''
said Phyllis McClure of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational
Fund Inc.
   ``I have personally encountered individuals who believe that it
would be pointless to file a ... complaint against their school
system because OCR would not do anything to correct the violations
or because doing so would subject black school officials to
retaliation,'' she said.
   According to the report issued last December by the committee's
Democratic staff, 58 percent of investigations closed between
fiscal years 1983 and 1988 were concluded with a finding of ``no
violation.''
   Between 1981-1988, the civil rights office initiated 9,768
complaint investigations, the majority of which related to handicap
discrimination.
   Only 15 percent of the complaints involved allegations of race
discrimination, 17 percent related to gender discrimination and 3
percent to national origin discrimination.
   The report also pointed to major cuts in budget and staff for
civil rights activities, and to ``confused policy directives,
administration mismanagement, numerous changes in leadership and
severe reductions in resources.''
   ``In recent years, we have been in the vanguard in our efforts
to eliminate dual systems of higher education,'' said James P.
Turner, temporary head of the civil rights division at the Justice
Department.
   Committee members were not impressed.
   Rep. Charles Hayes, D-Ill., said that all three major higher
education cases handled by the departments are still pending.
   ``One of the best defenses that this nation can ever have is not
found in whether or not we can explore the outer space or build a
new bomber but in whether or not we can educate our young
irrespective of their race, creed, color or sex or financial
status,'' Hayes said.
   Committee Chairman Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., said he was
disappointed in the agencies.
   ``You seem to be proud of your record,'' he said. ``I haven't
read any report that commends you or says that you're doing a good
job. You seem to be operating on the theory that you can do more
with less, which is a lot of baloney. You know that. It's nothing
but double talk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
