<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Proposal     11-29 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Proposal,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl's 10-Point Proposal for Federation With East Germany</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Germany-Reunification</UNK>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's 10-point
proposal for forming a federation with East Germany, as summarized
from his German-language speech translated by The Associated Press:
   1. West Germany offers immediate aid in humanitarian areas,
including medical assistance. Additionally, West Germany offers to
contribute to a special fund to finance foreign travel for East
Germans, provided the East German government also contributes
substantially. East Germany also must drop its requirement that
West German tourists exchange at least 25 marks ($13.50) in hard
currency per day while visiting East Germany.
   2. Existing areas of cooperation of mutual benefit should be
expanded, particularly in economics, technology, culture and
environmental protection. East Germany's telephone network should
be upgraded. Talks on expanded rail ties and connection of the East
German system to other European states should be opened.
   3. Joint-venture projects should be legalized and encouraged.
Electoral reforms should be implemented to allow free elections and
secret ballots. The Communist Party must give up its guaranteed
power monopoly. Bureaucratic planning and administrative practices
must be phased out. Private businesses should be established and
Western investments solicited.
   4. Joint institutions and committees in economics, transport,
ecology, science and technology, health and culture shouldbe
established.
   5. West Germany is willing to develop, step by step, the
structures of a federation with a legitimate, democratically
elected East German government. Envisioned is establishment of
joint government committees for continuous consultations and
political decision-making, joint special committees and joint
parliament commissions.
   6. The future design of Germany must fit in with the future
design of a whole Europe, with full respect for the integrity and
security of each state, full respect for human rights, including
the right of self-determination.
   7. West Germany recommends a speedy decision on a trade and
cooperation agreement with East Germany that expands and ensures
East German access to the European Common Market.
   8. The confidence-building process in Europe is the heart of the
design of a whole Europe, and must be energetically pursued.
   9. Overcoming the division of Europe and the division of Germany
requires wide-ranging energetic steps in disarmament and arms
control, which must keep pace with political advances. This applies
particularly to the Vienna negotiations on conventional arms in
Europe, agreement on confidence building measures, and a ban on
chemical weapons. It also requires reducing the nuclear potential
of the superpowers to strategic minimums.
   10. The political approach aims to foster peace in Europe in
which the German people can achieve unity through
self-determination.German unity remains a goal of the federal
government. Only in a climate of mutual trust can the division of
Europe and Germany be overcome.
</TEXT>
