<FIRST>r w PM-AFL-CIO-Soviet     11-29 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO-Soviet,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor's Hopes of Sending Delegation to Soviet Union This Week Dashed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO says its hopes of sending a
delegation to meet with striking Soviet miners this week were
dashed when Soviet officials refused to issue visas.
   Federation officials said Tuesday that the Soviets told them it
wasn't an appropriate time for an American delegation to visit the
striking miners in the Arctic Circle city of Vorkuta.
   ``We are hopeful that it will be put together for another day,
another time,'' said AFL-CIO spokesman Rex Hardesty. ``We are
continuing to talk with the Soviets, but we have abandoned the
timetable.''
   The AFL-CIO requested visas for the five-member delegation after
receiving a telegram from the striking Soviet miners two weeks ago.
The miners praised the federation's efforts to help Poland's
Solidarity and requested help in forming a free trade union.
   ``They (Soviet officials) gave us the standard response, that
this would not be a good time, that this would not be a beneficial
time given the sensitive situation,'' said Eric Chenoweth of the
AFL-CIO's international affairs department, one of those who
requested a visa.
   ``Our intent was not to exacerbate the situation but to respond
to the requests of the workers who invited us to investigate the
conditions that brought them to strike,'' he said. ``It is our
position that just because there are sensitive conditions doesn't
mean that a delegation should not be allowed.''
   Calls to the Soviet Embassy for comment were not immediately
returned.
   The telegram from the miners requested that the AFL-CIO provide
information on U.S. labor laws and union organizing and said the
workers were struggling not only for their rights but to end the
Communist Party's leading role in Soviet governance.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland's request for the visas also
asked that the delegation be allowed to travel to Moscow and
Vorkuta and to meet privately with the miners. He asked for a
response in time for the trip to begin by the end of this week.
   The delegation was to be led by Albert Shanker, president of the
American Federation of Teachers. It was to include John T. Joyce,
president of the Bricklayers union; John Banovic, secretary
treasurer of the United Mine Workers; Ken Young, a top aide to
Kirkland; and Chenoweth.
   Official Soviet media have described the miners and other
strikers as threats to President Mikhail Gorbachev's economic
reforms. Gorbachev last month proposed a law banning strikes in
some vital industries, including coal mining.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
