<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CoalStrike     11-29 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: Pittston Violated Laws in Voting Against Union Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says the Pittston Co. violated
securities regulations by voting proxies against three proposals
submitted by striking miners at its annual meeting.
   ``Pittston did not have discretionary authority to vote
management's proxies against the union's proposals,'' U.S. District
Judge Norma Holloway Johnson said Tuesday.
   The judge upheld the United Mine Workers challenge on grounds
the union proposals weren't mentioned on the cards shareholders
signed to give management proxy power.
   Johnson rejected Pittston's arguments that it had
``discretionary authority'' to vote the proxies against the union
proposals in May because it had indicated in other material sent to
shareholders that it intended to oppose them.
   ``Nowhere in these letters did Pittston actually disclose what
the three proposals were,'' Johnson said.
   The judge said Pittston's argument ignored regulations promoting
``an informed shareholder electorate'' and, if accepted, could lead
to ``a world where shareholders could be misled and where corporate
suffrage could be circumvented by way of overbroad claims of
discretionary authority.''
   UMW President Richard Trumka called the decision ``a resounding
blow for shareholder rights at every American corporation.''
   Attempts to reach Pittston officials late Tuesday afternoon were
unsuccessful. Calls to the company's Connecticut headquarters were
unanswered.
   Pittston, whose Pittston Coal Group subsidiary is locked in a
bitter labor dispute with about 1,700 miners in Virginia, West
Virginia and Kentucky, used its proxies to defeat union proposals
to submit a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover plan to shareholders, to
allow shareholders to vote by secret ballot and to form a committee
to study possible divestiture of some assets.
   Had Pittston not usedthe 15.5 million management proxies it
held, union officials say the first two proposals would have been
approved.
   Johnson said reaching a remedy would prove to be a ``difficult
task'' because shareholders have changed since the vote six months
ago, and ordered company and union attorneys to suggest possible
remedies within two weeks.
   The miners struck Pittston Coal Group in April, largely in a
dispute over Pittston's intention to withdraw from an industrywide
contract to provide medical and retirement benefits to UMW retirees.
   The union has been fined more than $30 million for violating
picketing laws during the sometimes violent strike, and Pittston's
coal production is off significantly despite its use of replacement
workers and some miners who refused to honor pickets.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole last month appointed former Labor
Secretary W.J. Usery Jr. to mediate. Usery has met repeatedly with
both sides and talks are scheduled to resume this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
