<DOCNO> AP891129-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Flight103     11-29 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Moves to Quash Pan Am Subpoenas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is moving to quash
subpoenas issued by Pan American airlines for documents in
government files about the investigation of the explosion of Flight
103.
   The airline wants the information to defend itself against
lawsuits filed by relatives of those killed in the Dec. 21 bombing
over Lockerbie, Scotland, that left 270 people dead.
   In a brief statement Tuesday night, the Justice Department said
it moved in a sealed court request last week to quash the subpoenas
served on six government agencies, including the FBI and CIA.
   While federal judges in Brooklyn, N.Y., and Washington declined
to grant the government's request, Pan Am was directed to narrow
its request for information.
   The department said Pan Am lawyers were told to submit a draft
court order seeking information about how the suitcase with the
bomb made its way aboard the flight.
   The department reserves the right to challenge the request for a
court order, said agency spokesman David Runkel.
   Runkel said the department moved to quash the subpoenas on the
grounds that information in government files was part of an active
criminal investigation and thus did not have to be produced.
   Meanwhile, a government source says that clothing fragments from
the suitcase containing the bomb that destroyed the flight have
been traced to a store in Malta.
   The fragments found at the crash site were linked to a suitcase
that held the radio cassette player believed to have contained the
explosive device, the source said Tuesday, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   A multinational team of investigators have traced the clothing
fragments to a store in Malta, lending credence to information that
the bomb passed through that Mediterranean island, the source said.
   British newspapers had previously reported the Malta clothing
link.
   The investigation is trying to identify the person who placed
the suitcase on the flight from Malta to Frankfurt, West Germany,
where it was transferred to the Pan Am jetliner.
   The Pan Am plane flew to London, where it became Flight 103. It
exploded en route to New York City.
   An insurance investigator hired by the airline said the U.S.
government learned a bomb had been placed aboard the flight but did
not tell Pan Am. A CIA spokesman has denounced the investigator's
report as outrageous.
   Investigators are focusing on a possibility the terrorist group,
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, is responsible for
the bombing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
