<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed for the
first time above 37,000 points Wednesday, while the dollar closed
lower against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar finished trading at 143.53 yen, down 0.12 yen from
Tuesday's close of 143.65 yen. The currency opened lower at 143.27
yen and rose toward the end of trading while ranging between 143.27
yen and 143.58 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 36.16 points, or 0.10
percent, closing at 37,021.46, yet another high. The index had set
its previous record only the day before when it gained 103.77
points.
   The index rose from 36,000 to 37,000 points in only five trading
days.
   ``The Nikkei's performance is stronger than we expected,'' said
Masahiro Umemori, an analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``There were no specific economic factors making the market so
strong, except for its strength itself, which seemed to be
reassuring and encouraging investors' buying incentives,'' he said.
   Participants also were eager to buy issues to increase year-end
profits, Umemori said. December transactions started Tuesday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar was gradually rising from its
lower start as investors bought it back to take profits on short,
or oversold, positions following its overnight declines overseas,
traders said.
   The dollar tumbled against most major currencies Tuesday when
the West German mark surged on enthusiasm over the prospects for a
united Germany.
   Yen-dollar trading was less active than that between the dollar
and European currencies, especially the mark, said a dealer with
the Bank of Tokyo who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The mark has been strong against the dollar and other currencies
since East Germany symbolically opened the Berlin Wall Nov. 9.
Market participants believe that West Germany will be one of the
principal beneficiaries of recent democratic and economic reforms
in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
