<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     11-29 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA OKs Fast-Acting Clot-Dissolving Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new drug that quickly dissolves blood clots
to prevent permanent damage after a heart attack has been approved
by the Food and Drug Administration.
   Anistreplase, the third clot-dissolving drug to be approved, can
be administered in five minutes or less while the other two drugs
must be administered continuously for one to three hours, said
SmithKline Beecham, which will market the drug as Eminase.
   Clot-dissolving drugs can open blocked arteries and limit damage
from heart attacks, but are used in only about 20 percent of the
estimated 400,000 to 600,000 patients who could benefit from
treatment each year, the Department of Health and Human Services
said Tuesday.
   More than 300,000 of the 1.5 million people who suffer heart
attacks each year die before getting to the hospital and an
additional 300,000 get there too late for treatment with
clot-dissolving drugs, the department said in announcing the FDA
action.
   A blood clot blocking one of the arteries to the heart is the
most common cause of heart attacks. The clot prevents blood from
carrying oxygen to the heart muscle, which can lead to heart
failure and death.
   The other two approved clot-dissolving drugs are alteplase, or
TPA, and streptokinase.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Judge Denies Hinckley Request for News Interviews</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential assailant John Hinckley won't be
allowed to be interviewed by news organizations, a judge ruled,
saying Hinckley's mental illness could worsen with public exposure.
   U.S. District Court Judge June Green on Tuesday rejected
Hinckley's request for up to two interviews per month with the news
media.
   A directive at St. Elizabeths Hospital in Washington prohibiting
personal interviews between maximum-security patients and the news
media ``embodies a reasonable and constitutionally valid'' approach
with regard to Hinckley, Green said.
   The directive, the judge noted, permits patients to correspond
with reporters by mail. Hinckley has done so in the past.
   Hinckley, found not guilty by reason of insanity in the March
1981 assassination attempt on President Reagan, has been a patient
at St. Elizabeths since August 1982. Three months ago, he filed a
motion saying his First Amendment right of free speech was being
violated.
   Hinckley's attorney, Mark Lane, said he would consult with his
client before deciding whether to appeal.
   White House press secretary James Brady was left partially
paralyzed in the 1981 shootings, in which a Secret Service agent
and Washington police officer were wounded as well as the president.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FBI to Begin Random Drug Testing of Employees Soon</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William S. Sessions says random
testing for possible use of illegal drugs by employees may begin
early next year.
   Sessions told the bureau's 9,700 agents and nearly 13,000
support personnel of the random testing program in a notice dated
Nov. 14, FBI spokesman Mike Kortan said Tuesday.
   The random testing is expected to begin after Jan. 14, Kortan
said.
   A computer program will be used to randomly select the names of
employees who will be required to undergo urine testing to
determine if they have used illegal drugs, Kortan said.
   Employees who test positive could be suspended or dismissed, but
``each case would be evaluated individually,'' Kortan said.
   Refusal to provide a urine sample would also result in
disciplinary action that could include dismissal, he said.
   The random testing is being started under a 1986 executive order
by President Reagan. A number of federal agencies have instituted
similar programs, which have met with mixed reviews in court
decisions resulting from lawsuits filed by affected employees.
</TEXT>
