<FIRST>u i PM-India 1stLd-Writethru a0462 11-29 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Resigns After Election Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPGRADE attribution. Picks up 6th pvs,
`Congress Party ...' ADDS 5 grafs with Gandhi re-elected to Parliament.
^By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rajiv Gandhi resigned as prime minister
today, having failed to lead his Congress Party to decisive victory
in elections for a new Parliament.
   President Ramaswamy Venkataraman accepted the resignation but
asked Gandhi and his Cabinet to remain in office until a new
government is appointed, the presidential palace announced.
   Gandhi's resignation had been expected and is a formality that
clears the way for the opposition National Front alliance to try to
form the next government _ provided Venkataraman asks it to do so.
   The president normally would ask the party that won the most
seats to attempt to form a government, but the constitution does
not specifically require this.
   Gandhi, who has served in Parliament since 1980 and became prime
minister in 1984, spent a half-hour with Venkataraman and drove
away from the palace behind the wheel of a silver gray Mercedes
Benz. He did not stop to speak to reporters.
   Congress Party leaders said Tuesday they were ready to enter
into the secondary role of an opposition party for only the second
time in India's 42 years of independence.
   Lawmakers from the National Front scheduled a meeting later
today to choose the man they claim will be the next prime minister
of the world's most populous democracy.
   The leading candidate was former Gandhi ally Vishwanath Pratap
Singh, although he has said repeatedly he does not want to become
prime minister.
   Other possible contenders included Chandra Shekhar, one of the
architects of the movement that ousted Gandhi's mother and
predecessor, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, from power in 1977.
   Mrs. Gandhi's defeat in elections that year relegated the
Congress Party to the role of opposition for 29 months until its
election comeback in 1980.
   National Front leaders said they planned to call on Venkataraman
later in the day and tell him they were ready to form a government.
   Under the Indian Constitution, it is up to the president to
decide who should be asked to form a government. In the past, the
decision was clear-cut, because the Congress Party had always won a
comfortable majority except for 1977, when the Janata Party
defeated Mrs. Gandhi.
   The situation this time was more confused.
   While the Congress Party and its small party allies had the most
seats, their combined total was far short of the 263 required for a
majority.
   The National Front lagged even farther behind, but it enlisted
the post-election tacit support of other opposition groups and
buoyed its hopes of forming a government.
   With 486 of the 525 parliamentary seats decided, the Congress
Party had 186 and its allies 17 for a total of 203.
   The National Front has 122, and its allies had 132 for a total
of 254.
   The rest went to small parties and independents.
   Gandhi was swept into power in December 1984 on a wave of
sympathy following the assassination of his mother two months
earlier.
   But support for him declined in the face of allegations of
government corruption. Gandhi has denied any wrongdoing.
   While Gandhi was closeted with the president today, election
officials announced that he had been elected to Parliament from his
Amethi constituency for the third consecutive time.
   He defeated his nearest rival, Raj Mohan Gandhi, grandson of
Indian independence leader Mohandas K. (Mahatma) Gandhi by 197,000
votes, United News of India said.
   The news agency did not give the vote totals, delayed by a
partial re-vote Monday after authorities evidence of voter fraud in
the initial Nov. 22 voting. Raj Mohan Gandhi, who is not related to
Rajiv Gandhi, had charged Congress Party activists with stuffing
ballot boxes and resorting to violence.
   Gandhi, who has served in Parliament since 1980 and became prime
minister in 1984, spent a half-hour with Venkataraman and drove
away from the palace behind the wheel of a silver gray Mercedes
Benz. He did not stop to speak to reporters.
</TEXT>
