<HEAD>Today's Developments in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest developments in Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership promises to give up the Communist Party's claim
to total power and bring non-Communists into the government this
week. Party chief Karel Urbanek, however, says the Communists must
remain a presence in the workplace, and he rejects demands the
party dissolve its paramilitary police force.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Egon Krenz rejects West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's call for an eventually united Germany. However, he
does not rule out the concept of a confederation, or partnership,
between the two Germanys. Krenz says talk of such an arrangement
``requires more time.''
</TEXT>
