<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Rights     11-29 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Rights,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Fights Terror With Brutality, Amnesty Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peruvians are caught in savage crossfire between
leftist rebels and government troops who have become equally
ruthless, killing hundreds of people as they try to end the
insurgency, Amnesty International said today.
   The international human rights group said in a report that the
Peruvian government's attempt to defeat the Shining Path rebel
movement has raised the level of ruthless and indiscrimate violence.
   ``Torture, mutilation, `disappearance,' murder and rape have
become a hallmark of the armed forces' `campaign against
terrorism','' the international organization said in the report on
human rights in Peru.
   It said the armed forces have singled out young people as
suspected supporters of the Shining Path.
   ``The killing, torture and `disappearance' of hundreds of
children and young people has been one cost of a strategy of
`terror to fight terror' adopted by the armed forces in Peru,'' it
said.
   The government must uphold the law and not resort to the terror
tactics of its enemies, Amnesty said. It called on the government
to investigate all alleged abuses and bring those responsible to
justice.
   But Amnesty also stressed the extensive and continuing
massacres, mutilations and torture by opposition forces such as the
Shining Path.
   As a result, it said, peasants in areas where the government has
declared a state of emergency have been ``caught between two
fires,'' victims of massive abuse by both government forces and
armed opposition.
   ``Many people have relatives who have been killed in cold blood
by both anti-government guerrillas and government forces,'' the
group said.
   More than 3,000 detainees have disappeared in the past seven
years and at least 3,000 more are estimated to have been killed by
security forces, individually or in mass executions, the report
said.
   It said targets for human rights abuses by government forces are
being drawn from increasingly broad sectors of society.
   Local government officers, community leaders, trade unionists,
journalists, lawyers, academics and people considered critics or
opponents of the government have been threatened, killed or had
their homes and offices bombed, Amnesty said. Many killings were
carried out after the victims had been detained and tortured, it
said.
   The report focuses on violations in the emergency zones, where
more than half of Peru's 21 million people live under
political-military command.
   In these zones, many killings appear to have been carried out to
punish communities for rebel activities in their areas, it said.
   Amnesty said few males between 14 and 40 remain in these zones
and women have been subjected to increasing abuse by government
forces.
   Rape by troops is widespread, and women of all ages are at risk,
Amnesty said, adding that it knows of no convictions for this crime
in the emergency zones.
   The report said it is common for women to be raped after
soldiers have entered villages and taken the men away. Other women
have been raped while in detention, it said.
   It cited the case of Maria Guinarita Pisco Pisango, 26, a farmer
from San Martin de Alao in Lamas province, who was raped, tortured
and killed by soldiers after she reported her husband's
disappearance in January 1988.
   Children appear to be most at risk during raids by government
troops, Amnesty said.
   ``Children and young people are under threat for their real or
supposed sympathies in the emergency zones. The place they live in,
the school they attend or the books they read may result in their
secret detention, torture or murder,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
