<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Rights     11-29 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Rights,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Invites UN Human Rights Inspector To Visit Its Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has ended its rejection of outside
investigations of its human rights practices and invited a U.N.
official to visit its prisons, according to Western diplomats.
   They said Iran reversed its policy as a political deal with a
U.N. subcommittee, which on Tuesday adopted by consensus a
resolution that did not criticize Iran's human rights situation.
   Iran has barred U.N. investigators since the U.N. Commission on
Human Rights expressed concern in 1984 over reports of torture,
summary executions and political and religious persecution in the
country.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition they not be identified,
said Ambassador Kamal Kharrazi of Iran has invited the commission's
representative, Reynaldo Galindo Pohl, to Iran.
   Galindo Pohl is expected to visit the country before February,
when the U.N. commission is to meet in Geneva to consider his final
report.
   The diplomats said that in letters of understanding exchanged
between Galindo Pohl and Kharrazi, Iran said the U.N. inspector
will be able to bring his own translators and travel freely.
   Kharrazi's letter invited Galindo Pohl to Iran so he could
prepare his report ``based on realities rather than allegations.''
   In an interim report released two weeks ago, based on interviews
with Iranian exiles and reports in the Iranian media, Galindo Pohl
said torture, political executions and other human rights abuses
were continuing in Iran.
   It said punishments include flogging, whipping the soles of feet
with cables or barbed wire, sexual abuse, mock executions, burning
with cigarettes or hot metal rods and confinement of prisoners in
``small closed rooms with high temperatures and insufficient
oxygen.''
   Galindo Pohl also wrote, ``The Iranian press has reported few
political executions so far in 1989. However, many allegations have
been received that the large number of executions for drug
trafficking masks political executions.''
</TEXT>
