<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-29 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Record High, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index, setting a
record high for the sixth consecutive trading day, closed above
37,000 for the first time today, while the dollar eased down
against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 36.16 points, or 0.10
percent, closing at 37,021.46.
   It took the Nikkei index just five trading days to rise from
36,000 to 37,000 points. The index closed above 36,000 for the
first time on Nov. 21, when it ended at 36,059.87.
   Wednesday's session was marked by wide fluctuations as
institutional investors traded large amounts of shares, said
Kazuyuki Suzuki, a Daiwa Securities dealer.
   The index fell by 49 points at mid-afternoon, he said, then
recovered as investors picked up issues that had fallen earlier.
   Suzuki said the overall rising trend was slowing as market
players became wary over the recent speed of the index's increase.
   Trading was hectic, with some 1.7 billion shares changing hands
on the first section, up from 1.5 billion Tuesday. Among gainers
were steel, shipbuilding and pharmaceutical issues.
   In currency dealing, the dollar closed at 143.53 yen, down 0.12
yen from Tuesday's close of 143.65 yen. It opened at 143.27 yen and
ranged between 143.27 yen and 143.58 yen.
   Following a downswing on overseas markets overnight, the dollar
gradually strengthened as it was bought back for profit-taking,
said Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan
Securities, Co.
   Japanese investors sold West German marks and Swiss Francs and
bought back the U.S. currency to take profits on short, or
oversold, positions following overnight declines overseas, he said.
   The mark has been a focus of recent trading. Market players
believe West Germany will be a major beneficiary of recent
democratic and economic reforms in the East bloc.
   The West German mark has been strong against the dollar and
other currencies since Nov, 9, when East Germany began allowing its
citizens to travel freely to the West.
   In contrast, the dollar-yen rate has been ``stuck between 142
yen and 144 yen'' without fresh market-affecting news, Kanai said.
   Fluctuations will remain small while the market awaits the
release of a series of economic data later this week and the
results of U.S.-Soviet summit talks starting Saturday, he said.
   Among economic figures to be announced later this week are U.S.
individual income and consumption for October and the Japanese
consumer price index for October.
</TEXT>
