<FIRST>r a PM-CraneCollapse-Cabbie     11-29 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crane Collapse-Cabbie,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crane Crushes Cab But Driver Fine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crane Collapse, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerry Smith heard rumbling and threw
himself down onto the floor of his taxi just before the cab was
crushed. Then he kicked out a window and walked away.
   ``I thought it was another earthquake. It didn't enter my mind
that a crane fell on me,'' Smith said of Tuesday's collapse of a
construction crane that killed five people in downtown San
Francisco.
   His two passengers, Richard and Andrea Bronson, were among those
injured. Mrs. Bronson, 41, was listed in serious condition with a
spinal injury, San Francisco General Hospital said. Bronson, 43,
was treated and released.
   Smith, 55, said no one at the scene could believe anyone in the
cab had survived.
   ``I said, `Hey, I'm the guy who was driving that cab.' The cops
seemed fascinated. They called me Mr. Lucky. Some woman called me
Mr. Miracle,'' Smith said.
   He called the Luxor Cab office a few hours after the accident.
   ``The operator answering the phone said, `My God! You're alive.
Now I won't have to spend $25 for flowers,''' Smith said. ``What
can you do? If a crane falls on you, it falls on you. I guess it
just wasn't my time.''
</TEXT>
