<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Conspiracy     11-29 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Conspiracy,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Election Winner to Be Freed in Indira Gandhi Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-India ^By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi has dropped
charges against a newly elected Parliament member who is accused of
masterminding the 1984 assassination of Gandhi's mother, officials
said today.
   Simranjit Singh Mann, a member of the Sikh religious sect and a
former police officer, was elected to the lower house of Parliament
from the northern state of Punjab by an overwhelming majority this
week.
   The order to drop charges against Mann was one of the last acts
as prime minister by Gandhi, the son and successor of Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi. A court must actually order Mann's release,
but that is considered a formality.
   Gandhi failed to lead his Congress Party to a decisive election
victory this week. He tendered his resignation today, but is to
remain in office until a new government is appointed.
   He asked Home Minister Buta Singh to ``take steps to withdraw
the case'' against Mann, a ministry spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said: ``The Home Ministry is examining the prime minister's
directions, but the release can only be ordered by the relevant
court.''
   The shots that killed Mrs. Gandhi on Oct. 31, 1984, were fired
by two of her Sikh bodyguards. One of them was shot to death on the
spot by other bodyguards.The surviving gunman and a Sikh government
clerk convicted in the plot were hanged in January.
   The government said the assassination was masterminded by Sikh
extremists fighting for a separate homeland in the Punjab. Mann,
who has been jailed for the past five years on sedition charges,
was charged with conspiracy when the assassination case was
re-opened in April.
   United News of India, in a dispatch today, quoted Gandhi as
saying: ``I will hold no ill-will or rancor. I have always striven
to heal wounds. At times I have succeeded. Sometimes I have been
disappointed.
   ``If there is any more step that can be taken to bring down the
curtain on the unfortunate past, and to ring in the future, that
step should be taken now. The conspiracy case ... will not heal
wounds,'' Gandhi was quoted as saying.
   United News of India and Press Trust of India said Gandhi
decided to seek Mann's release because Mann had sworn allegiance to
the constitution.
   Mann, 44, was elected from the Tarn Taran constituency in
Punjab, campaigning from a jail more than 850 miles away in Bihar
state.
   Mann, a senior officer in the prestigious Indian Police Service,
resigned soon after Mrs. Gandhi ordered an army attack on the
Golden Temple in Amritsar, Sikhdom's holiest shrine, to flush out
Sikh militants entrenched there.
   More than 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs, were killed in the 1984
army operation that precipitated the revenge slaying of Mrs. Gandhi.
   Another Sikh charged with conspiracy in the Gandhi murder,
Attinder Pal Singh, also was elected to Parliament while in jail.
There has been no word on whether he, too, may be freed.
   Bimal Khalsa, widow of Beant Singh, the assassin who was killed
on the spot, and his father, Sucha Singh, also were elected.
   All three belonged to Mann's Akali Dal party.
   More than 7,500 people have died in the 8-year campaign for the
homeland that Sikh extremists propose to carve out of Punjab, a
farming state bordering Pakistan.
   Sikhs, whose religion is rooted in both Islam and Hinduism,
comprise just 2 percent of India's 880 million people, but they
have a slight majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
