<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     11-29 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Reaches One Verdict in 2{-Year-Old Molestation Trial; 64 to
Go</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the 2{-year-old McMartin
preschool molestation trial returned its first sealed verdict after
more than three weeks of deliberations, but still has 64 counts to
decide.
   The jury also indicated Tuesday it was deadlocked on another
count.
   Concerned that the longest criminal trial in U.S. history could
end in a mistrial, the judge has taken the unusual step of having
jurors return verdicts under seal one at a time, instead of waiting
until decisions are made on all counts.
   There are no more alternate jurors, so if one panel member drops
out, a mistrial would have to be declared on any unresolved charges
against Raymond Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey,
63.
   ``Taking them one at a time is an insane process. But waiting
for all of them is just as insane because we may lose a key juror
before that time and thus lose all of those verdicts,'' Superior
Court Judge William Pounders said Tuesday.
   Pounders said he could find no precedent to support his plan,
but added that circumstances required it.
   He planned a meeting with attorneys Friday to decide when the
verdicts should be read, but said that if two or more decisions are
returned by then, an announcement could come as early as next week.
   The Buckeys are charged with conspiracy and child molestation at
their family-owned Manhattan Beach preschool. The trial has cost
Los Angeles County more than $15 million.
   Buckey's lawyer, Danny Davis, objected to the procedure Pounders
set down, saying jurors should have the chance to change their
minds about any count as their talks proceed.
   But the judge said, ``I'm not going to tell them they should
take sealed verdicts and redecide them.''
   Before returning the sealed verdict, the jurors indicated they
were deadlocked on one count.
   ``They've said only that they've taken several ballots and
cannot reach a verdict on a count,'' Pounders said. ``Given the
fact there are 65 counts, that is not too significant.''
   The judge said the jury's questions led him to believe the
deadlock involves a boy whose mother set off the McMartin
investigation six years ago with a complaint that her son had been
molested.
   The mother since has died and the boy did not testify. Jurors
had only medical evidence on which to consider the charges
involving him. The defense called that evidence inconclusive.
</TEXT>
