<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Winds Buffet Northeastern U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong northwesterly winds ushered arctic air into the Northeast
today and a fast-traveling storm barreled from Canada into the
northern Great Lakes region.
   Wind chill readings in Minnesota dipped to 25 degrees below zero
overnight. Temperatures were in the teens and single digits from
the central Dakotas through Minnesota and Iowa to Upper Michigan.
   Winds gusted to 60 mph at Montpelier, Vt., late Tuesday and
reached 66 mph at Saint Albans, Vt.
   High-wind warnings were posted today for the Saint Lawrence
Valley, the Adirondacks and the Champlain Valley of New York state.
A high-wind warning was also in effect for New Hampshire and
southern Maine.
   The strong northwest winds brought snow squalls to the lower
Great Lakes region. Northeastern Ohio braced for 3 to 6 inches of
new snow.
   Lake snow advisories were posted for parts of western New York
state, where 2 to 4 inches of snow were predicted.
   Showers and thunderstorms were developing ahead of the cold
front in Georgia, southern Alabama and northern Florida.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation with fair
skies over much of the central and western United States.
   Dense fog developed in eastern North Carolina with visibility
reduced to just a few feet around Beaufort and Morehead City.
   Strong Santa Anas continued over parts of Southern California. A
high-wind warning remained in effect for Cajon Pass and for areas
below the pass. Wind advisories were in effect for the remaining
coastal and mountainous areas of Southern California.
   Temperatures stayed below freezing all day Tuesday from the
Dakotas through the upper half of the Mississippi Valley to the
upper Great Lakes with highs only in the single digits across much
of Minnesota and eastern North Dakota.
   Cool temperatures prevailed across the central and western
states Tuesday. Afternoon highs in the 60s and 70s were confined to
southern Texas and Southern California with highs in the 60s in
southern Arizona.
   Temperatures warmed into the 60s and lower 70s in the middle
Atlantic Coast region and rose above 70 degrees from Florida to
South Carolina with afternoon highs in the 80s across Florida.
   The afternoon high of 80 degrees at Charleston, S.C., matched
the city's record for the date set in 1985.
   The nation's high temperature Tuesday was 87 at Fort Myers Fla.
   Temperatures reports at 3 a.m. EST:
   _East: Atlanta 42 partly cloudy; Boston 36 fair; Charleston,
S.C. 61 rain; Chattanooga 43 cloudy; Cincinnati 30 cloudy;
Cleveland 27 snow; Detroit 23 snow; Hatteras 56 showery;
Jacksonville 66 foggy; Key West 77 rain; Knoxville 43 cloudy; Macon
45 fair; Miami 75 showery; New York 40 windy; Philadelphia 40
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 29 cloudy; Portland, Maine 30 fair;
Richmond 45 partly cloudy; Tampa 67 foggy; Washington, D.C. 44
cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 29 partly cloudy; Chicago 17 fair; Denver 24
fair; Des Moines 5 fair; Indianapolis 26 cloudy; Kansas City 14
fair; Little Rock 34 fair; Louisville 33 cloudy; Memphis 33 partly
cloudy; Nashville 34 cloudy; New Orleans 50 windy; North Platte 17
fair; Rapid City 24 fair; St. Louis 19 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 3
fair; Sault Ste. Marie 8 partly cloudy; San Antonio 46 cloudy.
   _West: Anchorage 22 cloudy; Boise 27 fair; Casper 25 partly
cloudy; Fairbanks 21 fair; Great Falls 35 windy; Honolulu 69 fair;
Las Vegas 43 fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Medford 27 fair; Pendleton
28 fair; Phoenix 56 windy; Portland, Ore. 34 cloudy; Reno 26 fair;
Salt Lake City 20 fair; San Diego 52 fair; San Francisco 46 fair;
Seattle 43 partly cloudy; Spokane 28 cloudy.
   _International: Montreal 9 fair; Ottawa 3 fair; Regina 34 windy;
Toronto 12 fair; Winnipeg 14 windy.
