<FIRST>r a PM-ShuttleCondition     11-29 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Condition,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Damage to Shuttle Seen After Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Discovery
sustained little damage to its heat shield tiles and had few other
problems during its five-day military mission, a NASA official said.
   ``The basic orbiter system itself looks like it's just maturing
as everybody promised it would and I think the hardware is starting
to prove itself,'' said Tip Talone, Discovery's overseer between
flights.
   Discovery was on schedule to begin a two-day flight back to
Kennedy Space Center atop a jumbo jet Saturday, Talone said Tuesday.
   Talone said he tried to avoid the cliche of reporting that
Discovery had come back as ``the best and cleanest one yet,'' but
``it really is.''
   Initial inspection indicated fewer than 10 thermal tiles would
need replacement because of damage.
   The tiles are typically damaged by debris hits during launch and
landing.
   Discovery landed Monday on a concrete runway rather than a clay
runway on Edwards' dry lakebed, which reduces the amount of debris
kicked up by the tires.
   Talone also said the brakes were in good condition and the right
side tires had more wear than the others but that was not
considered worrisome.
   The amount of damage to an orbiter determines how long it will
take to make it ready for its next flight and affects the schedule
for facilities shared by all the orbiters at Kennedy Space Center
in Florida.
   At Cape Canaveral, Fla., the space shuttle Columbia was
transported to a refurbished launch pad Tuesday for a Christmastime
mission to deploy one satellite and retrieve another the size of a
bus before it falls to Earth.
   Discovery's next mission is to carry the Hubble space telescope
into orbit in late March.
   ``The bottom line is we think that we've got a really good start
... to get the Hubble out,'' Talone said.
   Discovery's toilet broke and had to be fixed by the crew, but
few other problems showed up during the mission.
   ``The inflight anomaly list was extremely clean,'' Talone said.
   Its five astronauts reportedly achieved their main goal on
Thursday by releasing a $300 million spy satellite, but there was
no confirmation of the mission's purpose because of Defense
Department-mandated secrecy.
</TEXT>
