<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-29 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today
and currency dealers said there were no elements in sight to break
the downward slide.
   Gold prices rose.
   ``Even though the dollar is entering an oversold range, people
are still selling,'' said one trader in Milan, Italy.
   ``We have had a downward movement since last night, and the
trend is still lower,'' said a dealer at a bank in Dusseldorf, West
Germany.
   The West German mark continued to be bolstered by an
increasingly positive view of the accelerating pace of change in
Eastern Europe, which is likely to present huge business
opportunities for West German companies, he said.
   Rumors that the Deutsche Bundesbank might raise its key interest
rates again Thursday to starve off inflationary pressures
associated with the influx of East German refugees also helped, he
said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.12 yen to a closing 143.53 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.44 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.7780 West German marks, down from 1.7880
   _1.5885 Swiss francs, down from 1.5950
   _6.0725 French francs, down from 6.1035
   _2.0075 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0270
   _1,314.00 Italian lire, down from 1,319.50
   _1.1663 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1674
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5635 to buy one pound, slightly more expensive than $1.5625 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $412.10 a troy ounce, up
from $411.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $410.75.
   ``Gold has risen so far so fast that one has got to look for a
pullback,'' said one London bullion dealer, predicting gold would
drift back down to 405 dollars before attempting another climb.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $410.70, up from $410.50 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.16 to close at a bid $411.35.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.64 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
