<FIRST>r a PM-BlinkDeath     11-29 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blink Death,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted by Blink Testimony Gets 6 Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MARLENE AIG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baker has been sentenced to six
months in prison for the fatal shooting of his best friend, who
identified his killer by blinking his eyes.
   Frank Zollbrecht wept as he apologized for the death of his
friend, Frederick Sannicandro.
   ``I would never hurt Freddy,'' said Zollbrecht, 45. ``I'm sorry
for what happened. ... I'm sorry I touched the gun. I'm sorry.''
   Sannicandro, 38, died more than six hours after Zollbrecht shot
him in the abdomen on June 3, 1988, while both men were working in
a Yonkers bakery.
   As he was being wheeled into surgery, detectives and an
attending physician questioned Sannicandro and urged him to respond
to the questions with eye blinks. One blink meant ``yes''; two
blinks ``no.''
   According to trial testimony, Sannicandro blinked ``yes'' when
asked if Zollbrecht had shot him and blinked ``no'' when asked if
the shooting was accidental. He was unable to speak because he had
a breathing tube in his throat.
   ``God brought him back for a few moments to communicate with
detectives,'' Westchester County Court Judge John LaCava said.
   Zollbrecht also admitted when he placed the emergency call to
police that he had shot his friend, Assistant District Attorney
Michael Romano said.
   LaCava also sentenced Zollbrecht to five years' probation and
1,000 hours of community service and ordered him to get treatment
for alcoholism and psychological problems.
   According to testimony during the trial, Zollbrecht had a
history of alcohol abuse, and his boss had hidden the gun on the
night of the shooting.
   But Zollbrecht went and got the gun, and the shooting occurred
when both were drunk.
   The defense maintained that Sannicandro's deathbed testimony
never should have been allowed into evidence, since Sannicandro
also was drunk at the time of the shooting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
