<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather     11-29 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Season Tropical Depression Heads for Yucatan Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare, late-season tropical
depression headed for the Yucatan Channel between Mexico and Cuba
today, and forecasters said it could become this year's 11th named
storm.
   At 5 a.m. EST, the depression's poorly-defined center was near
20.4 north latitude, 85.7 west longitude, about 105 miles
south-southwest of Cape San Antonio in western Cuba.
   It was moving north at about 10 mph with highest sustained winds
estimated at 35 mph. It was expected to maintain that motion
through today, said National Hurricane Center forecaster Hal
Gerrish.
   He added that he didn't think the system would become a
hurricane because it is likely to run into a cold front moving down
the Florida peninsula. It appeared this morning that the clash
between the two would most affect the Florida Straits off the
peninsula's tip.
   ``There'll be rain and some wind,'' he said. ``It'll be
primarily a concern for our marine interests.''
   The depression formed Tuesday about 500 miles southwest of the
lower Florida Keys.
   If its winds reach 39 mph, it would become Tropical Storm Karen.
The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June 1 through Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
