<FIRST>r a PM-Poindexter-Letter     11-29 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poindexter-Letter,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poindexter Seeks Help to Pay Legal Fees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter, facing trial in the Iran-Contra case, has begun a
fund-raising drive to pay for his legal fees, according to a
published report today.
   Poindexter wrote a four-page letter saying liberal special
interests want him ``silenced ... bankrupt or imprisoned,'' The New
York Times reported.
   He said that after having put five sons through college on a
Navy salary, he cannot meet his expenses alone.
   ``There is only one reason why I am being put through this
ordeal: political revenge,'' wrote Poindexter, who describes
himself as ``one man, alone against the massive onslaught of
liberal special interests who want to imprison me for serving my
country.''
   He went on: ``The liberals in Congress wanted to destroy the
Reagan presidency any way they could. When they found that they
were going to be unsuccessful, they turned on me.''
   Poindexter faces five criminal charges in a trial scheduled to
begin Jan. 22. The charges include conspiring to obstruct
congressional inquiries in August 1986 about whether National
Security Council aide Oliver L. North was making false statements
to Congress and secretly helping to arm the Contras.
   Poindexter's lawyer, Richard W. Beckler, called the former
admiral's legal fees ``substantial'' but would not disclose how
much they were. Some of those involved in the fund-raising appeal
suggested the fees would be $3 million to $4 million, the Times
said.
   Poindexter was unavailable for comment, the newspaper said.
   Poindexter wrote he has ``always done what I thought was in the
best long-term interests of the country,'' but ``because I care
more about the long-term security of America than I do about
myself, I must now face the liberals' accusations surrounding the
`Iran-Contra affair.'''
   Retired Adm. Clarence A. Hill Jr., one of three retired admirals
who set up a defense fund for Poindexter, said they were concerned
his legal fees would be about the same as North's but he would not
attract as many contributors as the former Marine.
   The other two former admirals are James L. Holloway III and
Gerald E. Miller.
   The letter asks for contributions of $35, $50, $100 and $500.
   Hill would not say how much money the drive has raised.
</TEXT>
