<FIRST>r i PM-NATO 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0502,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Agrees to Refrain From Arms Cuts Until Accord Reached</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Cheney, other NATO comment;
picks up 6th pvs: But they ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the reforms sweeping the East
bloc, NATO defense ministers agreed today to refrain from
unilateral reductions in conventional arms until a formal agreement
with the Warsaw Pact can be reached.
   The ministers, ending two days of talks, said in a statement
that they welcomed the changes in the East but issued a word of
caution.
   ``There has unquestionably been a change in the nature of the
threat which confronts us, but not yet a significant change in the
military capability of the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact,'' NATO
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the United States will
not bring home any troops from Europe without first consulting NATO
allies.
   ``We will not act unilaterally,'' he said, referring to a
Pentagon study of troop cuts in the early 1990s that would exceed
those now being negotiated at East-West conventional arms talks in
Vienna.
   In their statement, the ministers noted the start of unilateral
reductions in conventional, or non-nuclear, arms by the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact.
   But they insisted, ``we cannot ignore the fact that, even after
completion of these reductions, the Warsaw Pact will retain
well-equipped forces which substantially outnumber those of the
West.''
   As a result, the statement said the ministers would take a
``pragmatic, step-by-step approach'' to changes in the East, where
Hungary, Poland, East Germany, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia have
embraced democratic reform to varying degrees.
   The ministers also renewed their ``determination not to make any
unilateral reductions that could risk undermining the prospect of
reaching a (conventional arms) accord.''
   The 16 nations of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and
seven Warsaw Pact members are currently negotiating cuts in
non-nuclear arms and troops in Vienna, Austria.
   In those talks, Washington wants the Soviet Union and the United
States cut their forces in Europe to 275,000 soldiers each. That
would mean a cutback of 300,000 Soviet and 30,000 American troops.
</TEXT>
