<FIRST>r w PM-NATO-WarPlans 1stLd-Writethru a0463 11-29 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO-War Plans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Would Be Warned Well in Advance Of Soviet Attack: Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with Cheney comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet-bloc forces would need so much
preparation to attack Western Europe that U.S. intelligence would
detect the activity months in advance, according to a report
published today.
   The ``intelligence community believes we would have some 33 to
44 days of warning time,'' and possibly six months, The Washington
Post said in today's editions, quoting a study prepared for Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney.
   NATO war plans had been based on the assumption that the West
would have only 10 to 14 days' warning, the newspaper said. A short
expected warning time led to decisions to invest large sums in
airlift capability and forward storage of ammunition and supplies.
   The study said that while it remained possible for the Soviets
to launch a quick attack that would allow the West less than two
weeks' warning, such a move would be ``quite risky'' for the
Soviets.
   The study also found that during the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion
of Czechoslovakia, Moscow was so worried about possible
intervention from the West that it put its battlefield nuclear
rockets on 10-minute alert, even though ``Moscow clearly wanted to
avoid a general war in Europe.''
   In Brussels, Belgium today, Cheney told reporters, ``I haven't
seen any such planning document. That doesn't necessarily mean
there isn't one. Occasionally, I receive documents after they
arrive at the New York Times, The Washington Post.''
   Cheney was attending a two-day meeting of defense ministers of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</TEXT>
