<FIRST>r a PM-Carvel     11-29 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carvel,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tom Carvel Sells His Ice Cream Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Carvel, the gravelly voiced pitchman for
Fudgie the Whale, Cookie Puss and other Carvel Corp. confections,
has sold his ice cream empire to an investment bank.
   Carvel, 83, who founded the Carvel Corp. in 1938, sold his 99
percent share to Investcorp for more than $80 million, the bank
announced Tuesday.
   Based on annual sales, Carvel, based in Yonkers, is the
third-largest ice cream store chain in the country after Dairy
Queen and Haagen-Dazs, said Robert Glaser, a member of Investcorp's
management committee.
   Carvel has more than 700 stores, most of them in New York,
Florida, Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Jersey and other East
Coast states.
   Carvel will stay on as a consultant but will no longer make the
commercials promoting Fudgie the Whale and Cookie Puss ice cream
cakes, Flying Saucers ice cream sandwiches and Thinny Thin dietary
frozen dessert, Investcorp said.
   With the purchase of Carvel, Investcorp also acquired control of
two other food businesses owned by Carvel: Nedick's hot dogs and
Dugan's bakery products.
   Investcorp said it hopes to expand Carvel's business by
increasing the number of franchises, modernizing its image and
introducing new products.
   ``Carvel has a good name and we want to build on that,'' Glaser
said.
   Thomas Shick, a spokesman for Carvel, referred all questions to
Investcorp.
   Investcorp has offices in Bahrain, New York and London. Its
other investments have included Tiffany &amp; Co., Gucci and yacht
manufacturers Bertram &amp; Trojan.
</TEXT>
