<FIRST>r a PM-BeijingCharges     11-29 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beijing Charges,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Found Guilty of Lying to Go to Near Tiananmen Square</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ A college student who smuggled
footage of the Tiananmen Square massacre out of China for NBC has
been been found guilty by a Wake Forest University honor court of
lying in order to go near the square.
   Timothy W. Bell, a business major, was convicted by the Honor
Council on Tuesday night and put on probation until the end of the
term.
   Bell, who had gone to China last spring as part of a group of 28
students, was also ordered to write letters of apology to each of
the other participants.
   Two professors who led the group said Bell lied in telling them
he would not go near the square when he left their hotel on the
outskirts of Beijing.
   Bell, 22, said he watched the struggle the night of June 3 from
a foreign correspondent's hotel room about three blocks from the
square. Before the students left Beijing, an NBC crew gave Bell
tapes to take to Hong Kong.
   The tapes were seen on a June 4 report on the massacre. NBC
officials told him 20 million to 30 million people saw that
broadcast, Bell said.
   Bell was supposed to graduate in August, but his graduation was
held up by the Honor Council investigation. He said he will appeal.
</TEXT>
