<DOCNO> AP891129-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Anti-AbortionVow     11-29 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-Abortion Vow,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Newspaper Requires Anti-Abortion Vow from Politicians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newspaper of the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Providence has told politicians that if they want to
advertise holiday greetings, they'll have to sign a declaration
supporting a constitutional amendment against abortion.
   So far, politicians are refusing to sign. A spokesman for one,
Warwick Mayor Francis X. Flaherty, a Democrat considering a run for
governor, said he was offended despite his anti-abortion stance.
   Rhode Island politicians traditionally buy Christmas greetings
ads in the Providence Visitor.
   The paper previously has barred campaign ads from pro-choice
politicians, but in a recent letter told officeholders and office
seekers that congratulatory ads and holiday greetings also would be
rejected unless the politicians signed the declaration.
   ``The Providence Visitor holds the view that abortion
constitutes the greatest single outrage being waged against
humanity in America today,'' the letter said.
   The policy was decided on at a meeting last month of the
Visitor's board of directors, said the Rev. John W. Hunt, the
newspaper's executive director.
   The publisher, Bishop Louis E. Gelineau, did not attend but
supports the decision, Hunt said.
   Gelineau recently chastised Rep. Claudine Schneider, R-R.I., for
her view that a woman's decision whether to have an abortion is her
own, although Schneider personally opposes abortion.
   Circulation figures were not immediately available for the
weekly paper, but it is an influental publication in a state where
the population is two-thirds Catholic.
   Hunt said the paper could lose as much as $5,000 in revenue a
year. He would not identify the politicians to whom the letters
were sent but said no forms had been returned. Dec. 15 is the
deadline for the Christmas ads.
   Among those who have refused to sign are Johnston Mayor Ralph
Russo and Cranston Mayor Michael A. Traficante, both of whom oppose
abortion.
   ``I don't think it's fair,'' said Russo. ``I'm an administrator.
I don't set laws.''
</TEXT>
