<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0511,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Support Forced Repatriation of Vietnamese Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Vietnam rejecting forced repatriation,
CLARIFY that measure is merely advisory. Pickup 5th graf, `The nearly...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature today passed a motion urging
the forced return of Vietnamese refugees, and several lawmakers
condemned U.S. opposition to the idea.
   The Legislative Council vote reflected the strong local
sentiment to rid this British colony of the nearly 57,000
Vietnamese languishing in squalid detention centers after fleeing
their Communist homeland by boat.
   ``Mandatory repatriation is a must, and it should have been
implemented yesterday,'' lawmaker Rita Fan said during the debate.
   The measure was merely a resolution urging that Great Britain
secure an agreement for repatriation with Vietnam. Britain is
responsible for the negotiations.
   Vietnam's official news agency said today that Vietnam continues
to reject forced repatriation but will work toward reaching a
settlement ``on the basis of respect for the humanitarian spirit.''
   The nearly 12,000 Vietnamese in Hong Kong camps who arrived
before June 1988 automatically received refugee status and will be
resettled overseas.
   But under a tough new policy, the more than 44,000 boat people
who sailed into the colony later are considered illegal immigrants
subject to repatriation against their will unless they can prove
they fled political or religious persecution.
   Of the nearly 7,000 screened, only 687 have been granted refugee
status.
   The United States has been among the most vocal opponents of
forced repatriation, saying conditions must first improve in
Vietnam.
   Some lawmakers attributed Washington's position to a ``guilty
conscience,'' a reference to the U.S. role in the Vietnam War.
   They also argued that U.S. economic sanctions were preventing
Vietnam from escaping poverty, thereby contributing to the stream
of Vietnamese fleeing to seek a better life abroad.
   ``There is no reason for the United States to oppose mandatory
repatriation of (Vietnamese) illegal immigrants when they are
practicing this every day at the U.S.-Mexican border,'' lawmaker
Allen Lee argued.
   Boat people already have staged hunger strikes and
demonstrations in their detention centers to protest forced
repatriation.
   The Legislative Council motion was overwhelmingly approved by
voice vote.
</TEXT>
