<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Auction     11-29 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Auction,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auction Record Set for Modigliani Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A world auction record in sterling was set for the
work of Italian artist Amedeo Modigliani when a Japanese gallery
bought a painting by him for the equivalent of $7.89 million,
Sotheby's said.
   The sale of ``Fillette au Tablier Noir'' was part of an auction
Tuesday night of impressionist and modern paintings and sculpture
that together brought in $104 million.
   Twenty-two works, including ones by Claude Monet and Paul
Gauguin, each fetched more than $1.56 million.
   The Fujii Gallery paid 5,060,000 pounds for ``Fillette au
Tablier Noir,'' a painting of a girl in a black dress.
   The previous highest auction price for Modigliani was 4.4
million pounds in March 1988, then the equivalent of $7.9 million
against a stronger dollar.
   The seller was not identified but the picture last belonged to a
private collection in Baden, Switzerland. It was painted in 1918 in
Paris.
   Modigliani, whose portraits were characterized by deep oval
faces, only became famous after his death at age 36 in 1920 from
tuberculosis, aggravated by poverty, drink and drugs.
   The top price, paid anonymously by a telephone bidder, was $8.9
million for one of Monet's famous paintings of water lilies.
   Aksa International, a Japanese conglomerate, paid $6.8 million
for Gauguin's 1889 painting of a Breton boy in a landscape. The
company owns 7 percent in Christie's auction house, a Sotheby's
rival.
   The Gauguin was one of five works that together brought nearly
$17 million for the J. Paul Getty Museum in Malibu, Calif.
   The museum recently sent 15 works to Sotheby's for auction,
saying they represented the private taste of the oil billionaire,
who died in 1976. The museum said it will use the proceeds to
acquire other works better suited to its collection and public
display.
</TEXT>
