<FIRST>r a PM-TaintedBlood     11-29 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tainted Blood,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Selling Tainted Blood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man infected with the AIDS virus was
convicted of knowingly selling tainted blood and sentenced to six
years in prison.
   Assistant Solicitor Francis J. Cornely said Hank R. Mosely's
trial was the first clear test of a 1988 law making it a felony to
knowingly sell, donate or exchange blood or body fluids infected
with the virus without informing others.
   Earlier this year, a man pleaded guilty to the charge, Cornely
said.
   A jury convicted Mosely on Tuesday.
   The lawyer for the 32-year-old Ladson man argued he did not
expose anyone to AIDS since the blood was destroyed by the Alpha
Plasma Center when it tested positive for AIDS a week after it was
collected June 22. Police arrested him Aug. 9.
   Prosecutors argued that he had run the risk of exposing medical
technicians, nurses and others to the virus.
</TEXT>
