<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Israel     11-29 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Israel,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Calls for Closer Polish Cooperation with Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa met today
with Israeli Vice Premier Shimon Peres and called for closer
cooperation with Israel.
   Peres, the highest-ranking Israeli official ever to visit
Poland, told Walesa on the final day of a three-day trip that
Israel was closely following reforms in Poland and awaited a visit
from the Solidarity leader.
   Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski on Monday told Peres
that Warsaw will restore relations with Israel, broken off 22 years
ago.
   With reporters present at the start of today's meeting, Walesa
said the nations ``should tighten our cooperation. Poland is
pursuing reforms. In these reforms your participation is
indispensable.''
   One purpose of Peres' visit was to improve economic cooperation
between the countries. Polish trade with Israel will amount to $40
million this year, compared with $22.3 million last year.
   Walesa told Peres that Poland was applying a method of indexing
wages to prices similar to a policy used in Israel. ``We can rely
on and benefit from your experience,'' he said.
   Walesa also noted that Poles and Jews shared a common history.
``Let us remember this was a country of two peoples. The war
destroyed the Jewish people and to this day we feel the shortage,''
he said.
   Poland had the largest Jewish population in Eastern Europe until
the Holocaust, in which 3 million of Poland's 3.5 million Jews were
killed. Nearly all the survivors emigrated after World War II.
   Earlier today, Peres visited the Auschwitz concentration camp in
southern Poland, where 2.5 million Jews were among the 4 million
people who died there.
   There has been a steady warming in relations between Israel and
Poland in recent years, with senior officials, cultural figures and
private groups exchanging visits.
   All Warsaw Pact nations except Romania severed diplomatic
relations with Israel following the 1967 Middle East War.
   Hungary on Sept. 18 became the first Warsaw Pact country to
fully restore relations.
   Poland has had low-level ties since 1986, allowing Israel to
maintain a diplomatic office in Warsaw. The Soviet Union renewed
low-level relations last year.
</TEXT>
