<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0452 11-29 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Nominate Ex-New York State Senator for Civil Rights Post:
Sources</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New lead and 4th and 5th grafs with White House calling Dunne
top candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administration sources say President Bush will
nominate former New York State Sen. John R. Dunne to the top civil
rights post in the Justice Department. Bush's spokesman
acknowledged that Dunne is ``the top candidate.''
   Dunne, 59, belongs to the all-male Garden City Golf Club on Long
Island but has said he would resign if nominated as assistant
attorney general for civil rights.
   Bush earlier nominated William Lucas, a black from Detroit who
served as sheriff and county executive. Lucas' nomination was
blocked after a bruising confirmation fight on a tie-vote in the
Senate Judiciary Committee on Aug. 1.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today that
Dunne ``is the top candidate ... and we'll announce it when we
announce it.''
   He declined to talk about Dunne's qualifications for the civil
rights post, saying, ``We haven't made a selection yet.''
   The civil rights job, occupied by William Bradford Reynolds
during the Reagan administration, has been vacant all year.
Reynolds stirred controversy with his forceful opposition to
programs relying on racial preferences.
   On Tuesday, Bush signed legislation extending the life of the
U.S. Commission on Civil Rights through Sept. 30, 1991. The panel,
shrouded in controversy during the Reagan years, had been facing
extinction.
   Dunne is credited with helping reform the New York's prison
system after the deadly riot at Attica Prison in 1971. He went to
Attica and was critical of Gov. Nelson Rockefeller's handling of
the riot.
   Thirty-nine Attica inmates and guards were killed when
Rockefeller sent in heavily armed state police to retake the
prison; a guard and three inmates were also killed during the
uprising.
   The sources, who insisted on anonymity, said Dunne was
undergoing a background clearance check before the White House
formally announces the nomination. That check could take up to two
months.
   Dunne, a graduate of Georgetown University and Yale Law School,
resigned from the New York Senate in September after a 24-year
career in which he rose to deputy majority leader. He returned to
practice law in Uniondale, N.Y., after losing a race for majority
leader in the Republican-controlled Senate.
   A secretary who answered the telephone at Dunne's office said:
``The senator has no comments and is referring all calls to the
people in Washington.''
   ``If the president has to pick a Republican, he couldn't pick a
more decent person than John Dunne,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y., an old friend of Dunne's.
   Rangel said Dunne has the legal experience and training ``that
the previous candidate lacked.''
   During most of his 24 years in the Legislature _ a part-time
post _ Dunne lived at Albany's Fort Orange Club, which admitted
women to membership only last year.
   Dunne told Newsday in an interview last week that he would
resign his membership in the all-male Garden City Golf Club if
nominated to the Justice post.
   ``It would send the wrong message to stay,'' he said. ``It would
be inappropriate.''
</TEXT>
