<FIRST>r a PM-SoCalWinds     11-29 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SoCal Winds,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fierce Winds Whip Fires, Down Power Lines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dry, desert winds howling through Southern
California pushed flames across acres of brush and downed power
lines, cutting electricity to thousands.
   ``It's blowing like mad,'' said Highway Patrol officer Dale
Clark in San Bernardino. ``The Santa Anas are back with us again.''
   The Santa Ana winds reached 70 mph and accompanied regular winds
of 35 mph overnight at the Rialto Airport in San Bernardino County,
the National Weather Service said.
   Nearby in the Cajon Pass, wind ranged from 40 mph to 60 mph,
forcing trucks, campers and vans to stop on the shoulder of
Interstate 15 and wait for gusts to lessen, the Highway Patrol
said. Part of the interstate was all but closed Tuesday morning as
dirt and sand kicked up by the wind reduced visibility to almost
zero.
   The weather station in Sandberg, about 60 miles northwest of
downtown Los Angeles, reported steady winds of 30 to 35 mph Tuesday
night, with gusts to 45 mph.
   Earlier Tuesday, winds fanned a brush fire in northern San Diego
County that blackened more than 3,000 acres, destroyed several
structures and forced the evacuation of schools and homes.
   The blaze was 60 percent contained today and residents were
allowed back in their homes, authorities said.
   About 50 homes at the El Toro Marine Corps Air Station were
evacuated when a fire in a manure pile near the station's horse
stables ignited and was fanned by high winds, said base spokesman
Lt. Gene Browne.
   No one was hurt and no structures burned in the early morning
blaze. Residents were allowed back into their homes within two
hours.
   Power outages caused by wind affected 40,000 customers in San
Bernardino, Orange and Ventura counties. Power was restored to all
but a few users by Tuesday afternoon. About 5,000 Los Angeles
customers also were blacked out Tuesday.
   Jerry Steiger, a National Weather Service meteorologist, said
the winds were expected to decrease today as a high pressure system
over Utah weakens.
   Santa Ana winds typically are caused when a high-pressure system
forms over the northern Rocky Mountain states while a low-pressure
system hovers over Baja California.
   Air rushing across the Western deserts from high to low pressure
heats up and dries out, and then roars through mountain passes
around the Los Angeles basin.
</TEXT>
