<FIRST>r i PM-UN-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0527 11-29 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-PLO, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0527,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Talks With PLO Threatened By PLO's U.N. Bid For Nationhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE that resolution not expected until
Thursday; CORRECTS that food agency to provide technical assistance. Pickup
6th graf, `Since PLO ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering says
the dialogue between the United States and PLO will be jeopardized
if the General Assembly recognizes the Palestine Liberation
Organization as a nation.
   Debate on the Palestinian problem opens today in the General
Assembly, where Arab nations planned to introduce a resolution
Thursday that would raise the PLO's status from an observer
organization to a non-voting nation, like North and South Korea,
Monaco, the Vatican, San Marino and Switzerland.
   The State Department has threatened to cut off all U.S. funds
for the United Nations if the General Assembly approves the step.
The United States is assessed $216 million annually, one-fourth of
the U.N. budget.
   Pickering said Tuesday that the PLO move ``has serious
consequences for the peace process in the Middle East, our ongoing
dialogue with the PLO, a lot of very important issues, issues that
I would say should be much more important to the PLO than the mere
change on a nameplate here in the United Nations.''
   In Rome today, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization
ignored American objections and voted overwhelmingly to help the
PLO teach Palestinians how to grow food in Israeli-occupied
territories. The United States has threatened to cut funds to the
organization if the measure passed.
   Since PLO leader Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism last year,
the United States has held talks with PLO representatives in Tunis,
Tunisia.
   Arab League Ambassador Clovis Maksoud said the Arab group was
determined to go ahead with the move to change the PLO's status in
the United Nations, but that negotiations would continue with other
U.N. members.
   Pickering rejected any compromise, saying, ``We are clearly not
interested in exploring all the alternatives.
   ``We are interested in finding a way to end this particular
silly idea that the Palestinians can be declared a state here in
the United Nations when they have none of the attributes of a
state.''
   European and Nordic diplomats, who often play a buffer role in
the recurring U.S.-PLO confrontations, worked on a compromise prior
to the showdown vote Friday, but said privately they had little
hope.
   Upgrading the PLO's status would take a simple majority vote of
the 159 General Assembly members. As a member of the 102-member
non-aligned movement, the PLO has more than enough votes to prevail.
   Last year, the PLO declared the existence of a state of
Palestine in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and the
PLO says 117 nations have recognized it.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said the United States
is obligated to pay its U.N. dues even if the PLO is recognized as
``Palestine.''
   He rejected the U.S. threat of non-payment and commented,
``Sometimes I think I have the impression that the Americans think
that they're making a loan. The Americans ought to pay what they
owe.''
   Israel, America's firmest ally in the Middle East, calls the PLO
a terrorist organization and refuses to negotiate with it.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
