<FIRST>r a PM-HolidayNightmare     11-29 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday Nightmare,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Specter of Repo Man Looms in Peewee Team's Nightmare Road Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nightmarish Thanksgiving trip of two suburban
peewee football teams turned more bizarre with word that a team bus
thought to have been stolen from a Florida parking lot was actually
repossessed.
   During the five-day trip, the young players and their chaperones
faced repeated bus breakdowns, sleepless nights, a shortened trip
to Walt Disney World and two humiliating losses in football.
   The lowlight of the trip may have been the disappearance of one
of three buses used to transport the team, along with $2,200 in
donated cash, radios, cameras, jackets and other personal
possessions on board.
   The bus vanished from the parking lot of an Orlando-area high
school during the second of two Pop Warner League football games
involving the teams. Many of the 116 group members were left
stranded in Lake City, Fla. and forced to buy airline or bus
tickets back to Chicago.
   Team officials discovered Tuesday that the bus had been
repossessed and was parked at the ABC Bus Co. compound in Winter
Garden, Fla., the Chicago Tribune reported today.
   An ABC official in Winter Garden said he found $2,209 in cash on
the bus but little else.
   ``If we can get the $2,200 back, it would be a thrill,'' said
Roxanne Whited, president of the teams. ``We were left high and
dry.''
   Whited blamed the repossession on Falcon Motorcoach Co., which
provided the group with the buses, two of which broke down
repeatedly on the trip.
   But Ken Arnold, one of Falcon's owners, said his company is not
to blame because he had leased the bus from another company, B&amp;B
Tours, in south suburban Markham.
   B&amp;B officials, in turn, said they had leased the bus from yet
another firm _ Grand Tour by Linda, of Harvey, La. _ and had no
idea the company was behind on payments and that the bus might be
repossessed.
   B&amp;B repairs buses, among other things. Bernard Jackson, a
manager of B&amp;B, said that his company had repaired the bus that was
repossessed but that Grand Tour hadn't paid the bill. Grand Tour
had made arrangements for B&amp;B to use the bus as partial payment for
the work.
   Jackson said it's a common for companies that own buses to
employ repossessors to reclaim the vehicles when payments are
overdue.
   ``These guys ride around all over the United States, to the
hotspots where buses might be, and when they see the bus, they
snatch it,'' Jackson said today.
   Officials at Grand Tour by Linda could not be reached for
comment. The company's telephone was disconnected.
   Bob Yochum, an official at ABC's headquarters in Faribault,
Minn., refused to comment about the repossession. ``It's a private
business transaction,'' he said.
</TEXT>
