<HEAD>Second Distress Flare Spotted in Fishermen Search</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to fix `further' to `farther.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard searchers looking for five lobstermen
missing since last week moved farther out to sea this morning after
spotting a distress flare for the second night in a row.
   Three aircraft and two cutters searched a 10,000-square-mile
area about 270 miles southeast of Nantucket.
   ``The flares are coming from somewhere,'' said Lt. Paul Wolf.
   Rescuers said they hoped to find the boat's life raft, which
would have contained red and orange flares such as those spotted
Monday and Tuesday.
   The 72-foot Heidi Marie out of Stonington, Conn., was reported
missing last Wednesday by its owner.
   The vessel's last transmission was Nov. 21, the day officials
received a distress signal from a fishing area south of New York's
Long Island.
