<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev 2ndLd-Writethru a0536 11-29 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0536,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Begins First Visit Of Soviet Chief To Italy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with color, Gorbachev waving to
chanting crowds. Pickup 9th graf, `The talks...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Italians waving small Soviet flags
greeted Mikhail S. Gorbachev today as he prepared for a historic
meeting with the pope and became the first Soviet Communist Party
chief to make an official visit here.
   On Tuesday, the Vatican said the pope planned to ask for
establishment of permanent ties between the Holy See and the
Kremlin.
   Premier Giulio Andreotti welcomed the Soviet president shortly
after his Ilyushin-62 touched down at Leonardo da Vinci airport on
a sunny Rome morning. The two leaders inspected an honor guard and
a 21-gun salute rang out.
   Gorbachev, in a blue overcoat and gray fedora, shook hands with
a line of Italian officials before his motorcade departed for the
Soviet ambassador's residence, Villa Abamelek, where he and his
wife, Raisa, are staying.
   Thousands cheered Gorbachev as his motorcade traveled a short
while later to the Renaissance presidential palace for a meeting
with President Francesco Cossiga. Sharpshooters were posted on
buildings along the route.
   Crowds chanted ``Gorby! Gorby!'' and ``Bravo, Mikhail, bravo!''
A group of young people burst into the strains of the Socialist
Internationale, thrusting their fists into the air.
   ``Gorby, you are a beautiful man,'' one bystander yelled.
   While not as effusive as the popular welcome given the Soviet
president in other Western European countries, it was a rare public
tribute to a foreign leader in the Italian capital.
   The three-day visit comes just before the U.S.-Soviet summit off
Malta. Italian officials say they hope to get in ``the last
European word'' before Gorbachev heads into his talks with
President Bush.
   Gorbachev later joined a wreath-laying ceremony at the Tomb of
the Unknown Soldier in central Rome and went on a whirlwind tour of
Rome's famous sights, including the Colosseum.
   His first contact with the Roman public was at the central
Piazza Venezia, the square where fascist dictator Benito Mussolini
once stirred crowds from his office balcony. Gorbachev smiled and
waved as thousands cheered and waved plastic Soviet flags.
   The talks in Rome were expected to focus on Eastern Europe.
Czechoslovakia's leaders have now joined East Germany, Poland,
Hungary and Bulgaria in bowing to public pressure and rejecting
hard-line communism.
   As the Gorbachev visit began, Amnesty International's Rome
office issued an appeal for the release of seven Soviet political
prisoners, including one it said was detained for religious
activities.
   Gorbachev meets Friday with the Polish-born John Paul II in the
first such encounter between a pope, leader of the world's 850
million Roman Catholics, and a Soviet Communist Party chief.
   On the eve of Gorbachev's arrival, Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro said the pope would press for diplomatic relations with the
Kremlin.
   The statement was a dramatic indication of the improvement in
relations between the Vatican and the Soviet government, which once
tried to abolish religious practice.
   Gorbachev is popular among Italians for his reform programs, and
Italian-Soviet relations have been good in recent years. The
government is eager to help Gorbachev overcome the economic crisis
that his reforms have not resolved.
   About $3.3 billion worth of agreements between Italian private
and public industry and the Soviet Union are being concluded in
connection with Gorbachev's visit.
   The Fiat auto giant announced Tuesday the signing of a joint
venture agreement to produce 300,000 cars a year in the Soviet
Union.
   The visit comes as Italy's own Communist Party, the biggest in
the West, is moving toward changing its name and becoming a social
democratic grouping. The Italian Communists regularly win more than
25 percent of the vote.
   Rome prettied up for the visit, repaving roads and cleaning
building facades. ``Welcome to Italy, President Gorbachev'' read
red posters put up by the Italy-Soviet Union Association.
   The government planned to showcase Italy's famed cuisine at a
state dinner, with a menu that included small ravioli stuffed with
truffles, gilt-bream fish Sicilian-style, and fruit and eggnog
cream, along with wines and spumanti.
</TEXT>
