<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   11-29 1001</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,1033</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the country:
   Nov. 24
   Los Angeles Times on the 101st Congress:
   The first session of the 101st Congress blessedly faded into the
bleak November Washington dawn ... more notable for all that it
undid or left undone than for its few achievements. ...
   The House and Senate dismantled a major program, the 1988
catastrophic health care system, which sank under an anti-tax
backlash. They then pasted together a $14.7 billion budget deficit
reduction measure with a good deal of whole cloth, in the form of
fiscal shell games, and (hush) some $6 billion in various ``revenue
enhancements'' (i.e., tax increases). ...
   Sustantial progress was made on new programs such as the Clean
Air Act and child care. And the escalating demands of the
Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law may compel (President) Bush to
do something he failed to do this year; to lay a coherent fiscal
program before Congress in January. ...
   At the outset, the new president had lots of good will in
Congress, but he lost several big ones in his first year, including
his fight to fulfill a major campaign pledge, the capital gains
(tax) cut, and his selection for secretary of defense, John Tower
(a blessing in disguise, since he got the able Dick Cheney
instead). And he may have tripped himself up politically with his
hard-line position against public funding for abortion, even in
cases of rape and incest. ...
   The challenge for Bush is to develop a congressional agenda with
clear direction and to demonstrate a willingness to support his
kinder, gentler leanings with the necessary money.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 27
   The News and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on the Iowa blast probe:
   Since the (Navy's) own investigator made his original report, he
has changed his explanation of what triggered the blast. At first,
he said it was an electronic detonator; he now says it probably was
a chemical device.
   Yet even before the April tragedy, crewmen and their families
had been reporting accidents on board the Iowa, incidents not
mentioned in the Navy's report.
   There are conflicting stories about Seaman (Clayton) Hartwig
(who died in the blast and was blamed). Some of his shipmates
regarded him as depressed, others did not; others said he was
looking forward to his new assignment in London, and that he lacked
the technical expertise to construct the kind of device that
allegedly caused the explosion.
   And, too, there are disturbing questions about how the
investigation itself was conducted: At least one seaman said he was
threatened with severe retribution by Navy investigators if he
didn't tell the story they wanted him to.
   As a result, the armed services committees of both the Senate
and House have launched special inquiries into the explosion, as
has the General Accounting Office. Also under examination is the
Navy's handling of its own investigation.
   The inquiries are more than justified. The Navy may indeed turn
out to be correct in its conclusions. But the evidence and the
methods used by the service raise fears that rather than pursuing
the truth, Navy investigators sought to shift blame for the tragedy
from the Navy to a seaman no longer here to defend himself.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 28
   Philadelphia Daily News on U.S.-Salvador:
   No wonder the United States has trouble finding an answer in
Central America. We can't even figure out what the question isn't.
   For instance, it is not whether the government of El Salvador is
duly constituted or elected. Maybe it is, but so is the government
of Nicaragua, which the United States has made a holy crusade of
overthrowing.
   It is not whether the $1.5 million that gets soaked up every day
by the Salvadoran government helps the people of El Salvador. It
does not. It goes for weapons to keep the people in line and to
keep the thugs in charge, in charge.
   It is not a question of maintaining ourselves as some kind of
moderating influence, moving a nation toward democracy, or at least
away from official murder. We have no influence in El Salvador. We
can't even get murderers arrested.
   It is not a question of fending off communism, the world's most
overrated threat. The very fact of our providing aid to oppressors
provides the only soil in which communism seems to thrive. ...
   The only question that matters is one the Congress of the United
States and the Bush administration refuse to consider ... : Should
the United States give aid and comfort to those who are
slaughtering their own citizens?
   The civil war in El Salvador has been going on for 10 years.
Even under the most inhumane geopolitical standard, our involvement
has done nothing but make things worse and to up the ante in lives.
We are co-conspirators with murderers. We should not _ cannot _ be.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 26
   Central Maine Morning Sentinel, Waterville, Maine, on
U.S.-Salvador:
   Even in El Salvador, where the only thing more chronic than war
and violence is poverty, last week's murder ... of six Jesuit
priests, their housekeeper and the housekeeper's daughter was
shockingly savage.
   The six massacred Jesuits were scholars and teachers and
political activists, part of what has become known as ``liberation
theology.'' They opposed the right-wing Cristiani government, which
has denounced the murders and pledged to bring the perpetrators to
justice.
   Despite that pledge, the murders have stretched U.S. support for
the Salvadoran government to its limit. The U.S. House ... came
within 21 votes of passing a bill that would have cut aid to El
Salvador, which now totals $500 million a year, by a third. ...
   But should the aid have been suspended? Not this time, not for
this incident. Foreign policy, liberal or conservative, should not
be dictated by reactions to single incidents of violence. Decisions
should be made after careful consideration of the broader
situation. And the broader situation in El Salvador is both violent
and muddy.
</TEXT>
