<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     11-29 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Junta Meets With Political Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government met with an
opposition political party for the first time and repeated its
pledge to hold free elections in May, a party source said today.
   Meanwhile, Thai authorities said Burmese government troops have
launched their first big attack in four months on two rebel camps
near the Thai border.
   A member of the opposition Union Nationals Democracy Party said
in Rangoon that Brig. Gen. Khin Nyunt, the second-ranking
government official, held an hour of talks Tuesday with the party's
general secretary, Kyi Han.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted Khin
Nyunt as saying the government has ordered officials at all levels
to be strictly neutral in the election.
   The military junta came to power in a September 1988 coup in
which soldiers killed hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators.
   In recent months the junta has cracked down again on the
opposition. Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, the leaders of the popular
opposition National League For Democracy, were put under house
arrest July 20.
   Of the 206 political parties registered to take part in the
elections, six have developed a national network. They include the
National League For Democracy and the Union Nationals Democracy
Party.
   It was not immediately known why Khin Nyunt met only with an
official of the Union Nationals.
   In the northern Thai town of Mae Sot, a border patrol police
officer said Burmese forces fired mortar and artillery guns at two
camps of the ethnic Karen rebels. The officer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the offensive began Tuesday night just
across the border from Mae Sot.
   He said 2,000 rebels were defending the camps against about
4,000 government soldiers. The officer said he had no information
on casualties.
   The Karens withstood a fierce government offensive in late July.
   The ethnic minority is one of the strongest of a dozen guerrilla
groups fighting for greater regional autonomy.
</TEXT>
