<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: and muddy.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 25
   The Arizona Republic, Phoenix, on Czechoslovakia:
   No hyperbole has been spared in describing the momentous events
shaking Eastern Europe in recent weeks. Tongue-tied correspondents,
pundits and the people themselves _ Poles, Hungarians and East
Germans _ have fumbled for sufficiently forceful adjectives to
depict the historic developments.
   But the prize for understatement must go to Milos Jakes, the
general secretary of the Czech Communist Party who, along with the
rest of the top party leadership, resigned Friday (Nov. 24).
   In a speech to his besieged comrades just before the mass
capitulation, ... Jakes said that perhaps they had ``underestimated
completely the processes taking place in Poland, Hungary and
especially East Germany and their effect and influence on our
society.''
   For ... Jakes, the light apparently dawned ... when upward of
300,000 of his countrymen marched in Prague's 650-year-old
Wenceslas Square, the largest gathering in the history of
Czechoslovakia.
   The demonstration culminated weeklong uprisings in Prague,
Bratislava and other cities, capped by the triumphal return of
Alexander Dubcek, who championed the ill-fated 1968 democracy
movement that was crushed so ruthlessly by Soviet tanks.
   ``If there once was light,'' ... Dubcek told his cheering
countrymen, ``why should there be darkness again? Let us ... bring
back the light.''
   The old guard feels betrayed by Moscow. After the Red Army
smashed the quixotic '68 revolt, the Czech party became one of the
most servile in the communist bloc, toadying unabashedly to Moscow.
Now Mikhail Gorbachev, preoccupied with his own problems, has
abandoned these Czech sycophants, leaving them to their own devices.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 24
   Corvallis (Ore.) Gazette-Times on extending Chinese students'
visas:
   The Chinese government is threatening diplomatic retaliation
against the United States for the congressional passage of a bill
to allow Chinese students to stay in this country. ...
   Under current law, foreigners on student visas must return home
for at least two years after completing their education before they
can apply for a different visa status. The bill passed by Congress
would eliminate the two-year requirement for the Chinese students
now legally in this country. ...
   Beijing is trying to send a message to the students ... that
they have nothing to fear by returning home.
   The message is completely unbelievable. It comes from a
government that used tanks and armed soldiers to kill peaceful
demonstrators (and) has imprisoned leaders of the protest movement.
...
   One of the great tragedies ... of history ... occurred following
World War II. This country joined other Allies in the forced
repatriation to the Soviet Union of people who had fled or been
captured in battle. After promising (that no harm would come to
these people), the Soviet government killed or imprisoned them.
   Forcing students back to China could have the same tragic
results as that sorry episode. President Bush should learn from
history and sign the visa bill into law.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 26
   Oshkosh (Wis.) Northwestern on drug use and student grants:
   There is a bit of resentment on college campuses these days
because Uncle Sam is insisting on an oath of no drug use@dealing in
order to get federal student grants.
   It is not unlike the requirement a few years ago that students
must comply with the requirements of the selective service law
before they could have grants.
   The main point is that those federal grants to students are not
something to which the students are entitled as a right.
   It makes sense that a government which is appropriating large
amounts of money in a war on drugs should see to it that other
federal money is not being spent at cross-purposes.
   The issue is larger than Pell Grants to students, though. The
issue is whether there should be attached qualifications for grants
in general.
   Of course there should. ...
   If the grant is for education, it would be silly if the grant
were not made with an attached string, for instance, that the money
be used for education. And it is entirely reasonable that the
government requires the recipients to maintain a clear record,
whether clear of felonies or clear of drug-related offenses.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 27
   Northeast Mississippi Daily Journal, Tupelo, Miss., on gun
control:
   James Brady testified before a Senate subcommittee last week.
His subject, not surprisingly, was handgun control.
   Brady is something of a walking miracle. He was Ronald Reagan's
press secretary in 1981 when a bullet ripped through his brain
during an assassination attempt on the president.
   Brady's testimony was brave and riveting. He called the Congress
``cowardly lions'' for its failure to enact even the most
restrained controls on handgun sales. His words should pierce the
conscience of every congressman who has voted against a sensible
seven-day waiting period for handgun purchases.
   The bill is nothing more than an attempt to keep mentally
deranged people and outright criminals from legally buying
handguns. It is not designed to keep any lawabiding citizen in
(his) right mind from owning a gun.
   Now, let the National Rifle Association and other groups come
forward claiming gun-control backers are unpatriotic wimps. James
Brady puts the lie to that absurd claim.
   Brady casts the issue in a clear light that must be considered.
   Gun control is not a matter of gun ownership alone; it is a
matter of human life. Life is more important than owning a handgun.
</TEXT>
