<SECOND>AM-BRF--Too Young,0179</SECOND>
<UNK>Suspect 3 Hours Too Young to Be Tried as Adult</UNK>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for James M. Payton halted
his trial on battery charges by pointing out Payton couldn't be
tried as an adult because he was too young _ by three hours.
   Deputy Monroe County Prosecutor Chuck Huston was ready to argue
that Payton struck another man with a masonry hammer about 12:30
a.m. Oct. 15.
   Just before trial was to begin Monday, attorneym Pat Schrems,
noted that Payton turned 18 at 3:11 a.m. Oct. 15. Schrems said
Payton was a juvenile at the time of the offense and should be
tried as a minor.
   Huston argued that aspects of Indiana law say a person becomes a
certain age at midnight on his birthday. A person can legally drink
at midnight on his 21st birthday, he said.
   Monroe Superior Court Judge Douglas ``Randy'' Bridges agreed
with Schrems and dismissed the charges.
   Prosecutor Bob Miller said charges would be refiled in juvenile
court against Payton, who remains in police custody.
</TEXT>
