<FIRST>r a AM-MadDads     11-29 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mad Dads,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>MADD Sues Mad Dads, Charging Name Infringement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving, known as MADD,
wants a federal judge to stop a fathers' group called Mad Dads Inc.
to stop using that name.
   In a lawsuit filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, Dallas-based
MADD sought unspecified money for alleged damage to its efforts to
promote the interests of people opposed to drunken driving.
   MADD contends Mad Dads is trading on the goodwill MADD has built
up, and the similarity of the names is likely to confuse the
public. The lawsuit alleges violation of MADD's service mark,
registered in 1983 with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,
according to court documents.
   MADD also said it owns the service mark ``I'm a MADD Dad,''
which was registered Nov. 7.
   Mad Dads Inc. was formed this year to discourage use of alcohol
and illegal drugs by young people and prevent gang-related crime in
the Omaha area. Spokesman John Foster said the organization does
not want to fight with MADD, but does not want to change its name.
   ``Mad Dads depicts what we are all about, parents at the
grass-roots level trying to combat the gang and drug problem in
Omaha and outside Omaha,'' Foster said.
   An attorney for Mad Dads, Thomas Johnson, said a Texas law firm
that represents MADD refused his written suggestion of a meeting of
representatives of the two groups.
   Of the claim for money, Foster said, ``Mad Dads doen't have much
money. All we have is firm commitment and determination.''
</TEXT>
