<FIRST>r a AM-InternationalMarriage     11-29 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-International Marriage,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Language Barrier, American to Wed Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Klasavich speaks no Russian and
Marina Enikeeva speaks no English, but that will not stop the
American from marrying the Soviet next month.
   Klasavich of Old Orchard Beach plans to fly to Archangel, a
Soviet city near the Arctic Circle, to marry the woman he met on a
trip in June to improve U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``Everybody thinks I'm crazy except the people who were on that
trip,'' he said. ``They understand perfectly how this could
happen.''
   Klasavich and 42 other Mainers spent four days in Archangel as
part of the sister-city exchange between Greater Portland and the
Soviet port city of about 400,000 people.
   ``You would have thought we were royalty there,'' Klasavich
said. ``They were the warmest and friendliest people that I've ever
met.''
   The wedding has generated so much excitement in Archangel that
it may be broadcast on the city's television station, and the mayor
will be at the reception, said Klasavich, a telephone equipment
installer.
   It took only one day and a river cruise for Klasavich, 44, and
Enikeeva, 23, to know that something was happening between them. He
returned to Archangel four months later and won support from
Enikeeva'a mother and grandmother before he dropped to one knee in
front of the family and asked her to marry him.
   U.S. immigration officials estimate it will be at least three
months after the wedding before Soviet and U.S. red tape can be
cleared to bring Enikeeva and her 4-year-old son from a previous
marriage to Maine, where they intend to live.
   He said he sometimes wonders how they will manage without an
interpreter, whether their age difference is too great and whether
she is marrying him only to get out of the Soviet Union, as some of
his friends have suggested.
   But he says, ``I can't stand the idea of living without her.
It's that simple.''
</TEXT>
