<HEAD>Police Outraged After Slain Officer's Badge Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEWISTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are outraged over the theft of a
badge that belonged to a slain officer from a memorial plaque in
the station, the chief said.
   ``In my mind, you have to be sick to do something like that,''
Chief Laurent F. Gilbert Sr. said Wednesday. ``To us, it mant
everything. To someone else, it's just a trophy.''
   Gilbert said he noticed Tuesday that David R. Payne's badge had
been taken from a plaque in the station lobby. A security camera
does not focus on that area, Gilbert said.
   Payne, 26, was shot to death while on duty July 23, 1988. Joseph
Loveall, also known as Nicolo Leone, has been sentenced to 20 years
in prison for manslaughter in Payne's death, and 40 more years for
attempted murders of two officers who had gone to Payne's aid.
   Gilbert appealed for the return of the badge or information on
who may have taken it.
   ``I want that badge back,'' Gilbert said.
