<FIRST>u a PM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0482 11-29 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors of Fiery Bus Crash Scrambled Over Fellow Passengers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony from two
survivors. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `I looked up ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two survivors of a fiery church bus crash
testified today that they dived over a pile of fellow passengers
jamming an emergency door to escape the flames after the bus
collided head-on with a pickup truck.
   Thomas Hertz and Monica Obregon took the witness stand on the
fifth day of the trial of Larry Mahoney, the driver of the pickup.
   Mahoney, 36, is charged with 27 counts of murder, 12 of assault,
42 of wanton endangerment and one of drunken driving in what
authorities say is the nation's worst alcohol-related traffic
accident.
   The truck was driving in the wrong lane at the time of the 1988
accident, which left 24 youngsters and three adults dead and 13
people injured.
   Hertz, of Hendersonville, Tenn., testified he jumped over a pile
of people to escape flames and growing heat inside the bus owned by
the First Assembly of God church in Radcliff. The bus was returning
from an outing to a Cincinnati amusement park.
   Hertz said someone held his feet and he was ``hanging upside
down outside of the bus ... face at the bumper.''
   ``I did not know how much longer it would be before it would
blow up,'' he said.
   Ms. Obregon, 17, was asked if more people could have escaped if
there had been more exits. She tearfully replied, ``Yes.''
   Mahoney remained stoic throughout the morning proceedings, his
eyes fixed on a table he shared with his attorneys. On Tuesday he
wept as a witness described seeing a fellow passenger engulfed in
flames cry, ``Oh Lord, I'm coming home.''
   Testimony from more passengers was expected today, said the
prosecutor, Assistant Attorney General Paul Richwalsky Jr.
   On Tuesday, another teen-age survivor, Tammy Darnell, recounted
the panic on the church bus after the 10:55 p.m. collision on
Interstate 71 about five miles south of Carrollton.
   ``I looked up and seen nothing but flames and fire,'' said Miss
Darnell, 17, of Radcliff. She broke down in sobs, prompting Circuit
Judge Charles Satterwhite to call a brief recess.
   Afterward, Miss Darnell recalled seeing Chuck Kytta III,
engulfed in flames in the former school bus' stairwell.
   ``I saw our youth leader raise his hands and say `Oh Lord, I'm
coming home,''' Miss Darnell said. Kytta was one of 24 young people
who died. His father and two other adults also died.
   Mahoney broke down during the graphic testimony of Coroner James
B. Dunn, who described the bodies found inside the bus. Families of
the victims clasped hands tightly and dabbed tears with
handkerchiefs during Dunn's testimony.
   ``I couldn't believe what I had seen,'' Dunn said. ``I thought I
was having a nightmare.''
   Mahoney's sobbing prompted Satterwhite to order a recess.
Mahoney also broke into tears Monday as witnesses described the
screams and agony of the injured and dying.
   Russell Baldani, a defense attorney, said during a recess he
didn't know what effect Mahoney's sobbing would have on the jury.
   ``It's nothing staged. I'm sure they don't think that,'' Baldani
said.
   Mahoney's lawyers began building their case that the bus
carrying 67 people was unsafe.
   Before the crash, some passengers climbed over seats to sit with
friends and others were lying in the aisles, according to testimony
from survivors.
   ``It's no secret that's a big factor in our favor,'' Baldani
said.
</TEXT>
