<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Namibia     11-29 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Namibia,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Soldier of Angolan War Returns Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last soldier from the South
African-Angolan war returned home Wednesday after having been
sentenced earlier this year to 10 years in prison following his
capture.
   Simeon Petrus, a member of the disbanded South-West Africa
Territorial Force, was captured in Angola in 1987 and kept in
prison in Luanda, the Angolan capital, until he was sentenced Jan.
31.
   There was no information on the circumstances of Petrus'
capture, but members of his 101 Battalion often crossed into Angola
in pursuit of South-West African people's Organization guerrillas
in the 23-year bush war in Namibia. South African forces also
crossed into Angola to aid the guerrillas fighting the Marxist
government of Angola.
   The sentencing followed a peace agreement in which South Africa
withdrew its soldiers from Angola, ended aid to the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola and agreed to grant
independence to the territory of Namibia, while Cuba began
withdrawing its 50,000 soldiers who support the Angolan government.
   The agreement also called for all sides to free their prisoners.
Petrus, 24, was handed over to the Red Cross in Luanda on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
