<FIRST>r i AM-Linh     11-29 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Linh,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Leader Nguyen Van Linh Reported Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese Communist Party chief Nguyen Van Linh
suffered a stroke and is hospitalized in Ho Chi Minh City, it was
reported Wednesday.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service, quoting unidentified sources, said
Premier Do Muoi has temporarily taken over as party general
secretary.
   Linh, 72, was hospitalized first in Hanoi, the capital, then in
Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, after his return on Oct. 24 from
a visit to East Germany, Kyodo said, quoting sources in Hanoi.
   Kyodo quoted a Vietnamese Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying
Linh had been in ill health, but was recuperating under doctors'
care.
   Linh, who became party leader in 1986, said in September that
capitalist-style economic reforms would continue in Vietnam, but he
rejected any multiparty system or speeding of democratic reforms.
   He accused the United States and other ``imperialists'' of
trying to undermine the socialist camp and launching ``frenzied
attacks against socialism.''
</TEXT>
