<FIRST>r i AM-Tombstones     11-29 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tombstones,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stonemason Invents Tombstones to Stand up Against Quakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stonemason has patented a tombstone designed to
keep standing through severe earthquakes, saving high replacement
costs in a country where elaborate, expensive markers reflect deep
respect for ancestors.
   ``My earthquake-proof tombstones can resist even a temblor as
strong as the Great Kanto Earthquake,'' said Toshihiko Nagoya, 41.
   The 1923 earthquake, estimated at 7.9 on the Richter scale,
destroyed much of Tokyo, then a city of 2 million people, and
killed 140,000. Tokyo's population is now 12 million.
   The new tombstone uses stainless steel poles implanted in the
center, and its parts are pressed together with Nagoya's special
glue. He tested it with the help of Tokyo University's seismology
department.
   Japan, sitting along a major geological fault, is hit by
hundreds of quakes annually, although most are too weak to be felt.
   The idea for the new tombstone came after Nagoya inspected the
wreckage of statues and tombstones _ some costing nearly $70,000 _
after a strong earthquake two years ago in Chiba, just outside
Tokyo.
   ``Almost everything was destroyed at many temples and graveyards
I visited,'' he said.
   More stunning was the death of a woman hit by a falling stone
lantern in the quake, measured at 6.6 on the Richter scale.
   The new quake-resistant tombstone would not cost much more than
the normal price of up to $35,000, he said. Existing tombstones can
be made quake-resistant for about $1,045, he added.
</TEXT>
