<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 11-29 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fighting Resumes in San Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with rebels overrunning home of
U.S. official, Baker comments; Picks up 10th graf, `Guerrillas and ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador-Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting broke out in the
affluent western sectors of San Salvador again today, and U.S.
officials said leftist guerrillas briefly overran the home of an
American Embassy officer.
   The rebels also burned a mansion just blocks away from the
American ambassador's official residence, but no injuries were
reported to U.S. employees, according to the American officials.
   It was not immediately clear if the fighting signaled the
resumption of a major guerrilla offensive on the capital that began
Nov. 11 and appeared to have ended when the rebels withdrew on Nov.
22.
   The rebels said on their clandestine radio today they had
attacked the headquarters of the Joint Chiefs of Staff with
mortars. But officers on the scene said none had fallen in the
compound, which also houses the Defense Ministry. Reporters saw at
least six dead soldiers in one neighborhood and one dead guerrilla
in another.
   Residents of the zone, in the capital's western sector, said
they heard several loud explosions near the fortified complex
between 2 a.m. and 3 a.m.
   Rebels fired rocket-propelled grenades and assault rifles at the
Public Security Academy in the western suburb of Merliot. Col.
Rigoberto Soto, director of the academy, said the attack was
repelled. He said his troops suffered no casualties but that a few
guerrillas appeared to have been wounded.
   Fighting continued to be heavy after daylight on the edge of the
affluent Escalon neighborhood, which reaches to the slopes of the
San Salvador volcano, a guerrilla stronghold.
   Wilfredo Hernandez, soundman of a crew of the Spanish language
network Univision, was wounded in the back in the fighting in upper
Escalon.
   Fighting was heavy at times before dawn along the tree-lined
streets of San Benito, a wealthy residential district where U.S.
Ambassador William Walker has his official residence. Guerrillas
burned a mansion just blocks from Walker's house. It was not
immediately known whether Walker was home at the time.
   Some of the homes attacked belonged to U.S. Embassy employees,
but all the Americans were reported safe, White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater told reporters in Washington.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III later told reporters in
Washington that the rebels were ``shooting their way into and
invading certain private homes. They briefly overran the home of a
U.S. Embassy officer but were driven out by the Salvadoran armed
forces.''
   Walker lives in the same neighborhood, Baker said.
   Baker also cited unconfirmed reports that the rebels also
invaded the Japanese embassy in San Salvador. He offered no further
details. ``It is our belief that all United States personnel and
their families are safe but several are in their homes in this area
of heavy fighting,'' he said.
   Guerrillas and soldiers of the U.S.-supported, rightist
government also exchanged fire in Guadalupe, south of the Chiefs of
Staff, where three light tanks were positioned across the street
from a movie theater.
   Helicopters and O-2 spotter aircraft fired machine guns and
rockets at suspected guerrilla positions west and south of the
capital for several hours before dawn. Reporters saw at least six
dead soldiers and a burned light tank on the edge of Escalon, and
one dead guerrilla near Guadalupe.
   Rebels last week assaulted Escalon and briefly took over the
blocks surrounding the El Salvador Sheraton Hotel.
   That attack marked the conclusion of what may have only been the
first phase of a massive rebel offensive launched Nov. 11, the
largest in the 10-year-old civil war that has killed an estimated
71,000 people.
</TEXT>
