<DOCNO> AP891129-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel     11-29 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis: No Intervention Even if Syrians Attack Aoun</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a long history of supporting Lebanese
Christians, Israeli officials say they won't intervene this time to
defend Christian Gen. Michel Aoun from Syrian attack.
   The bitter experience of Israel's occupation of Lebanon from
1982-85 is largely responsible for the change in policy.
   However, the Israelis have issued new warnings to Syria about
making moves they say would endanger Israel's security and its
northern border.
   For example, Maj. Gen. Avihu Bin-Nun, the Israeli air force
chief, said on armed forces radio Wednesday that surprise flights
by Syrian warplanes over Lebanese territory where Israelis
routinely patrol could lead to clashes.
   Referring to reports that a Syrian MiG-23 had buzzed Aoun's
presidential palace in Baabda, Bin-Nun said: ``There is no doubt
that entrances like this to Lebanon can result in a clash, even
unwanted.''
   He hinted at diplomatic contacts to prevent greater tensions and
said, ``We are trying to make sure that the Lebanese do not get us
involved in a war that we don't intend, and we hope we will succeed
in that.''
   Israel has insisted it needs a clear view from Lebanon's
airspace to protect its border from attacks by Palestinian and
Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem guerrillas. It also has used the skies
to launch 15 air raids on guerrilla targets this year.
   Officials have said Israel would not tolerate Syrian troops
moving south of Sidon and the Awali river, about 25 miles north of
Israel's border, or into areas Israel evacuated in June 1985 at the
end of the three-year occupation. Those areas include the Bekaa
Valley.
   The occupation produced a consensus that is strongly against
renewed Israeli involvement. The war cost the lives of 650 Israeli
soldiers, damaged Israel's image abroad and caused deep political
splits at home.
   Israel invaded Lebanon in June 1982 following clashes in which
Israeli troops went to the defense of Christian militiamen being
attacked by Syrian forces.
   Israel threw its military backing and political support to
Bashir Gemayel, a Christian militia chief. But Gemayel was
assassinated in 1982, reportedly with Syrian involvement, and
Israel's hopes for a friendly Lebanese government were undone.
   The Christian militia's refusal to play a major role in driving
out Palestinian guerrillas also caused deep resentment in Israel's
army.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of staff, said last week that
Israel had no plans to intervene in the current standoff between
Aoun and Syrian troops unless its own security was threatened.
   ``As a matter of principle and policy, we do not involve
ourselves in Lebanon, as long as there is no Syrian threat or other
threat along our northern border,'' he said.
   One senior Israeli official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said Israel would not support Aoun just because he was a Christian
leader.
   ``We are tired of backing losers in Lebanon,'' the official said.
   However, there was lingering support among some Israelis for
Aoun's anti-Syria campaign, especially in the right-wing led by
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Rafael Eytan, a former chief of staff and now a member of
parliament, said Wednesday that Israel should support Aoun.
   He said Syrian gains in Lebanon ``will bring increased pressure
on us in southern Lebanon,'' where Israel still supports a
2,500-member Christian-led militia known as the South Lebanon Army.
