<HEAD>Bomb Squad Detonates Suitcase, Finds a Nintendo Game</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with item found to be a Nintendo game. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bomb squad officers at the airport today blew
up a Colombia-bound suitcase thought to contain explosives, only to
discover the bag contained nothing more dangerous than a video
game, police said.
   ``It wasn't an explosive device. It was a Nintendo game,'' said
Lt. Helen Kidder.
   X-rays at Los Angeles International Airport had detected what
appeared to be sticks of dynamite, wiring and a clock inside the
suitcase, which was to have been loaded onto an Avianca Airlines
jet bound for Colombia, police said.
   ``Our bomb squad acted on that information and we exploded it in
the canister,'' said Officer Bill Frio.
   There were no reports of threats against the flight, police said.
   On Monday, an Avianca jet exploded near Bogota, Colombia,
killing all 107 people aboard. Drug traffickers in Colombia have
waged a campaign of bombings there, but investigators have raised
doubts about whether terrorists caused the blast.
   ``This got more publicity because of the Avianca jet
explosion,'' Frio said of today's incident.
