<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessSuit     11-29 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Suit,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Sue MTA Over Panhandling Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulations that ban panhandling in the subway
system violate the constitutional rights of homeless people who may
need to beg to survive, according to a lawsuit filed by advocates
for the homeless.
   The class-action lawsuit brought Tuesday in U.S. District Court
challenges ``Operation Enforcement,'' a recent drive by the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority to enforce existing rules,
including the prohibition on panhandling.
   The lawsuit charged that the ban on begging singles out the
homeless because it allows other people to solicit contributions
for charitable, religious and political causes.
   ``The intended purpose is simply to roust the homeless and needy
from the subways,'' the lawsuit said.
   The regulation violates the First and 14th Amendment rights of
the homeless, it charged.
   ``To deny them this exercise of free speech is to deny them the
means to survive, for they spend the money they ask for on the very
necessities of life, that is, on food, shelter, clothing,
transportation and medicine,'' the lawsuit said.
   The plaintiffs are two homeless men who panhandle in the subway
system. The lawsuit, brought by the Legal Action Center for the
Homeless, was filed on behalf of all homeless people in the state.
   The defendants are the MTA and two of its agencies, the Transit
Authority and the Metro-North Commuter Railroad.
   ``We don't believe it's a constitutional right to panhandle, but
it's an obvious issue for the courts to decide,'' said MTA
spokesman Tito Davila.
   The lawsuit seeks a court order barring the MTA from enforcing
the ban on panhandling. A hearing is scheduled Friday before Judge
Leonard Sand.
</TEXT>
