<HEAD>Police Officer Finds Bomb Under Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army experts safely defused a
bomb a police inspector found under his car Wednesday, the Royal
Ulster Constabulary said.
   The bomb contained one pound of a plastic explosive, a police
spokesman said, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   The inspector, who was not identified, found the bomb during a
routine search of his car that all police officers are supposed to
make before driving.
   No group claimed responsibility for planting the bomb.
   In nearby Lisburn, 37 families were evacuated from their homes
Wednesday while army experts defused a bomb found in a hijacked
taxi, police said.
   A spokesman said police received a telephone call from someone
claiming to be a member of the Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed
Protestant group, alerting them to the bomb.
   The bomb contained a small quantity of explosives, he said.
