<HEAD>Soviets Producing Special Summit Watch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A watch factory that produces a popular timepiece
called the ``Slava'' _ coincidentally the name of the Soviet
warship to be used in the Malta summit _ is manufacturing a
commemorative watch.
   A small number of the watches were being sent to Malta to be
handed out as souvenirs to participants in the summit meeting
aboard Soviet and U.S. ships off the Mediterranean island of Malta,
the government newspaper Izvestia said.
   Moscow's Watch Factory No. 2 also is manufacturing a larger
number of various Slava watches to be sold in allied countries,
Italy, the United States, France, Singapore and other countries.
   The center of the watch, shown in a picture in the newspaper,
displayes the blue and white flag of the Soviet navy.
   Soviet watches, including those made by the Moscow factory, have
become a popular fashion item in many Western countries, including
Italy.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev began a visit to Italy on
Wednesday that precedes the two-day summit meeting off Malta with
President Bush. Gorbachev will have one day of meetings with Bush
on the Soviet warship Slava.
