<HEAD>Search Moves Farther Out to Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard rescuers searching for five lobstermen
moved farther out to sea Wednesday following a trail of distress
flares that appeared two nights in a row.
   Three aircraft and two cutters were searching a
10,000-square-mile area about 270 miles southeast of Nantucket,
Coast Guard spokesman Steven Aitkins said.
   The rescuers shifted their search after spotting a flare Tuesday
night about 60 miles east of where a flare was seen the night
before, Aitkins said.
   Coast Guard officials were not discounting the possibility that
the flares came from different sources, Aitkins said, adding, ``We
didn't find an origin for either one.''
   The last transmission of the 72-foot Heidi Marie, out of
Stonington, Conn., was Nov. 21.
   Since then, the Coast Guard has found the boat's emergency
signal device and other debris, but no other sign of the crew.
