<DOCNO> AP891129-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Summit-Bush 5thLd-Writethru a0622 11-29 0962</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Bush, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0622,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Deletes repetitive pvs grafs 14-15, He stressed ... instability;
minor editing elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
today the United States and Soviet Union should seek ``mutual
advantage'' from the dramatic changes in Eastern Europe, and hinted
that President Bush would back improved Soviet trade opportunities
at this weekend's superpower summit.
   At the same time, Baker said the two days of talks between Bush
and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev are ``not an arms control
summit.''
   At a White House news conference on the day before Bush's
departure for a shipboard summit off Malta, Baker also said the
continued flow of Soviet-made arms to leftist rebels in El Salvador
and the Afghanistan government amounted to a ``Cold War relic.''
   He stressed in a prepared statement and in reply to questions
that U.S.-Soviet relations were on the upswing, and that U.S.
support for Gorbachev's perestroika, or restructuring, program to
reform the Soviet economy was firm.
   Baker said it would be a mistake not to support the reform
movement sweeping the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe even if there
is a chance the pace may bring some temporary instability.
   ``The real question is not whether perestroika will succeed or
fail,'' he said. ``The real question is this: Do you engage the
Soviet Union in a search for mutual advantage in this time of
uncertainty. And our answer to that question is a resounding
`yes.'''
   Hardline Communist governments have been removed from power in
recent weeks in East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria, in
addition to the changes that moved through Poland and Hungary
earlier in the year.
   Gorbachev has expressed fears that the changes within the Soviet
bloc would be exploited by the West. But in a nationally televised
speech last Wednesday night, Bush offered ``our assurance that
America welcomes reform, not as an adversary seeking advantage but
as a people offering support.''
   Baker broadly hinted that Bush would offer to support Soviet
participation in the international group known as GATT _ the
General Agrement on Tariffs and Trade _ that would make it easier
for the Soviets to trade with other countries.
   Baker said the issue definitely was on the president's summit
agenda, but he did not want to pre-empt Bush's discussion with
Gorbachev. And he said the success or failure of the summit
depended on no single issue.
   Baker spoke as Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said the
Bush administration needs ``a more meaningful response'' to the new
political climate in the Soviet Union and urged the president to
press for movement on trade and arms control at the summit.
   ``While I welcome the administration's offer to provide
technical advice to the Soviet Union, I believe a more meaningful
response is necessary,'' the Maine Democrat told a news conference.
He again called for a trial waiver of trade restrictions aimed at
the Soviets under the so-called Jackson-Vanik amendment.
   Baker used his pre-summit appearance before reporters to take a
hard line on Central America, and to rule out a deal in which the
United States would cut off its assistance to rebels in Afghanistan.
   Baker's remarks about El Salvador, where rebels recently renewed
their offense against the government, and Soviet support for
Afghanistan and Cambodia contrasted with an otherwise warm stance
toward Moscow.
   Baker said Soviet behavior in regional conflicts contrasts
sharply with the pattern of its conduct in Eastern Europe.
   ``The continuing pattern of Soviet arms shipments to Moscow's
Third World clients is especially disturbing ... This pattern is a
Cold War relic,'' he said.
   Baker said that if Gorbachev can promote perestroika and foster
new thinking in Eastern Europe, he can also stop ``throwing fuel on
the fire'' in El Salvador.
   Baker spoke as sources said the U.S. budget squeeze may force
Bush to confront a proposed armed forces cutback even as he
reassures the allies he will not cut a military deal with Gorbachev
behind their backs at the summit.
   On Bush's desk before his takeoff Thursday evening for the
Mediterranean could be a recommendation from Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney to trim the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps by
275,000, or 12.9 percent from current levels, defense sources told
The Associated Press on Tuesday night.
   The Army would be reduced by 135,000, the Air Force by 100,000
and the Navy and Marine Corps by 40,000 under a proposal from the
U.S. armed services chiefs, said the sources, who declined to be
identified.
   Cheney will find the recommendation on his own desk when he
flies home from Europe early Thursday. The cuts would be carried
out by 1994, and would involve the elimination of three army combat
divisions, five and a fraction Air Force fighter wings and about 60
naval vessels, the sources said.
   The fleet includes 562 vessels, and the idea would be to reduce
to about 500 by 1994.
   If Cheney accepts the recommendation, he would take it to the
president before his departure for the summit. Richard Darman, the
director of the Office of Management and Budget, is pushing for
even deeper cutbacks in the U.S. military, the sources said.
   It was not clear whether the president would make a decision
before his takeoff, and White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
declined comment today on the matter.
   He said the president planned to spend most of the day in
preparation for the summit, and would also discuss the summit at
some length at a private dinner at the White House tonight for
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   The spokesman also said that Bush had discussed the summit today
by phone with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. They also
discussed Kohl's new proposal for the reunification of Germany, the
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
