<FIRST>r w AM-Summit-Mitchell     11-29 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Mitchell,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Leader Urges `More Meaningful Response' to Gorbachev'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell on
Wednesday said the Bush administration needs ``a more meaningful
response'' to the new political climate in the Soviet Union and
urged the president to press for movement on trade and arms control
at the summit.
   ``While I welcome the administration's offer to provide
technical advice to the Soviet Union, I believe a more meaningful
response is necessary,'' Mitchell told a news conference. He again
called for a trial waiver of trade restrictions.
   Mitchell said the ``American people are united in support of
President Bush as he travels to this important meeting.'' And he
added that Bush was right in his approach concerning possible
discussion of arms control and military forces with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the summit off Malta.
   He expressed hope that Bush would reaffirm his commitment to a
START treaty.
   Mitchell said the administration should say clearly it will
abide by the 1972 ABM treaty and ``abandon the view that it can
reserve the right to unilaterally change the terms of a treaty
limiting strategic defenses while seeking to conclude a binding
agreement limiting strategic offenses.''
   He said that ``concluding the current conventional negotiations
under way in Vienna has assumed even greater importance in light of
the changes taking place in Eastern Europe.''
   On trade, Mitchell said the Bush administration should forget
its offer to provide technical assistance to the Soviets. ``They've
not requested that,'' Mitchell said.
   ``But we should demonstrate our willingness to move toward a
trade relationship based on market principles rather than political
proscriptions,'' Mitchell said.
   He reiterated his suggestion of last May that the administration
should grant a trial waiver of the Jackson-Vanik amendment, which
restricts trade with the Soviets to bring pressure on Moscow for
freer emigration policies.
   He said Moscow's loosening of emigration curbs over the last few
years justifies such a move.
   Mitchell also urged Bush to propose talks aimed at reaching a
commercial trade agreement with the Soviet Union.
   He said in response to a question that such an agreement would
not result in any quick upturn in imports from the Soviet Union.
``The reason is very simple. There's very little produced in the
Soviet Union that Americans would be interested in buying. They do
not have a competitive economy and I think they realize this.''
   Meanwhile, 15 senators urged Bush to raise the issue of
political rights of Baltic peoples at the summit.
   ``This is of vital importance to the safety and security of both
of our nations, as well as to our allies in Europe,'' said a
statement issued by the office of Sen. Robert Kasten, R-Wis.
   The lawmakers called on Bush to tell Gorbachev that economic
assistance and trade with the United States must be linked with
progress toward democracy in the Baltic states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
