<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Park     11-29 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Park,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Parks Legislation for Colorado, Iowa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Wednesday
clearing the way for expansion of the Rocky Mountain National Park
in Colorado and helping create an interpretive center for three
national historic trails in Council Bluffs, Iowa.
   Part of the 515 acres being added to the park are a migratory
route to winter ranges for deer and elk. Some of the land had been
eyed for a housing development. Other portions now lie within the
Roosevelt National Forest, which will cede the land to the Rocky
Mountain National Park.
   The government expects the 515 acres to be donated for the
265,000-acre park 65 miles north of Denver, which draws 3 million
visitors annually.
   A separate measure signed by Bush authorizes federal help of up
to $8.4 million to develop the interpretive center in Council
Bluffs near the Lewis and Clark, Oregon and Mormon Pioneer trails.
   The legislation requires that every $2 in federal funds be
matched with $1 in non-federal funds. The Bush administration had
opposed federal participation in building the center, which will
not be located on a historic site. No funds have yet been
appropriated to carry out the plans.
   Bush signed both bills without comment.
</TEXT>
