<FIRST>u a PM-Navajos-MacDonald 1stLd-Writethru a0459 11-29 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0459,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Navajo Chairman Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with innocent plea; PICKS UP 10th
graf pvs, `Prosecutors said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter MacDonald, suspended chairman of the Navajo
tribe, pleaded innocent to corruption charges today in tribal court.
   The 60-year-old leader of the nation's biggest Indian tribe was
charged Oct. 11 by special prosecutors hired by the tribe with 107
offenses, including conspiracy, bribery, fraud, extortion and
election-law violations.
   MacDonald, who was suspended by the Navajo Tribal Council three
months ago, also is the target of a federal grand jury
investigation and a defendant in a multimillion-dollar lawsuit
filed by the 225,000-member tribe.
   The lawsuit and the bulk of the criminal charges focus on the
tribe's purchase of an Arizona ranch for $7.2 million more than the
sellers had paid for it hours earlier.
   The tribe's prosecutors also filed charges against the suspended
vice chairman, Johnnie R. Thompson, and MacDonald's son, Peter
MacDonald Jr. Thompson has pleaded innocent to 15 election-law
violations; the younger MacDonald was to be arraigned later today.
   MacDonald, who three years ago was inaugurated for a fourth term
in a lavish ceremony attended by dignitaries in rented limousines,
is pleading poverty and has asked for a court-appointed defense
attorney.
   On Monday, Tribal Judge Robert Yazzie rejected the request,
saying MacDonald is ``far better off financially than all but a
handful of Navajos,'' but gave MacDonald until today to provide
more evidence that he's indigent.
   McDonald appeared at his arraignment today without an attorney
and did not press his request. ``I'm still in the process of trying
to retain counsel. ... I can find one,'' he told Yazzie as the
arraignment began.
   Prosecutors said MacDonald has a net worth of more than $400,000
in addition to the $55,000 annual salary he still draws while on
paid administrative leave.
   Allegations emerged in testimony before a special U.S. Senate
committee in January that MacDonald personally profited from the
tribe's 1987 purchase of the 491,000-acre Big Boquillas Ranch.
   The tribe paid Byron T. Brown and K. Tom Tracey, two longtime
friends of MacDonald, $33.4 million for the ranch soon after they
had purchased it for $26.2 million.
   Brown told the Senate panel that MacDonald received $50,000 plus
vacation trips and lease of a BMW automobile.
   In August, the tribe filed a $24 million lawsuit in state court
against MacDonald and others over the ranch purchase. Meanwhile, a
federal grand jury investigation has been under way for at least a
year.
   MacDonald has strongly denied the allegations.
   At a news conference the day after the complaint was filed,
MacDonald promised to ``stand up and fight.'' He reiterated his
contention that the federal government wanted to oust him and other
strong Indian leaders so it could have easier access to minerals
and other natural resources on reservations.
   Attempts to reach MacDonald on Tuesday were unsuccessful. His
Flagstaff residence has an unlisted telephone.
   MacDonald was acquitted of federal fraud and income tax evasion
charges in 1977, six years after he began his first term as
chairman. He lost a re-election bid to Peterson Zah in 1982 but
regained the office with a 750-vote victory over Zah four years
later.
   His latest problems began after the U.S. Senate Select Committee
on Indian Affairs' hearings on his financial dealings.
   Several witnesses, including his son, testified that bribes and
kickbacks were an accepted way of doing business on the Navajo
Reservation.
   A month later, he was placed on administrative leave by the
88-member Tribal Council.
   Sporadic violence followed, culminating in a July clash between
police and about 300 club-wielding MacDonald supporters in Window
Rock. Tribal police shot and killed two of MacDonald's supporters,
and nine other people were injured.
   Leonard Haskie, the interim tribal chairman, blamed MacDonald
for the violence, saying he could have prevented it had he wanted.
MacDonald, however, blamed the police, saying they overreacted to a
peaceful demonstration by his supporters.
</TEXT>
