<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Zambia-University     11-29 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Zambia-University,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second University Closed After Violent Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KITWE, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of students packed their
belongings and left campus Wednesday after authorities closed
Copperbelt University to end violent protests, the second school to
close in Zambia this month.
   Students were ordered to leave the university in Kitwe, 225
miles north of Lusaka, by nightfall, campus officials said.
   Students were expected to return after the Christmas vacation, a
campus spokesman said.
   The decision to shut down the campus ahead of the vacation came
after several days of unrest in which students stoned cars and
buildings and assaulted teaching staff to protest low food
allowances, said the spokesman.
   On Monday, rampaging students dragged vice chancellor Mubanga
Kashoki from his office and forced him to stand on the roof of his
car and address protesters gathered in a parking lot.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   The students demanded that their food allowances of about $166 a
term be more than doubled to match allowances received by privately
sponsored students.
   Zambia's main university campus in Lusaka was closed Nov. 23
after 3,000 state-sponsored students looted food stores and
boycotted class.
</TEXT>
