<FIRST>u a PM-RandyKraft     11-29 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Randy Kraft,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer of 16 Men Sentenced to Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Kraft was sentenced to the gas
chamber today for strangling 16 young men during a 12-year spree of
sexual torture and mutilation.
   ``Burn in hell, Kraft!'' one of the victims' relatives shouted
as Kraft was led from court. ``Turn around and look!'' the relative
shouted.
   The 44-year-old Long Beach computer consultant was convicted of
murder in May after a 10{-month trial. In August the jury
recommended the death penalty, and Superior Court Judge Donald A.
McCartin today agreed.
   The judge recounted one of Kraft's slayings, which included
cigarette lighter torture, castration and mutilation, and said, `If
anyone ever deserved the death penalty, he's got it coming.''
   Kraft was convicted of murders that occurred between 1972 and
1983. Prosecutors said he picked up hitchhikers, gave them drugs
and alcohol, sexually tortured or mutilated them and then strangled
them.
   The bodies were dumped along roads, frequently from a moving car.
   Highway Patrol officers arrested Kraft in 1983 after pulling him
over for erratic driving and discovering a strangled Marine in his
car.
   The courtroom was full of victims' relatives, who cried and
hugged when it became apparent the death penalty would be imposed.
Kraft remained calm throughout the proceeding, playing with a pen
cap, yawning, laughing and chatting with his attorney.
   Kraft after sentencing addressed the judge, saying only, ``I
have not murdered anyone and I believe a reasonable review of the
record will show that.''
</TEXT>
