<FIRST>r w AM-BaseClosings     11-29 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Commission Overestimated Savings from Base Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal commission overestimated the annual
savings from closing or realigning 15 military bases, but the
eventual amount still will be considerable, a congressional agency
said Wednesday.
   The General Accounting Office said that based on revised and
updated data it found that the annual savings from shutting down or
scaling back the 15 bases amounted to $453.4 million _ about $170
million less the $622.9 million the commission estimated.
   ``But still a substantial annual savings,'' the GAO said.
   The congressionally established Commission on Base Realignment
and Closure recommended in January closing a total of 86 military
bases and scaling back five more, a proposal accepted by
then-Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   Despite overwhelming support in Congress for the plan, a number
of lawmakers questioned the commission's methodology and complained
that its findings were based on faulty data.
   Members asked this past summer that the GAO, the investigative
arm of Congress, review the commission's work on 15 bases slated
for closure or realignment, including the Presidio in California,
Fort Dix in New Jersey and Chanute Air Force Base in Illinois.
   The GAO, in its report, said the commission overestimated the
savings at the 15 bases because of ``data errors, inaccurate
estimates and the exclusion of certain relevant costs.''
   Specifically, at the Jefferson Proving Ground in Indiana, the
commission did not calculate the cost of cleaning up munitions at
the facility. The panel estimated annual savings of $6.6 million at
the base and six years to recover the closure costs.
   But the GAO said that it could take anywhere from 38 to more
than 200 years to recover the expense of closing Jefferson Proving
Ground. The GAO also estimated savings at $6.3 million annually.
   The GAO recommended that Defense Secretary Dick Cheney closely
monitor the closing and realignment of the bases, which are to be
completed by Sept. 30, 1995.
   The GAO said the Department of Defense provided oral comments on
a draft of the report which generally agreed with the agency's
findings, although it estimated that the annual savings from the 15
bases will be about $522 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
