<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Lenin     11-29 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Lenin,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowd Attacks Lenin Monument at Nowa Huta</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and water cannon to
force back hundreds of young demonstrators Wednesday who attacked
the towering monument to Vladimir I. Lenin at Nowa Huta in southern
Poland, state media reported.
   The demonstration, called by the radical Movement for an
Alternative Society, targeted the statue that dominates a square in
Nowa Huta, an industrial city of 220,000 people built outside
Krakow in the 1950s to be a model workers' community.
   According to state TV and the official PAP news agency, the
demonstrators used metal bars and hacksaws to begin dismantling
barriers surrounding the monument to the founder of the Soviet
state before police intervened.
   Demonstrators shouted chants calling for dismantling the
monument and the removal of the estimated 40,000 Soviet troops in
Poland.
   The protesters finally dispersed after pleas for moderation from
Solidarity parliament Deputy Edward Nowak, who promised to propose
dismantling of the monument to parliament Thursday, state TV said.
   The 33-foot-tall statue long has been a hated symbol of Soviet
domination in the city, a Solidarity stronghold which until 1977
was denied the right to have its own Roman Catholic Church.
   Last week, demonstrators splashed paint on the statue and tried
to set it ablaze.
   In 1979, worker activists dynamited the statue, blowing off one
of its legs. It was quickly repaired by communist officials and
several people were imprisoned in the attack.
   The attempt to dismantle Lenin's statue follows the officially
sanctioned dismantling of another hated symbol, a monument in
Warsaw to Felix Dzerzhinsky, the founder of the Soviet secret
police, on Nov. 17.
   City officials agreed to the dismantling of the statue and the
renaming of Dzerzhinski Square where it stood, saying the statue's
removal was needed in connection with subway construction work.
   The Solidarity-led government has sought to maintain friendly
relations with the Soviet Union, including a trip to Moscow last
week by Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki. He has condemned
outbreaks of anti-Soviet vandalism.
   But his government has stressed that Poland is a sovereign
country and must no longer be dominated by its larger neighbor.
</TEXT>
