<FIRST>r w AM-Satellite'sDemise     11-29 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellite's Demise,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Expected to Crash Through Atmosphere Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solar Maximum satellite, responding
increasingly to Earth's pull, dropped 7.5 miles in 24 hours and is
expected to crash through the atmosphere about 1:49 a.m. EST on
Saturday, NASA said Wednesday.
   The U.S. Space Command in Colorado, which tracks objects in
space, said it did not know where on the globe the 10-year-old
satellite might fall because a few minutes one way or another can
mean hundreds of miles. The impact point will be estimated more
closely as the time of the satellite's demise comes nearer.
   Solar Max has been studying the sun since it was launched in
February 1980. It ran out of fuel recently and began tumbling out
of control. NASA jettisoned its solar panels last week, depriving
the satellite of power.
   The 5,000-pound spacecraft will be mostly destroyed by fire, but
some larger pieces may survive and fall in chunks to Earth.
</TEXT>
