<HEAD>Mistrial Denied as Defense Loses Witnesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge refused to grant a mistrial
Wednesday in a state anti-pollution lawsuit against Amtrak after
the defense said all of its witnesses would invoke the Fifth
Amendment protection against self-incrimination.
   Circuit Judge Robert Perry gave Amtrak attorney Edward Booth
until Thursday morning to find substitute witnesses. The lawyer
said he plans to rest his case if no one else can be found.
   Amtrak faces four counts of commercial littering for human waste
allegedly flushed from trains into the St. Johns River and Rice
Creek. A couple fishing under a trestle also testified they were
sprayed.
