<FIRST>r a AM-EversProbe     11-29 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evers Probe,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Judge Says No to Prosecutors Wanting to Look at Commission Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to open
records of the state's defunct segregation spy agency to allow a
prosecutor to examine reports about the 1963 assassination of NAACP
leader Medgar Evers.
   Hinds County District Attorney Ed Peters is trying to decide if
Byron de La Beckwith, whose first two trials on charges of killing
Evers ended in mistrials, should be tried again.
   In an order made public Tuesday, U.S. District Judge William H.
Barbour Jr. ruled it would be premature to grant prosecutors access
to the closed records of the state Sovereignty Commission.
   Peters sought access to the records to determine if there was
jury tampering in the two 1964 trials of Beckwith, a former
Greenwood fertilizer salesman accused of killing Evers. Beckwith
now lives in Tennessee.
   Mistrials were declared in both trials when all-white Hinds
County juries failed to reach verdicts.
   A Hinds County grand jury that meets Dec. 11 is expected to
explore whether to bring new charges.
   ``The decision of the district attorney as to whether to try
Beckwith again should be based on whether he thinks the evidence
available to him at this time is sufficient to obtain a
conviction,'' Barbour wrote in the new ruling. Barbour also wrote
that evidence of jury tampering would not be admissible in any new
murder trial.
   The Sovereignty Commission, created by the 1956 Legislature,
infiltrated and harassed civil rights groups. It went out of
existence in 1973 when its funding was cut off.
   The 1977 Legislature sealed the agency's records until 2027.
Barbour ruled July 27 the records should be open to the public, but
allowed them to remain sealed pending appeals to the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Published reports have been that the commission screened
potential jurors before Beckwith's second trial in April 1964.
   Evers was shot to death outside his Jackson home June 12, 1963.
Beckwith's rifle was found nearby and one of his fingerprints was
on the rifle sight, but Beckwith testified the gun had been stolen
from him.
   Barbour said he might later reconsider Peters' request for the
records.
   ``The district attorney argues that if he attempts to retry
Beckwith, that Beckwith will argue that such retrial would be
barred by his constitutional right to a speedy trial,'' Barbour
wrote.
   While prosecutors plan to respond that proof of jury tampering
would make it possible to retry the case, the judge wrote, ``this
argument is premature and may be renewed if the district attorney
decides to retry Beckwith and if Beckwith raises the speedy trial
issue.''
</TEXT>
