<FIRST>r a AM-ElephantRoundup     11-29 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elephant Roundup,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Agents Roundup, Haul Off Two Stolen Elephants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A posse of FBI agents has rounded up two
adult Asian elephants allegedly stolen in New Jersey more than five
years ago by a man who insists he repossessed the animals for
non-payment and animal abuse.
   FBI spokesman Norm Middleton said Tuesday the agents seized the
elephants Monday at a farm where circus animals are trained and
boarded.
   Civil action involving the elephants is pending in federal court
here, Middleton said.
   Arlan Seidon, 60, was arrested in October by Marion County
deputies and is fighting extradition to New Jersey. He is free on
$20,000 bond.
   FBI agent Mike Santimauro in Dallas said the elephants weren't
seized until this week because authorities didn't know where they
were.
   Seidon says he repossessed the elephants in 1984 after a dispute
with two men who bought them from him in 1981. Seidon claimed the
buyers mistreated the animals and fell behind on their payments.
   Seidon was arrested after he was tracked down by one of the men,
Richard Drake, who has said he has spent thousands of dollars
searching for Seidon and the elephants around the country.
   Seidon sold the elephants, Tory and Duchess, to Drake and his
son, Edward, who owned a now-closed exotic-animal ranch in
Tehachapi, Calif., in 1981 for $80,000.
   A judge in Monmouth County, N.J., in 1984 ordered Seidon to
return the 7-foot-tall elephants. Instead, Seidon fled with them in
a truck and hid them.
   The Drakes denied abusing the animals.
   Seidon has said he raised the animals, now in their late 20s,
from infancy. He told a newspaper in 1988 that he left his
Fordland, Mo., farm and his career preparing animals for circus and
television appearances to care for the elephants. He also said he
hadn't seen his four children or met his grandson since he took off
with the animals.
   Middleton declined to say where the elephants were taken after
the roundup, but said they are somewhere in eastern Texas.
   Seidon faces charges of theft in New Jersey. If convicted he
would face up to five years in prison and a $100,000 fine.
</TEXT>
