<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     11-29 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Masked Palestinians Shot to Death by Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed two masked
Palestinians who were throwing stones at Israeli cars Wednesday,
the army said.
   The men reportedly were stoning the cars on the main highway
between Jerusalem and Ramallah in the occupied West Bank. They
started to run after soldiers arrived and ordered them to halt, the
army said.
   ``The soldiers then opened fire according to standing
regulations, and as a result two were killed,'' said an army
spokesman, who cannot be identified under military regulations.
   Their deaths raised to 619 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli soldiers or civilians during the nearly 2-year-old uprising
against Israeli rule in the occupied territories. At least 151
others have been slain by fellow Arabs as suspected collaborators.
Forty-two Israelis have also been killed.
   In the Gaza Strip, 16 Arabs were wounded from army gunfire as
Palestinians in the occupied territories observed a general strike
to mark the anniversary of the U.N. vote to partition Palestine,
Arab reports said.
   The Palestinians, ranging in age from 8 to 28, were shot with
live and plastic bullets during stone-throwing clashes with Israeli
soldiers, Arab reports said. Most of the wounded were shot in the
legs.
   The army said it had no reports of any Arabs wounded but that
two Israeli soldiers were slightly injured by stones thrown at them.
   The army also said it sealed two houses in the Gaza Strip
belonging to families of men accused of helping kill Palestinians
suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   In the West Bank, soldiers found two metal pipes with explosives
and detonators near the city of Tulkarm. One bomb was blown up by
soldiers and the other fell apart, according to Israeli reports.
   The strike, called by leaders of the Palestinian uprising,
marked the 42nd anniversary of the U.N. General Assembly's vote to
partition Palestine into separate Jewish and Arab states, which led
to Israel's creation less than a year later.
   Workers in the occupied territories stayed home, merchants
closed their shops and public transportation ground to a halt, Arab
reports said.
   General strikes have been a frequent protest tactic in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which were captured from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East War.
   Twenty-five people lived in the nine-room house that was sealed
in Gaza City. In nearby Beach Camp, 17 people lived in the
five-room house sealed by Israeli soldiers. Each had a family
member suspected of helping kill an accused collaborator with
Israel.
   Israeli military authorities have destroyed 244 Palestinian
homes and sealed 116 others since the start of the uprising, army
figures show.
   International human rights groups have condemned the moves as
harsh and drastic measures that have failed as a deterrent.
</TEXT>
