<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-29 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TARENTUM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iva Mae Long's hobby has a nice ring to it
_ 20,000 rings that is.
   She collects bells, and her home in West Deer Township, 20 miles
north of Pittsburgh, is brimming with them.
   ``I do have a lot of bells,'' said Mrs. Long.
   That's an understatement.
   By her own estimate, about 20,000 bells fill every nook and
cranny in her home, which she calls Bell Haven. A 2,200-pound bell
is displayed in the front yard, and other bells adorn her front and
back porches, gazebo and driveway.
   ``It's the largest collection in the world,'' said Louise
Collins of Natrona Heights, another collector and former editor of
Bell Tower, the publication that connects 2,600 members of American
Bell Association International, Inc.
   Mrs. Long said bell collecting is contagious, and her children
and grandchildren have caught the bug.
   ``Touch one or two and first thing you know, you're a
bell-a-holic,'' she said.
   Mrs. Long caught the bug from her father and inherited his
collection, although she had started her own many years before he
died.
   She finds bells at auctions, in shops and trades with other
collectors.
   Among her most unusual pieces are a set shaped like a man and a
woman. The man nods no, and the woman nods yes. She has three
bells, dating between 1828 and 1862, from the locks of the old
Pennsylvania canal.
   An 1869 ``Wedding of the Rails'' bell commemorates the opening
of the transcontinental railroad. Other bells resemble figures of
famous people including Edgar Allen Poe and Friar Tuck.
   She can't resist collecting. ``After all, a bell is the only
thing in the house that thanks you for dusting it _ it rings,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Milwaukee policeman received a $500,000
check from the city of Mobile, but quickly discovered the wealth
was fleeting.
   A city computer error sent the check to Blue Knight Publishing
Co., a home-operated business run by John Karlovich and his wife,
Ann, when it was supposed to go to Blue Cross to cover insurance
payments.
   The city once purchased a book from the Wisconsin couple, so
their company was in the computer's list of vendors.
   ``Once the checks come off the printer they're folded and mailed
automatically,'' said investment officer Arthur Barnes. ``The error
was discovered that afternoon, but the check was in the mail.''
   Barnes telephoned Karlovich.
   ``I just want to look at all those zeros some more before I send
it back,'' Karlovich said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
