<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Mbeki     11-29 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Mbeki,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC's Mbeki Gets Honorary Degree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Govan Mbeki received an honorary
doctorate degree from the University of the Western Cape on
Wednesday, the first leader of the outlawed African National
Congress to be so honored in South Africa.
   ``We live in exciting and disturbing times when much of the
world seems to be in the process of renewal,'' Mbeki said after
receiving the philosophy doctorate from the university's
chancellor, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   ``We are fortunate that this happens on the eve of our own
liberation,'' Mbeki said. South Africa should ``draw on the
experiences of other countries and tap the African experience so
that what we build does not repeat the mistakes that the sister
peoples on our continent have made,'' he added.
   Although he argued that capitalism was the foundation for
apartheid, Mbeki challenged the view ``expressed in some circles
that genuine democracy would result in the masses descending on the
economy like a swarm of rapacious locusts, eating up everything in
their path without regard to the vital question of persuing an
economic policy that would guarantee growth and development.''
   Mbeki's imprisoned colleague, Nelson Mandela, sent a message of
congratulations that was read by his wife, Winnie.
   ``This is the first time a South African University will honor a
red-hot freedom fighter who has spent years in prison and has
emerged from that harsh experience with his convictions
unscathed,'' the message said.
   Mrs. Mandela received a standing ovation from the audience of
about 1,000 as she took the stage to read her husband's words.
Earlier this year, black anti-apartheid leaders had distanced
themselves from Mrs. Mandela, accusing her of complicity in the
death of a teen-age activist and her bodyguards of conducting a
``reign of terror'' in the Johannesburg township of Soweto.
   Since the men imprisoned for life with her husband in 1964 were
freed last month, she had made several appearances with them.
Mandela is the only one of the group still imprisoned for sabotage
and plotting to overthrow the government.
   Mbeki, 79, was freed in 1987 after 24 years in jail. After
holding two news conferences, at which he declared he believed in
the actions for which he was sentenced and remained a member of the
outlawed ANC and the South African Communist Party, he was
prohibited from making public appearances or statements until his
restrictions were lifted last month.
   Mbeki, the son of a Xhosa tribal chief, earned university
degrees in education and economics before he helped found the ANC's
military wing. He worked as a teacher, journalist, store owner and
union organizer. While in prison, he earned an advanced degree in
economics by correspondence course and was awarded an honorary
doctorate in social science by the University of Amsterdam for his
book, ``The Peasant Revolt.''
</TEXT>
