<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Corruption     11-29 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Corruption,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Say Former Premier Lived in Luxury</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the latest disclosure of alleged
corruption in the top Communist ranks, newspapers Wednesday said
that the former premier of East Germany turned a park into a
private estate.
   The Communist leadership that took over last month has launched
a campaign to expose abuses by former party officials, who could
face prosecution. The aim is to improve the embattled party's image
and restore its credibility.
   The official Communist Party newspaper Neues Deutschland
reported that Willi Stoph, the former premier, lived ``surrounded
by Western luxury'' on an estate containing several houses, fruit
plantations and an indoor pool. He employed servants, including
three gardeners, the newspaper said.
   Stoph, who was fired from the Politburo, resigned as premier on
Nov. 7.
   The trade union newspaper Tribuene said the estate was located
within a protected wildlife area on which Stoph built roads to
carry his family and guests in Volvo sedans ``when he didn't use a
helicopter.''
   The report said the estate contained more than 10 large
refrigerators filled with food imported from the West, along with
hundreds of bottles of the ``finest imported wine.''
   Stoph left the estate after he lost his posts, Neues Deutschland
said, ``taking his most beloved furniture and other things with a
truck.''
   Tribuene said the house looked ``like it had been left in
panic.''
   Neither newspaper gave Stoph's whereabouts.
   The party commission investigating corruption allegations said
Wednesday it will turn over its findings to judicial officials.
   The official news agency ADN said the commission recommended
that the party's Central Committee expel former non-voting
Politburo member Gerhard Mueller. The report did not elaborate.
   The agency also said three officials expelled from the party in
the 1950s had been rehabilitated, and that the expulsions of other
former leaders were being reviewed.
   Also on Wednesday, the Communist-dominated trade union
federation expelled former chief Harry Tisch. He was removed from
the ruling Politburo this month for allegedly abusing his powers.
   The lavish lifestyles of top party officials have been a major
source of discontent in a country where the average citizen has to
wait 10 years or more for a car.
   Since taking over from ousted hard-line leader Erich Honecker on
Oct. 18, Egon Krenz has begun a program of sweeping reforms that
includes promises of free elections and abolition of the
Communists' 40-year monopoly of power.
   Krenz himself has moved from the exclusive residential compound
of Wandlitz, just north of East Berlin, to a modest house in the
city.
   The wooded, walled-in compound has been home to high-ranking
Communist Party members. Tribuene said several former Politburo
members and two current ones still live in Wandlitz, but that it
would be turned into a rehabilitation center. Honecker is among
those still living in the compound.
   Neues Deutschland said the Communist Party had ordered that a
special shop in Wandlitz be emptied of rare Western-made consumer
goods, such as video recorders.
   The Communist party has blamed Honecker and former economy chief
Guenter Mittag for East Germany's economic crisis and has begun a
disciplinary investigation of them. Mittag already has been kicked
out of the party.
</TEXT>
