<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bice,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventor of First Internal Surgical Dressing Dies in Dallas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Claude W. Bice, a prominent nutrition
specialist and inventor of the first internal surgical dressing,
died at a Dallas hospital after a brief illness. He was 71.
   The funeral for Bice, who died Saturday, will be held Thursday
in Hayes, Kan. There also will be a memorial service Friday in
Gainesville.
   Bice, of Lake Kiowa, wrote more than 50 scientific papers
dealing with nutrition, research and food safety.
   In 1947, he received a patent for his internal surgical
dressing. He also received several other patents relating to food.
   Bice was principal research scientist for nutrition for
Frito-Lay Inc. in Irving from 1978 until his retirement in 1984.
   Survivors include his wife, Eileen J. Bice, a daughter and a son.
