<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Israel     11-29 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Israel,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peres Praises Poland for Offer to Help Move Convent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Vice Premier Shimon Peres praised
the Polish government on Wednesday for offering to help move a
Roman Catholic convent located on the edge of the Auschwitz
concentration camp.
   Peres said the government had offered land and financial support
to build a new convent for the Carmelite nuns living in an
abandoned theater used by the Nazis as a storehouse during World
War II.
   ``I appreciate the position taken by the Polish government,''
Peres said. ``I was told the Polish government offered land and
financial support and they expect the Catholic church to do the
rest.''
   The presence of the convent at the camp where up to 2.5 million
Jews were murdered by the Nazis is considered deeply offensive to
Jews and severely strained Jewish-Catholic relations.
   Tension mounted earlier this year when the Roman Catholic church
failed to honor a 1987 agreement to move the convent. Under
pressure from the Vatican, Primate Jozef Glemp in September pledged
to move the convent.
   ``I do not see why this Carmelite monastery should hang like a
cloud on our relations,'' Peres said.
   Peres visited the former concentration camp Wednesday on the
final day of a three-day visit to Poland during which Poland said
it would restore full diplomatic relations with Israel early next
year.
   Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski on Monday informed Peres
of Warsaw's decision to restore relations with Israel broken off 22
years ago.
   Peres also met with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and said he
had invited the union leader to Israel.
   Walesa told Peres, ``We should tighten our cooperation. Poland
is pursuing reforms. In these reforms your participation is
indispensable.''
   A major aim of Peres' visit was to improve economic cooperation.
Polish trade with Israel will amount to $40 million this year,
compared with $22.3 million last year.
   Walesa also evoked the common history of the two peoples who
existed together for centuries in Poland.
   ``Let us remember this was a country of two peoples. The war
destroyed the Jewish people and to this day we feel the shortage,''
Walesa said.
   Poland had the largest Jewish population in Eastern Europe until
the Holocaust claimed 3 million of Poland's 3.5 million Jews, with
nearly all the rest emigrating after World War II.
   There has been a steady warming in relations between the two
countries in recent years with senior Israeli and Polish officials,
cultural figures and private groups exchanging visits.
   Except for Romania, all Warsaw Pact nations severed diplomatic
relations with Israel following the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
