<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt   11-29 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Abortion, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Arguments on Abortion Parental-Notice Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court was asked Wednesday to rule
that most young girls have no right to abortions without first
telling their parents.
   The justices, who have allowed limits on the availability of
abortions for minors in the past, questioned lawyers defending and
attacking parental-notification laws in Minnesota and Ohio.
   In two hours of relatively narrow arguments, they gave no sign
they are considering the broader possibility of scrapping the
court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized abortion _ an
idea much discussed outside the court whenever they take up any
abortion case.
   ``The court showed no interest in overturning a woman's
constitutional right to abortion,'' Cleveland lawyer Linda Sogg
said after the argument session in which she attacked the Ohio law.
   Minnesota Chief Deputy Attorney General John Tunheim agreed. ``I
don't think Roe should be on the table in this case,'' he told
reporters after defending his state law before the court.
   Last July, the court voted 5-4 to give states more authority to
regulate abortions for all women. Four justices appeared ready to
go even further and overturn Roe vs. Wade, but Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor refused.
   Groups on both sides of the abortion issue had looked to the
court this term to help clarify its allegiance to the 1973 decision.
   But settlement of an Illinois dispute over regulating abortion
clinics _ a case that was to be argued before the justices next
month _ may have eliminated the greatest immediate threat to Roe
vs. Wade. The Illinois settlement still must be approved by a
federal judge.
   O'Connor is expected to play the pivotal role again in the
Minnesota and Ohio cases, to be decided by July. At issue in both
are laws requiring parents to be notified before abortions are
performed on unmarried girls under 18 who are still supported by
parents.
   About half the states have laws requiring parental notification
_ or even parental consent _ in such cases, but most of the laws
have been invalidated after court challenges.
   Nationwide, about 40 percent of the nearly 1 million teen-agers
who become pregnant each year seek abortions. Of the 1.5 million
legal abortions performed annually since 1973, about 12 percent _
180,000 a year _ have been for girls 17 and younger.
   The Ohio law requires that one of a minor's parents be notified
by a doctor at least 24 hours before an abortion is performed. The
girl can avoid telling her parent if she persuades a judge she is
mature enough to make the decision on her own, or that telling her
parents is not in her best interest.
   The Minnesota law requires that the minor's two biological
parents be notified at least 48 hours before she has an abortion. A
judicial bypass alternative also is provided.
   Both Tunheim, Minnesota's lawyer, and Ohio Assistant Attorney
General Rita Eppler argued that states do not have to provide a
judicial alternative in such cases. But because both states do
provide them, the court might not have to say.
   O'Connor, vigorously questioning Tunheim, seemed deeply troubled
by Minnesota's two-parent requirement.
   ``The statute just doesn't provide for any exceptions, even when
it's not in the child's best interest,'' O'Connor said. ``How do
you defend the state's interest'' in requiring both parents be
notified, she asked Tunheim.
   O'Connor also quizzed Ms. Eppler about that portion of the Ohio
law requiring a girl to prove her maturity by ``clear and
convincing evidence.'' O'Connor asked whether the standard might be
too stringent, resulting in a ``greater risk of erroneous
deprivation'' of a minor's abortion right.
   O'Connor never has said whether she believes such a right to
abortion _ for any woman _ exists.
   The court in 1981 allowed states to require parental
notification before minors' abortions, but the focus in that Utah
case was limited to how the state law was applied to ``immature''
minors.
   Ms. Eppler said the Ohio law ``represents no undue burden,'' and
properly balances a minor's rights with the need for parental
involvement ``when their daughter faces perhaps the most serious
dilemma of her young life.''
   But Ms. Sogg warned the court that ``not all parents are
loving.'' She said many girls seeking abortions need to be
protected from parental retaliation and abuse.
   The Minnesota law was in effect for five years before being
ruled unconstitutional by a federal judge. A federal appeals court
later ruled that the law is valid, but blocked its enforcement
pending Supreme Court action.
   The Ohio law, enacted in 1985, never took effect due to a
successful legal challenge by an Akron abortion clinic and one of
its doctors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
