<FIRST>r a AM-RomeoandJuliet     11-29 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romeo and Juliet,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thwarted Romance Involving Exchange Student Prompts Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 students walked out of class
in freezing weather to protest what they considered an attempt to
break up a relationship between an exchange student and a high
school senior.
   Kelly LaPointe, 17, and her boyfriend, Iiro Lehtinen, 18, of
Kiviniemi, Finland, were infuriated when exchange program officials
transferred Lehtinen to a school in Maine, saying the relationship
was hurting his grades.
   Lehtinen said he was given two hours' notice on Nov. 11 that he
was being moved from Farmington to live with a new host family in
South Portland, Maine, about 90 minutes away by car.
   ``I have been treated unfairly,'' Lehtinen told Foster's Daily
Democrat. ``I would be happier in Farmington.''
   Susan Jackson, program coordinator for the Education Foundation
for Foreign Study in New Hampshire and Maine, said Lehtinen was
moved because his grades began to drop and he was not spending
enough time with his host family.
   The host family has repeatedly refused to comment on the issue.
   Lehtinen said he had been given two weeks to break up with
LaPointe and was told he might be sent home if he continued to see
her.
   Jackson said the two were not told to break up, but that
Lehtinen had been told he was seeing too much of LaPointe and not
enough of his host family.
   As a show of support for the couple, about one-third of the
student body walked out of Farmington High School Monday when the 8
a.m. bell summoned the start of classes. They stood outside in
freezing weather for about a half-hour.
   No disciplinary measures were taken against the students,
LaPointe said.
   Principal Ken Beaupre said he would welcome Lehtinen back to the
school if the program moved the teen-ager back to town.
   Lehtinen said he appreciated the students' show of support. He
said his father in Finland has contacted the foundation, demanding
that he be returned to Farmington.
   South Portland High School, where he now is enrolled, has 1,200
students, compared to Farmington's 300. ``There is a different
climate here in terms of friendships,'' he said.
</TEXT>
