<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     11-29 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0443</SECOND>
<UNK>Armenians, Azerbaijanis Reject Karabakh Solution</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's latest bid to break a bitter
territorial dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan was met
Wednesday with demonstrations, strikes and angry criticism from
both sides.
   On the final day of its fall session Tuesday, the Supreme Soviet
parliament overwhelmingly approved a directive disbanding a special
commission that had imposed direct rule from Moscow on the disputed
Nagorno-Karabakh territory. The territory is located inside
Azerbaijan but the the majority of its population is Armenian.
   The decision appeared to give ultimate control over
Nagorno-Karabakh back to Azerbaijan. It ordered Azerbaijan
officials to work with reinstated local officials from
Nagorno-Karabakh to ensure law and order, economic and cultural
development in the region.
   It established a parliamentary oversight commission and said
that soldiers would remain in the region to ensure stability during
the transition.
   Officials of that commission have acknowledged that despite the
presence of Interior Ministry soldiers a virtual civil war has
raged there.
   The region's Armenian population, supported by the neighboring
Armenian republic, has demanding that it be annexed to Armenia
because of what it calls years of willful neglect by Azerbaijani
authorities.
   ``The whole resolution doesn't suit us,'' said Ektibar Mamedov,
a spokesman for the Azerbaijani People's Front Movement.
   Bobkin Arargetsyan, an Armenian activist, said the decision by
the Supreme Soviet parliament proved legislators ``can't make a
political decision based on the internationally recognized right of
self-determination.''
   Oleg Bakhshyan, a spokesman for the disbanded commission in
Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, said by telephone that
few people were happy with the decision.
   Activists from both sides said a general strike was under way in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Thousands of people gathered in the Armenian capital Yerevan on
Tuesday to protest the decision, said Arargetsyan, a member of
Armenia's Karabakh Committee. A joint meeting of the Armenian
Supreme Soviet legislature and Nagorno-Karabakh legislators was
scheduled Thursday, he said.
   In a continuation of the violence that has killed scores of
people since February 1988, Arargetsyan said a policeman was killed
in a border region between the two republics on Wednesday. He had
few details and the report could not be confirmed independently.
   Deputies from Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia walked out of the
Supreme Soviet session on Tuesday to protest the resolution, and
Arargetsyan said Armenian Communist Party official Golust Goloyan
appeared on local television Wednesday night to criticize the
Supreme Soviet's move.
   But Mamedov, the Azerbaijani activist, claimed that there was a
secret point to the agreement that prevents Azerbaijan from
interfering in the affairs of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   He predicted more violence in the mountainous region.
</TEXT>
