<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Press     11-29 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Press,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Says Media Restrictions to Be Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President F.W. de Klerk said
Wednesday the government is considering changing the 3-year-old
emergency restrictions on the press in a way that will address the
difficulties of journalists and editors as well as security
concerns.
   In a speech to the Johannesburg Press Club, de Klerk said the
government doesn't want to place any unneccessary obstacles in the
way of the press, because, he said, it has an important task to
perform in the debate on changing South Africa.
   He said the whole question of the national emergency was under
constant review and it would be lifted as soon as circumstances
permit.
   De Klerk had been expected to make a more substantive statement
on the emergency media regulations, which prohibit journalists from
covering or reporting on unrest events or security force action,
boycotts, strikes, statements the government considers subversive,
and detentions without trial. The restrictions are not uniformly
obeyed, and scores of journalists have been repeatedly arrested at
the scene of news events.
   Several newspapers have been closed without recourse to the
courts, and one, the New Nation, is under threat of a second
closure.
   One newspaper editor faces a prison sentence for violating the
emergency regulations by quoting a prohibited person.
   On Friday, the government-run South African Broadcasting Corp.
had given the strongest indication yet that some of the emergency
restrictions were about to be lifted.
   ``The lifting of media restrictions that are no longer relevant
in today's relaxed political climate will promote a more open
public debate on crucial national issues and bring the country
closer to more comprehensive and fruitful negotiations on a new
political and constitutional dispensation,'' it said in a
commentary.
   Former President P.W. Botha declared the national emergency on
June 12, 1986, and renewed the emergency restrictions in 1977,
1988, and 1989, saying they were necessary to control a situation
of political unrest in black townships. Botha was ousted in August,
and de Klerk became acting president before leading the National
Party government to a parliamentary victory in September.
   De Klerk already has modified the emergency regulations, by
allowing outdoor political rallies and marches, which had
previously routinely been broken up by police. The prohibition
remains on the books and can be invoked at any time, along with
bans on many forms of political expression, including wearing
T-shirts, displaying of banners and making certain speeches. The
punishment for violation of an emergency regulation is a maximum of
six months in prison or a $4,500 fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
