<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Jews     11-29 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Jews,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamic Radio Station Prevented From Broadcasting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents penultimate graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broadcasting board has suspended the license
of an Islamic radio station after its owner was convicted of
defaming Jews.
   The decision by the Swedish Local Radio Board occurred Tuesday
after Radio Islam's owner and leading broadcaster, Ahmed Rami, was
sentenced to six months in prison.
   A district court found him guilty of broadcasting ``disparaging
and deeply offending'' remarks about Jews and the Jewish religion
on his local station.
   Sweden's 15,000-member Jewish community has viewed it as a
landmark case. It is only the second time that a court has
overridden the right of free speech to enforce an anti-racism law
barring the defamation of a people, race or ethnic group.
   The court reached its verdict two weeks ago after an eight-week
trial. The prosecution called in distinguished clergymen to argue
that Rami's programs were anti-Semitic.
   Rami was convicted of 18 counts of broadcasting anti-Semitic
remarks, including quotes from Nazi writings such as Adolf Hitler's
``Mein Kampf.'' He has spoken on the air of a Jewish conspiracy to
achieve worldwide power.
   Rami, a Moroccan immigrant, has said he will appeal the court
sentence. His license would be returned if the Appeals Court
overturns the verdict.
   Rami had called the verdict ``a judicial murder, a scandal.'' He
said he had been judged in a political trial and accused the
prosecutor of ``Zionist sympathies.''
   ``I want to crush the state of Israel. ... If I am allowed on
the air again, I will say the same things again,'' he said.
``Zionism, Judaism and the state of Israel are fakes.''
    Radio Islam and about 2,500 independent companies or
individuals rent air time from the Local Radio Board. Radio Islam
had been broadcasting an hour a week.
</TEXT>
