<FIRST>r w AM-MedicareCare     11-29 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare Care,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Calls For Penalizing Poor Treatment For Medicare Patients</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee on Wednesday called for
stronger action against doctors and hospitals that provide
substandard care for Medicare patients.
   The House Government Operations Committee said that while
tougher laws are needed the Department of Health and Human Services
also must begin to use the broader authority Congress granted in
1985 to punish doctors and hospitals.
   A report by the panel criticized the department for the delay in
putting out regulations to enforce the law, which allows HHS to
deny payment hospitals and physicians in cases where substandard
care is provided.
   The department is working on the regulations, said Dennis
Siebert, a spokesman for the Health Care Financing Administration,
which handles Medicare, the government health-care program for 33
million elderly, blind and disabled Americans.
   ``They're fairly controversial and complex regulations,'' he
said. ``We've spent a lot of time consulting with medical care
industry.''
   Currently, physicians can be terminated from participating in
Medicare or be fined up to the amount of the care provided, but
only in cases where there has been a clear pattern of incompentence
by physicians who were ``unwilling or unable'' to improve their
treatment.
   The report said the standard that has to met is too stringent
because it allows physicians to escape punishment by agreeing to
taken an educational course to indicate their willingness to
improve. It also said the monetary penalty is too low.
   HHS Inspector General Richard Kusserow recommended that Congress
strengthen the standard and raise the fine to $10,000 per case.
   The report also estimated that more than 800,000 errors are made
each year by doctors and hospitals caring for Medicare patients,
mostly by releasing them too early.
   ``The large number of beneficiaries who may be at risk of
inadequate hospital-discharge planning is of special concern to the
committee due to fears that the PPS system (Medicare's system for
paying hospitals) ... is resulting in patients being discharged
faster and less stable,'' the report said.
   Eight Republicans on the 39-member committee, in an accompanying
document, cautioned that the error estimate was derived by
extrapolating from random reviews, called generic screens, which
were designed to detect potential problems. An error can result
from merely failing to sign a form in the proper place, they said.
   ``If an exhaustive look were taken at all generic screen
failures, we are convinced the number of quality problems would be
far below the committee report's projections,'' they said.
   The report said the prospective payment system, created in 1983
as a Medicare cost-saving measure, ``provides the greatest profits
to hospitals that give the shortest in-hospital care and the least
services.''
   Under the system, hospitals are paid a flat fee for each
treatment they provide. The fee assumes a certain length of
hospital stay and medical services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AgricultureSubsidies     11-29 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Subsidies,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study from Calif., Ark., Miss., La., Texas: Farmers Dodging Subsidy
Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attempts by Congress to keep farmers from
dodging a $50,000 limit on federal crop subsidies probably will
have little effect because farmers are creating new loopholes, the
Agriculture Department's watchdog agency said Wednesday.
   The department's Office of Inspector General said in a new audit
report that 1987 legislative changes are scheduled to take effect
this year and in 1990 for wheat, feed grains, rice, cotton, honey
and other price-supported commodities.
   But the 1987 legislation failed to effectively limit the use of
``multiple legal entities'' and other ways to avoid the payment
limitations, the report said.
   Federal crop ``deficiency'' payments used to make up part of the
difference between a low market price and some higher price target
are supposed to be limited to $50,000 per person. As an example,
last month's average corn price at the farm was $2.20 per bushel.
The target price for 1989 corn is $2.84. Farmers should get 64
cents per bushel from the government.
   ``However, our review determined that producers have found new,
innovative ways to reorganize farming operations so that 1989
payments will not be limited significantly by the legislative
changes,'' the report said.
   The audit report, which was provided upon request by The
Associated Press, followed one sent to Congress describing the
inspector general's activities for the six-month period that ended
on Sept. 30.
   In that review, the excessive crop subsidies were noted among a
number of abuses checked by investigators and auditors. The audit
report released on Wednesday dealt specifically with operations of
crop programs handled by the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service.
   The auditors checked five state offices of the agency and 14
county offices. In the counties, 822 of 7,424 farm operating plans
were selected for preliminary review. Finally, 52 farms were chosen
for in-depth analysis.
   The review of 52 farming operations identified 12 that
reorganized so that all entities _ which can be individuals,
corporations, associations, trusts or other legal entities _ could
continue receiving payments as ``persons'' under the program.
   ``For example, one operation we reviewed in Tunica, Miss.,
created 51 irrevocable trusts in 1989 so as not to have payments
reduced,'' the report said. ``The operation involved three joint
ventures (A, B and C) controlled by two intermingled families and
was determined (to include) 43 persons in 1988.''
   The 43 ``persons'' consisted of six individuals and 37
corporations, the report said. Owners of the 37 corporations
consisted of 11 individuals and one corporation.
   ``Seven of the individual owners were the immediate members of
the two families (a father and two daughters, and a father, two
sons, and a daughter) that controlled the operation,'' the report
said.
   If the complex arrangement had remained as it was in 1988, it
would have collected no more than $700,000 in payments in 1989. But
with reorganization, the operation is expected to collect as much
as $1,431,576 in subsidies this year.
   ``One of the family members of this organization told us that
the main purpose of the reorganization was to maintain the maximum
program benefits,'' the report said. ``He said it became a
challenge to see if he could get a trust established for all of the
operation's full-time employees. He called it a profit-sharing
plan.''
   Although the reorganization was allowed by current regulations,
auditors said the trusts themselves are believed to be
``flow-through entities'' to avoid new regulations last year
limiting a person's membership in more than three entities.
   ``We conclude this because about $1.3 billion per year will be
routed back to the seven immediate family members through
management fees, equipment and land leases, and loans,'' the report
said.
   No individual names were released. Here are the counties or
parishes checked:
   _Arkansas, Jefferson, Crittenden and Phillips.
   _California, Butte and Kern.
   _Louisiana, Morehouse, Natchitoches and Tensas.
   _Mississippi, De Soto, Noxubee and Tunica.
   _Texas, Jackson, Jefferson and Lubbock.
</TEXT>
