<FIRST>r w AM-ConventionalForces     11-29 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conventional Forces,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Troop Reductions Will Have Small Effect On U.S. Defense Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A possible agreement next year between NATO
and the Warsaw Pact nations to cut conventional arms and troops
will have a minimal direct effect on U.S. military spending,
defense analysts said Wednesday.
   But a reduction in the Warsaw Pact's superiority in armed
forces, tanks, artillery and armored troop carriers could have an
indirect impact that would result in long-term savings for the
United States.
   In negotiations between the NATO and the Warsaw Pact, President
Bush has proposed that the United States and the Soviet Union
reduce their forces in Europe to 275,000 on each side. The Soviets
would have to withdraw 300,000 troops while the United States
reduce its forces by 30,000.
   The American cut of 30,000 amounts to less than 1.5 percent of
the 2.1 million U.S. troops worldwide, and the Congressional Budget
Office has estimated savings from that reduction of about $2.1
billion annually.
   The current Pentagon budget is about $300 billion.
   Analysts for the Defense Budget Project, an independent
non-profit research group, told a news conference that conventional
arms reductions would have to produce larger savings to have a
significant impact on U.S. military spending.
   Long-term savings could occur if after an agreement is reached
creating a numerical parity between the 16 NATO countries and the
seven Warsaw Pact nations, NATO decides it needs less war stocks,
can rely more on reserve forces and less expensive, lighter
infantry forces and limits modernization of its military hardware.
   At the news conference on the issue of U.S. policy after a
conventional arms agreement, Stephen Flanagan, a member of the
State Department's policy planning staff, said such a treaty will
be a ``watershed event'' but a number of outstanding issues means
the pact is not a done deal.
   Political developments in Eastern Europe make it difficult to
predict what the Soviet force structure will be and what levels the
United States will maintain in Europe, Flanagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0180 </DOCNO>
