<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Mice     11-29 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Mice,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill To Rebuild Mouse-Breeding Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Wednesday
authorizing up to $25 million in federal funds to build a
laboratory to breed mice for medical research.
   The contract is expected to go to help rebuild the Jackson
Laboratory of Bar Harbor, Maine, destroyed by a fire last May that
killed more than 400,000 research mice.
   The 60-year-old nonprofit Jackson Laboratory was the nation's
largest supplier of laboratory mice, and federal health officials
have warned its loss could interfere with reearch into cancer and
other diseases.
   Drugs and vaccines are commonly tested first in mice, and the
Jackson Lab had special breeds of mice for longterm study of
specific ailments.
   The 1990 appropriations bill for the Department of Health and
Human Services _ the parent agency of the National Institutes of
Health _ contains $15 million for the mice breeding facility.
   The legislation that Bush signed requires that every $3 in
federal funds for the facility be matched with $1 in non-federal
funds.
