<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     11-29 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serbia Cuts Ties With Slovenia; Possible Breakup of Yugoslavia Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's largest republic,
Serbia, urged all its organizations to sever ties with rival
Slovenia on Wednesday in what analysts said may be the first step
toward the breakup of Communist Yugoslavia.
   The move came after the northern republic of Slovenia introduced
emergency measures to prevent a mass rally planned for Friday by
Serb nationalists seeking to topple Slovenia's liberal leadership.
   Organizers had predicted at least 40,000 people from Serbia
would travel to the rally in Ljubljana, the Slovenian capital.
   The Serbian Socialist Alliance issued a proclamation calling on
all Serbian ``institutions and enterprises to break all contacts
with Slovenia.''
   The alliance, a communist-led mass organization, serves as a
mouthpiece for the republic's ambitious president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
   It said Serbs will no longer allow themselves ``to be
humiliated'' by Slovenia and that ``all freedoms and human rights
have been suspended'' there.
   The state Tanjug news agency carried a statement from the
rally's organizing committee, calling off the rally because ``we
don't want to be greeted by clubs and rifles.''
   Slovenian TV called Serbia's decision ``senseless'' and said the
Serbian leadership ``has reached the lowest possible moral and
political level.''
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, consider
Serbia's move as a first step toward disintegration of Yugoslavia.
   The country is a loose confederation of six republics and two
provinces, containing many different nationalities and religious
groups. Economic problems and sinking living standards have
heightened ethnic tensions.
   A commentary broadcast nationwide on an evening newscast said
Serbia's decision ``complicated the political situation in the
country to an extreme.''
   Slovenian police said earlier Wednesday they would block all
vehicles carrying Serbian demonstrators to the rally in Ljubljana.
They announced other emergency measures including banning all
public rallies and gatherings of more than 30 people without
explicit approval by authorities.
   Slovenian authorities hinted they would use force against
demonstrators, who planned to travel the 550 miles to Ljubljana by
bus, train and automobile. The rally was to protest alleged
harassment of the Serbian minority in Kosovo province by ethnic
Albanians.
   The protesters reportedly demanded toppling of the liberal
Slovenian leadership that they claimed supports the ethnic
Albanians. They accused the Albanians of intimidating the Serb
minority and forcing Serbs to leave the economically backward
province.
   Hard-liners in the Serbian leadership supported the Ljubljana
protest. They strongly oppose the Western-style democratization
processes in Slovenia, including next year's planned introduction
of a multiparty system.
   Serbia advocates the Communist Party's continued monopoly on
power and strong central control. It is deadlocked with Slovenia
over Yugoslavia's political future. Serbian leaders have been
accusing Slovenia of wanting to secede from the federation, and the
statement by the Socialist Alliance said Serbs ``will no longer beg
Slovenes not to break away from Yugoslavia.''
   Yugoslavia's population of nearly 24 million includes 9 million
Serbs and 2 million Slovenes. Slovenia is economically the most
developed region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
