<HEAD>Supreme Court Blocks Execution of Prejean</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs at end addressing issue of retardation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday blocked the
execution of Dalton Prejean, who was due to die early Thursday in
Louisiana for killing a state trooper when Prejean was 17 years old.
   The court granted Prejean's emergency plea to save him from the
electric chair, barring his execution until the justices decide
whether they will hear his formal appeal to set aside his death
penalty.
   No date has been set for the court's action on the formal appeal.
   Prejean had been scheduled to be executed shortly after midnight.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer of Louisiana denied clemency to Prejean on
Tuesday, rejecting a 3-2 recommendation of the state's pardon board
to commute the sentence to life in prison.
   Prejean, 30, has been on death row in Louisiana for 12 years _
longer than anyone else in the state's history. He was convicted of
fatally shooting Donald Cleveland in 1977 after a traffic stop by
the trooper.
   His lawyer has argued that he should be spared because he was
retarded, with an I.Q. of 76, and because of his age at the time of
the crime.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which rejected the appeal
Tuesday, said he is not retarded under standards of the American
Association on Mental Retardation, which sets a threshold at 70.
