<HEAD>Kemp Gives Up New York Residency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs political background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp has given up his New
York state residency, ending any chance he'll run for governor next
year, a spokesman said.
   Kemp notified the Erie Board of Elections on Monday that he was
withdrawing his voting registration there, said Robert Nipp, a
Housing and Urban Development spokesman in Washington.
   ``He intends to register in Montgomery County, Maryland,'' said
Nipp.
   Nipp said Kemp was making the change because ``he's no longer a
congressman from Buffalo'' and ``he has his home in Bethesda.''
   Steven LaFever, a spokesman for the New York state Republican
Committee and a former official at the state Board of Elections,
said that to run for governor a person must be a resident of the
state for five consecutive years.
   State GOP Chairman J. Patrick Barrett had hoped that Kemp, who
unsuccessfully sought the 1988 Republican presidential nomination,
might be willing to challenge Democrat Mario Cuomo's expected
re-election bid next year.
   A recent GOP poll had found that, among those New Yorkers
surveyed, Kemp tested well against the popular Cuomo. The governor
won that theoretical matchup, 48 percent to 42 percent.
   Cuomo, should he do well in a re-election bid next year or skip
it entirely, is considered a potential 1992 presidential contender.
Because of that, supporters of President Bush would like to see
Cuomo given a tough race next year.
