<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Otto     11-29 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Otto,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Nazi Suspected of Killing Former Communist Leader Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Nazi SS sergeant
suspected of the 1944 death camp execution of German Communist
leader Ernst Thaelmann has died. Wolfgang Otto, who served as a
guard at the Buchenwald concentration camp, died Sunday at his home
in the town of Geldern, the Rheinische Post newspaper reported
Wednesday. He was 78.
   Otto was said to be in frail health. He had lived in Geldern
near West Germany's border with the Netherlands for more than 10
years.
   In May 1986, Otto was found guilty of complicity in the shooting
death of Thaelmann at Buchenwald. Thaelmann was imprisoned when the
Nazis took power in 1933.
   Otto was sentenced to four years in prison by a court in Krefeld
but remained free pending an appeal.
   Prosecutors had argued Nazi leader Adolf Hitler personally
ordered Thaelmann's execution and that Otto carried out the orders.
Otto denied the charges.
   The case was appealed to West Germany's Supreme Court, which
overturned the verdict because of a legal error.
   Two years later, Otto was retried and acquitted of the murder
charges by a Duesseldorf state court. The court said there was
insufficient evidence.
   Otto served five years of a separate 20-year war crimes sentence
imposed by a U.S. military court in 1947. His later prosecution was
delayed by bureaucratic wrangling complicated by the failing
memories and deaths of witnesses.
</TEXT>
