<FIRST>r a AM-Lukens-Appeal     11-29 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens-Appeal,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal Hearing Set For Convicted Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens, convicted of
having sex with a 16-year-old girl, has left for Taiwan while a
state court hears arguments in his appeal but is ``upbeat'' about
his prospects, an aide said Wednesday.
   The 58-year-old Republican from Middletown was convicted May 26
of contributing to the unruliness of a minor and was sentenced to
30 days in jail and a $500 fine. He is appealing to the 10th Ohio
District Court of Appeals while free on bond.
   Oral arguments were scheduled for Thursday morning.
   Lukens left Wednesday for Taiwan with four other congressmen to
oversee elections there on Friday, said William Jarrell, Lukens'
chief of staff.
   Jarrell said Lukens refused a request for an interview on the
advice of his attorney.
   ``I can tell you that he's very upbeat about it, but he will be
nowhere near Columbus, Ohio, tomorrow,'' Jarrell said in a
telephone interview from his Washington office.
   Lukens was convicted after a five-day trial in Franklin County
Domestic Relations Court. The girl, Rosie Coffman, and her mother,
Anna, had charged that Lukens knew she was underage when he paid
her to have sex at his Columbus apartment in November 1988. The
girl is now 17.
   Lukens, who did not testify at the trial, had denied the
allegations.
   Anna Coffman's complaint to a Columbus television station last
year led to the congressman's indictment in February.
   She testified at the trial that during a meeting with Lukens in
November 1988, Lukens offered to find her a government job after
she accused him of having sex with her daughter. Television station
WSYX videotaped the meeting.
   Court records show that the focus of the appeal will be a ruling
by Domestic Relations Judge Ronald Solove that kept Lukens'
attorney, Thomas Tyack, from using Rosie Coffman's juvenile court
file and school records as evidence. Tyack had said the records
were crucial to the defense.
   Tyack did not return telephone messages seeking comment
Wednesday.
   Thomas Tornabene, a spokesman for Franklin County Prosecutor
Michael Miller's office, said the state will argue that the girl's
past had nothing to do with the encounter in Lukens' apartment.
   Lukens' conviction sparked calls for his resignation from
Republican leaders in Ohio, including in his home district. In
Congress, the House ethics committee is investigating Lukens.
   Lukens has said he will await the outcome of his appeal before
deciding whether to seek re-election.
</TEXT>
