<FIRST>r a AM-RyanWhite     11-29 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ryan White,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Victim Prepares For Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIE FAIRBANK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS victim Ryan White, who faced pickets
and lawsuits to attend school, was scheduled for tests to see if he
is strong enough for surgery.
   His mother, Jeanne White, says Ryan is scheduled for surgery to
correct a hernia on Dec. 4, at Riley Hospital for Children.
   ``He needs it very much. He's swollen really bad,'' Mrs. White
said. The pre-testing was scheduled Thursday.
   Ryan, 17, contracted AIDS through a blood-clotting agent used to
treat his hemophilia. He was diagnosed with Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome in December 1984.
   Ryan was barred in July 1985 from attending Western Middle
School near Kokomo because of fear that he could spread AIDS to
other students.
   A judge ruled the following spring that Ryan should be allowed
to attend school, because AIDS cannot be spread through casual
contact. The lawsuit and controversy split the community of Kokomo.
Ryan's family eventually moved 20 miles away to Cicero, a town of
about 3,200 people.
   In Cicero, the school system welcomed Ryan, but because of his
hernia, and staph infections in his eyes and legs, he has not
attended school much this year.
   ``This year's been really rough,'' his mother said.
   The tests Thursday are to see if Ryan's blood count is high
enough for surgery. Hemophiliacs are subject to prolonged bleeding
because they are missing a normal blood-clotting factor.
</TEXT>
