<FIRST>r a AM-RandyKraft     11-29 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Randy Kraft,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serial Killer of 16 Men Sentenced to Die in Gas Chamber</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted serial killer Randy Kraft was
sentenced to death Wednesday for a 12-year spree of sexual violence
in which he murdered 16 young men and grotesquely mutilated their
bodies.
   ``Burn in hell, Kraft!'' the father of 22-year-old murder victim
Mark Howard Hall shouted as Kraft was led from court.
   Kraft, 44, insisted he was innocent after Orange County Superior
Court Judge Donald A. McCartin ordered him put to death in the gas
chamber. Relatives of victims cried and hugged each other.
   ``If anyone ever deserved the death penalty, he's got it
coming,'' the judge said, recounting the grisly savagery of one
slaying which included torture by cigarette lighter, castration and
mutilation.
   ``I don't know of any person who could do that to another human
being,'' said McCartin.
   ``Mr. Kraft took innocent and unsuspecting victims who he
drugged, tortured and mutilated. .... He demonstrated an
unbelievable, aggressive, violent tendency toward humanity. I just
can't imagine this violence to satisfy his sexual desires,'' the
judge said.
   Kraft was convicted of murders that occurred between 1972 and
1983. Prosecutors said he picked up male hitchhikers in their late
teens or early 20s, gave them drugs and alcohol, sexually tortured
or mutilated them and then strangled them. Their bodies were dumped
along roadsides.
   California Highway Patrol officers arrested Kraft on May 14,
1983, when they pulled him over for erratic driving and discovered
a strangled Marine from El Toro Marine Corps Air Station in his car.
   ``I sat here for a year, and I didn't see any remorse, feelings
or regret,'' McCartin said. ``It seemed he was in another world
during this trial.''
   Kraft, who played with his pen cap, yawned, laughed and chatted
with his lawyer during the proceeding, briefly addressed the court
after sentencing.
   ``I have not murdered anyone and I believe a reasonable review
of the record will show that,'' said Kraft, a Long Beach computer
consultant.
   McCartin imposed the death sentence for 11 murders and
consecutive life prison terms for the other five murders. The judge
said he did that to keep Kraft in custody in case all the death
sentences were somehow overturned.
   A death sentence is automatically appealed to the state Supreme
Court.
   Kraft also was sentenced to 10 years in prison for three counts
of sodomy, four counts of mayhem and three counts of great bodily
injury.
   A jury of 10 women and two men convicted Kraft on May 12 after a
10{-month trial and recommended the death penalty in August.
   Deputy District Attorney Bryan Brown mentioned again a list
found in Kraft's car which prosecutors believe contains the names
of 65 murder victims. Kraft was sometimes called the ``scorecard
killer'' because of that list.
   McCartin told Kraft he had received letters from parents in
Corona del Mar, Calif., and ``somewhere in Iowa'' whose children
were missing and wanted to know if there was some way the list
could divulge their fate. He did not give the families' names.
   McCartin, noting he was addressing Kraft as an individual and
not as a judge, said if the death sentence appeals fail ``you might
give some thought in your waning moments to help those people out.''
   Outside court relatives of victims clasped hands, hugged and
cried.
   ``My vindication will come the day I know he's gone to the gas
chamber. Then I can truly say it's over,'' said Shirley De Vaul,
mother of murder victim Roger James De Vaul Jr., who was killed at
age 20.
   She and her husband, Roger Sr., are sponsoring an initiative
drive to hasten the judicial process in death penalty cases.
Kraft's case from arrest to sentencing took six years.
   ``People say the death penalty is not a deterrent. Sure it's not
a deterrent because it's never imposed,'' De Vaul said.
</TEXT>
