<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     11-29 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice Presidential Candidate Facing National Assembly Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators debated on Wednesday
whether to deny immunity to a fellow member, who also is the
opposition candidate for vice president, so he can be prosecuted on
charges of misusing donations.
   A decision is expected this week in the single-house National
Assembly, which is dominated by the ruling Sandinistas, on whether
Virgilio Godoy should be stripped of the immunity to which
membership entitles him.
   Godoy is the running mate of publisher Violeta Barrios de
Chamorro, presidential candidate of the 14-party United National
Opposition in the Feb. 25 elections.
   The dispute is over Godoy's handling of a West German donation
worth $60,000. If the assembly allows him to be tried, and he is
convicted, Godoy could be expelled from the legislature.
   The accusations originated in his own Independent Liberal Party,
but he claims the Sandinistas manipulated party members. He said it
is part of a ``Moscow-style'' witch hunt with which the Sandinistas
hope to discredit him and the opposition alliance.
   ``What they want to is exhibit me, to keep me in the store
window for several months,'' Godoy said. ``This won't end until
Feb. 25.''
   About the possibility of losing his immunity, he said: ``Let
them do it. Those who have lent themselves to this dirty
maneuvering need to be taught a lesson.''
   Because of infighting among alliance factions, Mrs. Chamorro has
been surrounding herself with a ``shadow cabinet'' to counter those
who conspre against her close advisers.
   While she was out of the country earlier this month, the
alliance's political committee voted to expel Alfredo Cesar from
the campaign directorate. Opposition sources said it was done
without Mrs. Chamorro's knowledge or consent, and while Cesar also
was abroad.
   When she returned to Nicaragua, Mrs. Chamorro appointed Cesar as
the first of what she said would be 10 personal advisers, and
selected two more soon afterward.
   The Godoy problem involves money and goods given by the
Friedrich-Naumann Foundation of West Germany to a research center
started by the Independent Liberal Party, of which he is president.
   Some party members said Godoy had not given a clear accounting
of the donation and asked the National Assembly to strip him of
immunity so he could be formally charged and tried.
   In a letter, the foundation dismissed the allegations of
mismanagement and demanded a retraction from what it called ``the
pro-Sandinista media.''
</TEXT>
