<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Arms     11-29 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Arms,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Newspaper: Soviets Reining in Nicaragua, Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has told both Nicaragua and Cuba
to stop supplying arms to leftist rebels in El Salvador, a French
newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The Soviet ambassador to Nicaragua gave the instructions at a
secret meeting Tuesday in Managua, the Nicaraguan capital,
according to the authoritative daily Le Monde.
   The newspaper said the meeting was apparently called by the
Soviets and included high-ranking Cuban and Nicaraguan officials.
   The report came in advance of a weekend summit between Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev and President Bush off the Mediterranean
island of Malta.
   The newspaper said the Soviets hoped to gain points with
Washington by ordering Managua and Havana to cut their support for
the leftist Salvadoran rebels, the newspaper said. The United
States backs the rightist Salvadoran government.
   The newspaper said the Soviets were embarrassed by the crash
last weekend over El Salvador of a plane loaded with arms that
apparently originated in Cuba, Moscow's client state.
   The order to stop supporting the rebels of the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, or FMLN, was better received in Managua
than Havana, the newspaper said.
   ``The El Salvador business can only worsen our isolation, even
though we had nothing to do with these last events,'' the newspaper
quoted an unidentified Nicaraguan leader as saying. ``This
offensive and this arms shipment were organized by the FMLN and
Cuba.''
   The newspaper said the leftist Sandinista rulers in Nicaragua
were privately furious with Cuban leader Fidel Castro for
jeopardizing their position with other Central American nations.
   Nicaragua signed a 1987 regional peace plan, promising not to
interfere in other countries' affairs.
</TEXT>
