<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PrisonRegulations     11-29 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Regulations,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Quashes Proposed Restictions On Prison Interviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Thornburgh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Wednesday
abruptly rescinded a Bureau of Prisons proposal restricting the
circumstances under which reporters could interview federal
prisoners.
   Thornburgh issued a brief statement announcing his decision just
hours after he had defended the day-old proposal at stormy session
with reporters who cover the Justice Department.
   Reporters sharply questioned the attorney general about the
regulations, accusing the Bureau of Prisons of seeking to control
the way news organizations cover conditions in federal prisons.
   The regulations, published in Tuesday's Federal Register, would
have empowered wardens to refuse to allow reporters to conduct
further interviews if they failed to seek comment from correction
authorities about allegations about prison conditions.
   Under the proposal, inmates would have been allowed to be
interviewed by journalists once a month. No more than one interview
between a prisoner and a reporter could be held each day in any
facility.
   In his statement, Thornburgh said he ordered the Bureau of
Prisons to withdraw the proposed regulations. ``This proposal was
submitted prematurely and without my personal review. It will be
subject to further review before resubmission,'' the attorney
general said.
   Thornburgh's spokesman David Runkel said the attorney general
had learned of the regulations Tuesday night and decided to rescind
them Wednesday afternoon.
   Bureau of Prisons spokesman James Jones said he did not know
what, if any, provisions Thornburgh found objectionable. He said
the attorney general did not outline specific objections to the
Bureau of Prisons when he announced his order.
   During the morning session with reporters, Thornburgh had
defended the proposal, stressing that he had not personally
reviewed it. ``I think there is a problem that they are trying to
address of reconciling their management responsiblity with the flow
of information in and out of prisons,'' Thornburgh had said.
   ``Let's start from the reductio ad absurdum that any prisoner
who wants to talk to any reporter at any time can do so,'' the
attorney general said. ``I find that unacceptable in terms of
managing a prison population.''
   The regulations ``are designed to ensure two things: one that an
accurate flow of information and observe what is necessary to
properly manage prison facilities.''
   Before it was rescinded, the proposal was branded as a form of
censorship by Ed Koren, an attorney for the American Civil
Liberties Union's national prison project.
   ``It is certainly an attempt to cut of any kind of criticism and
to protect the Bureau of Prisons from any embarrassments,'' Koren
said.
   ``What is particularly obnoxious is that provison ... that
requires reporters to come up with a balanced approach on the pain
of not being able to get further interviews,'' Koren said.
   The proposed regulations said that reporters ``have a
professional responsibility to make a reasonable attempt to verify
any allegations regarding an inmate, staff member, or institution.''
   ``To ensure an opportunity to gather complete information
regarding both sides of any issue in the institution, a
representative of the news media, as a condition of any
face-to-face interview granted by the bureau, shall provide
authorized staff of the Bureau of Prisons an opportunity to respond
to any allegations that might be published or broadcast,'' the
regulations said.
   Jones said the policy or requiring reporters to obtain comment
from corrections officials has been existence for a decade.
   ``All we are asking for is if there are allegations made, we get
a chance to respond.''
   Jones said ``there is not a whole lot that's new'' in the
proposed regulations, which were published for public comment.
   New elements of the regulations were the proposals to limit the
number of interviews per institution to one a day and the number of
meetings an inmate could have with a reporter to one a month, Jones
said.
   Jones said that the new regulations would not have functioned as
a limit because ``we determined that the average number of
interviews per institution a month was five.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
