<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-PLO-US     11-29 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-PLO-US,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Says U.S. Threat to Cut Funds Is `Financial Terrorism'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization said
Wednesday the United States it is guilty of ``financial terrorism''
by threatening to cut off funds to the United Nations if the
General Assembly calls the PLO a nation.
   Arab diplomats plan to introduce a resolution changing the PLO's
status from an observer to a non-voting nation like North and South
Korea, Switzerland, Monaco, San Marino and the Vatican.
   The State Department says it will halt U.S. payments if the
General Assembly approves the resolution. The United States is
assessed $216 million annually, one-fourth of the U.N. budget.
   Zehdi Labib Terzi, the PLO representative, told a luncheon
meeting: ``This is another example of financial terrorism.''
   In Rome, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization ignored U.S.
threats and voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to help the PLO teach
Palestinians how to grow food in Israeli-occupied territories.
   The United States said such a policy involved the FAO in
politics and said it would stop funds to the agency if it was
approved. It also has threatened to withdraw from the FAO.
   ``We have made it absolutely clear to the FAO leadership over
the last few days that passing the resolution would have serious
consequences for the organization,'' the State Department announced.
   A U.S. official said the State Department would consult with
American delegates to FAO on their return from Rome before
announcing their next step.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli government condemned the FAO action.
   In the General Assembly, a vote on the PLO resolution has been
postponed from Friday until next Wednesday.
   Diplomats said privately negotiations were under way on a
compromise acceptable to both the PLO and United States.
   On Tuesday, U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering said: ``We are
clearly not interested in exploring all the alternatives. We are
interested in finding a way to end this particular silly idea that
the Palestinians can be declared a state here in the United Nations
when they have none of the attributes of a state.''.
   Upgrading the PLO's status would need only a majority vote of
the 159 General Assembly members. As a member of the 102-member
non-aligned movement, the PLO theoretically has more than enough
votes to prevail.
   Last year, the PLO declared an independent state of Palestine,
without defining its borders but presumably in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, and says 117 nations have recognized it.
</TEXT>
