<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru a0690 11-29 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0690,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>Krenz Vows Independence; Bonn Begins Reunification Offensive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with later Moscow developments, Leipzig
rally, details, minor editing. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Egon Krenz joined
leading dissidents Wednesday in calling for East Germany to remain
independent, as West Germany began a worldwide diplomatic push to
win support for reunification.
   Krenz insisted that East Germany will remain a staunchly
socialist state, sovereign and independent.
   The United States already has given its support to uniting the
Germanys, whose common border is considered the dividing line of
East and West and was established after the Nazi defeat in World
War II.
   Soviet officials on Wednesday rejected a reunificiation plan
advanced by West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and said a united
Germany could upset European stability.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher informed
British officials about the proposal in London Wednesday and
planned a similar stop in Paris Thursday. He will brief the Soviets
on it Tuesday in Moscow.
   About 10,000 people marched late Wednesday in a Communist
Party-organized rally in Leipzig, considered a hotbed of
pro-democracy opposition.
   ``There is no collective guilt of the Communist Party,'' said
city party leader Thomas Bonesky, referring to widespread
corruption being uncovered during the leadership of ousted
hard-line party chief Erich Honecker.
   Speakers clearly rejected reunification, the official East
German news agency ADN said.
   Krenz and other East German Communist leaders have rejected any
talk of reunification, despite sweeping changes and upheavals in
this troubled nation. He and Communist Premier Hans Modrow signed
an appeal circulated by leading dissidents demanding an East German
state that offers ``a socialist alternative to West Germany.'' It
was initiated by writer Stefan Heym and other East German
intellectuals concerned about the nation's future.
   Krenz told the organizers in a letter: ``We have the historic
duty to preserve this country with its anti-fascist ideals and
traditions as a socialist alternative within German development.''
   Echoing the petition's sentiments, he called for ``peace and
social justice, individual freedom, freedom of travel for all and
the preservation of the environment.''
   His government, bowing to reform demands, already has promised
free elections by early 1991 and a constitutional amendment
stripping it of its 40-year monopoly on power.
   Kohl says East Germany must hold free elections if it wants West
German aid and closer ties.
   Kohl on Tuesday outlined his 10-point reunification plan, which
received the approval of West Germany's opposition Social Democrats.
   Kohl discussed his proposal Wednesday with President Bush in a
``very intensive and complete telephone conversation,'' government
spokesman Hans Klein said in Bonn.
   West Germany sent the plan to its embassies worldwide, and
ambassadors were told ``to deliver it to the host governments'' and
explain it, Klein said.
   In Rome, where Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev began a
state visit on Wednesday, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady
I. Gerasimov told reporters, ``Not one country in Europe is anxious
to see a united Germany because it could upset the present
stability in Europe.''
   He said Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told Italian
officials that before Moscow would reconsider, West Germany must
renounce any claim to Germany's pre-World War II borders, which
included many areas now belonging to Poland, the Soviet Union and
other border states.
   Gerasimov deputy Yuri A. Gremitskykh said in Moscow that Kohl
presented his proposal ``without considering the opinions of other
countries. ... We can clearly see an attempt to shift the movement
that started in East Germany to nationalistic lines.''
   Many Europeans fear a reunified Germany, with a population of 80
million people, would dominate the continent politically and
economically.
   Kohl sought to ease such worries Tuesday by saying a united
Germany would never again threaten Europe.
   He did not offer a timetable for reunification, but said it
could take years.
   Reunification talk began after East Germany opened its borders
and the Berlin Wall on Nov. 9 as part of a policy allowing citizens
to travel freely.
   The moves came after thousands fled their homeland and hundreds
of thousands took to the streets demanding social and political
reforms.
   The party ousted Honecker Oct. 18 and the new leadership has
begun exposing corruption and abuses by party members.
   East German newspapers on Wednesday described how former Premier
Willi Stoph turned a natural park into a private estate.
   Stoph was sacked from the ruling Politburo and resigned as
premier Nov. 7.
   The official Communist Party newspaper Neues Deutschland said he
had lived ``surrounded by Western luxury'' on an estate containing
houses, fruit plantations and an indoor swimming pool.
   East German opposition groups, church leaders and the Communists
are to meet Dec. 7 for the first round of talks on reform.
</TEXT>
