<FIRST>r w AM-Pilots     11-29 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilots,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Union Expects Eastern To Begin Rehiring Pilots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association expects
Eastern Airlines to begin rehiring its members who ended their
strike last week at the rate of about 100 a month, the union
president said Wednesday.
   ``The airline needs some reconciliation with its traditional
employees to work, because it's sure not working now,'' said Henry
A. Duffy, ALPA president.
   Duffy, speaking at a Washington Journalism Center seminar, said
Eastern officials have taken a ``soft approach'' in initial
discussions with pilots and flight attendants who ended their
support for a Machinists strike after eight months off the job.
   Duffy said he expects Eastern to hire back 700 union pilots.
   The airline, which has about 1,800 pilots, said it has no
openings for the returning strikers but might accept some of the
ALPA pilots when openings occur.
   About 3,500 pilots initially joined the sympathy walkout, along
with 6,000 flight attendants. Some 8,500 members of the Machinists
union remain on strike over company demands that they take wage
cuts and grant other concessions.
   Duffy said recent ALPA defeats, including a rejection of union
representation by Federal Express employees and the failure of an
employee effort to take over United Airlines, have not weakened the
union.
   He blamed a New York bankruptcy court and President Bush for
failure to resolve the Eastern strike. The court has rejected
union-backed efforts to end the strike since Eastern filed for
reorganization. Bush refused to intervene in the strike and vetoed
a bill that would have set up a congressional advisory commission
to help settle it.
   Duffy said the union is still working with the flight
attendants' union and United Airlines management to make a new
offer that would prevent the airline from being taken over in a
leveraged buyout.
   He said the Machinists union, which opposed the previous
management-employee takeover, might be more willing to join a new
proposal because the share price will be lower. United's stock fell
after the deal collapsed, helping to trigger the Oct. 13 stock
market plunge.
   Duffy said that although British Airways has said it foresees no
further involvement in the deal _ it had planned to acquire a 15
percent interest _ talks are continuing with several foreign
carriers who might join the next bid.
</TEXT>
