<FIRST>r w AM-MalariaChief     11-29 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaria Chief,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Head Of Malaria Research Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chief of the government's $91.2
million-a-year malaria research program was indicted Wednesday on
charges of conspiring with a consultant to convert more than
$140,000 for his personal use.
   James Erickson, who has been suspended as chief of the Agency
for International Development's malaria research program, was
charged in a 12-count indictment, AID said in a statement.
   Erickson was indicted in Alexandria, Va., along with George
Diaz, a former malaria project consultant who was charged with
conspiracy.
   The two are accused of conspiring to transfer more than $140,000
in federal research grant funds for their personal use.
   Erickson was also charged with making false statements, conflict
of interest, accepting gratuities, making a false claim against the
government and filing false income tax returns.
   If convicted of the charges, Erickson could be sentenced up to
41 years in prison and fined more than $500,000, according to the
agency's statement.
   Diaz, a close friend of Erickson, faces a possible five-year
prison sentence if convicted of conspiracy.
   The indictment resulted from an investigation by the agency's
inspector general. The General Accounting Office recently
criticized the management and financial practices in the program
that Erickson administered.
   The indictment supersedes an earlier one filed against Erickson,
charging him with one count of making a false statement about a
government malaria grant.
