<HEAD>Snow Threat In Western Pennsylvania, California Cooler on a Windy
Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gale force wind warnings were posted Wednesday for the Great
Lakes, central New England coast and western Gulf of Mexico, and as
much as 3 inches of snow was expected western Pennsylvania.
   In Northern California, the city of Reading posted a record low
for the date of 27 degrees, and Bakersfield tied its 41-year-old
record for the date of 31.
   Santa Ana winds blustered over the mountain ridges and passes of
Southern California, clocked at 45 mph at Rialto, 40 mph at
Sandberg and 26 mph at Needles and Riverside.
   A tropical storm watch was posted for western Cuba for a
tropical depression moving toward the north at about 10 mph. At
noon, rain was falling over southern Florida.
   Snow showers were scattered from the western half of New York
across north central and western Pennsylvania, West Virginia,
eastern and central Ohio, and michigan.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at noon included less
than a quarter inch at West Palm Beach. Snowfall for the period was
heaviest in Michican, with 2 inches at Pellston and 1 inch at Grand
Rapids, Muskegon and Traverse City.
   The low temperature for the Lower 48 Wednesday was 16 degrees
below zero at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Temperatures across the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Saranac Lake, N.Y., to 77 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla.
