<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PregnantMurder     11-29 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pregnant Murder,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Agers Say Husband Present at Pregnant Wife's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of arranging his pregnant
wife's murder watched as two teen-agers stabbed her, according to
court documents unsealed Wednesday.
   Anthony Pfaaf, 19, told police that Kenneth Johnson offered him
$10,000 to kill Johnson's wife, Sharon, according to an account of
a police interview on Monday filed with Merrimack District Court by
State Police Sgt. Roland Lamy.
   Pfaaf said he recruited Jason Carroll, 19, to help kill her the
night of July 28, 1988.
   Johnson, 37, currently of Warwick, R.I., Pfaaf of Wallace, N.C.,
and formerly of Manchester, and Carroll of New Boston were all
charged with capital murder Tuesday in the woman's death.
   Sharon Johnson, 36, was seven months pregnant and had been
married to Johnson for three years when she was killed.
   Pfaaf said he asked Carroll to pretend to be someone named
``Bob'' who was to give her some money. They met Sharon Johnson at
the Mall of New Hampshire in Manchester, forced her into her car
and to drive to a Bedford sand pit, Pfaaf told Lamy. He said
Kenneth Johnson gave them directions to the sand pit earlier in the
day.
   When they arrived at the pit, Carroll told Lamy they got out and
a man, whom he assumed was Johnson, approached from nearby woods.
   ``What are you doing here?'' Sharon Johnson asked the man,
according to Carroll's account.
   Kenneth Johnson responded by cursing her and accusing her of
cheating on him, said Carroll, who had never met Johnson before.
   Pfaaf, who also placed Johnson at the scene of the killing, said
his wife began to struggle and Carroll stabbed her, then gave him
the knife and he stabbed and choked her. Pfaaf said Johnson
supplied them with the knife used in the killing.
   Pfaaf said he and Carroll later went to Johnson's home in Bow
where he paid them $10,000.
   Based on information supplied by Kenneth Johnson, police
circulated a sketch of ``Bob'' and tried to locate him during the
months after the murder. At one point last year, Johnson told
police that Bob was ``someone who put in bets for me and he owes me
money.''
   An investigation, however, later showed there was no ``Bob,''
and suspicions focused on Johnson.
   The three, who face the death penalty if convicted, were ordered
held without bail at the Hillsborough County Jail in Manchester.
</TEXT>
