<HEAD>Salvadoran Diplomats Close Embassy, Leave Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-11 pvs `Cristiani announced ... fully re-established.'
with 7 grafs to ADD that U.N. debate set, background on pullout of ambassador,
minor editing. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran diplomats closed their
embassy in Managua and returned home Wednesday after their country
suspended diplomatic relations with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government.
   But charge d'affaires Roberto Lopez Geissman insisted there was
no break in relations between the two countries. He told reporters
at the airport before leaving for San Salvador that he was just
being recalled indefinitely for consultations.
   ``Unfortunately, there's been speculation that there's a
breaking of relations between El Salvador and Nicaragua, which is
not true,'' Lopez said.
   ``It's not even a suspension .... It's a re-calling for
consultations. Of course, it's much graver because it's the whole
diplomatic and consular delegation'' that is leaving Managua, he
added.
   Lopez left together with the Salvadoran Consul, an executive
secretary and their families. The Salvadoran diplomatic mission was
shut down Wednesday.
   The Colombian Embassy in Managua might look after Salvadoran
affairs, but this has not been finalized, Lopez said. Meanwhile, he
said Costa Rican Ambassador Farid Ayales had agreed to act as
caretaker.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani announced Sunday he had
suspended diplomatic and commercial relations with the Sandinista
government, accusing it of smuggling weapons to leftist guerrillas
in El Salvador.
   Cristiani announced the break a day after authorities in the
neighboring country found two small planes were ferrying
surface-to-air missiles and other military hardware to the rebels.
   In one plane, three crew members died as a result of the crash
and a fourth survived but committed suicide afterwards, Salvadoran
military authorities said.
   They said the other plane landed and unloaded but could not take
off for reasons still being investigated and the crew set the
aircraft afire and fled the scene.
   Lopez said ``because of the fellowship that has united the
Central American countries'' the closure won't last long, and
``diplomatic relations can be fully re-established.''
   El Salvador re-called its ambassador after the 1978-79
Sandinista revolution, when the embassy was fired on. Since then,
the mission has been headed by several charge d'affaires.
   In New York, diplomats at the United Nations said the Security
Council will hold a debate Thursday on El Salvador's complaint that
Nicaragua is sending weapons to the rebels.
   El Salvador has requested the debate, and the council members
decided to go ahead during private consultations Wednesday, the
diplomats said on condition of anonymity.
