<FIRST>r a AM-Batman-CBS-Turner     11-29 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Batman-CBS-Turner,0226</SECOND>
<UNK>CBS Buys ``Batman'' Rights, Turner Buys Rights for 1,000 Films</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS has bought rights to the summer blockbuster
hit, ``Batman,'' and Ted Turner's cable company has bought rights
to 1,000 films from Columbia Pictures Television, CBS and Turner
officials said Wedneday.
   The officials wouldn't disclose the purchase prices, but Susan
Tick, a spokesman for CBS in Los Angeles, characterized as ``just
silly'' one report that said CBS paid up to $20 million for
``Batman.''
   She said she didn't know when CBS will air the film. One
executive who asked not to be identified said the network probably
won't broadcast the film until 1992.
   The cable rights purchase by Turner's year-old Turner Network
Television cable channel and his TBS SuperStation is for films
dating from 1935 to 1983.
   They range from ``Tootsie'' to ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.''
The majority of the films will air on TNT.
   Rights to show the films begin in January and extend through
May, 1999 1999.
   Turner's film library already includes the pre-1986 MGM films,
pre-1950 Warner Brothers films and a number of RKO titles.
   In a statement, Turner Broadcasting System, which owns TNT and
TBS, said the Columbia purchases represents ``the largest movie
package ever licensed from a single Hollywood studio in the history
of basic cable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
