<FIRST>r i AM-East-Glance     11-29 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-Glance,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wednesday's Developments in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   These were the major developments Wednesday concerning political
change in Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament voted unanimously to scrap the provisions in the
constitution that mandated a leading role for the Communist Party.
   A member of the Communist Party's ruling Politburo said free
elections _ the first in four decades _ could be held within a year.
   Parliament also ended a requirement that all education be based
on Marxist-Leninist principles. Dropping that requirement was a
primary demand of student demonstrators.
   Premier Ladislav Adamec said would be prepared to negotiate the
withdrawal of Soviet troops from Czechoslovakia. He also said he
had asked the opposition group Civic Forum for suggestions on whom
to include in the new government.
 
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>EAST GERMANY</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Egon Krenz said East Germany should remain
an independent, sovereign and socialist state.
   West Germany has begun a diplomatic campaign to win
international support of its plan for reunification of the two
Germanies. But Soviet officials rejected the West German plan and
said a united Germany could upset European stability.
   A campaign to expose abuses by former party officials continued
as newspapers reported former Premier Willi Stoph turned a wildlife
park into a private estate for himself.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>YUGOSLAVIA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Serbia, the largest republic in Yugoslavia, urged all its
organizations to sever ties with the rival republic of Slovenia.
The move came after Slovenia introduced emergency measures to
prevent a mass rally planned for Friday by Serb nationalists
seeking to topple Slovenia's liberal leadership.
   Western diplomats see Serbia's action as a first step toward a
breakup of Yugoslavia, a loose confederation of six republics and
two provinces.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HUNGARY-COMANECI</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's news agency reported that Nadia Comaneci, the Romanian
gymnast who made history with perfect scores at the 1976 Olympics,
has fled her country and been granted a temporary residence permit
by Hungary. Her exact whereabouts were not known. Comaneci, 28,
told border guards she left Romania ``for the sale of freedom,''
the news agency said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>POLAND</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and water cannon to push back hundreds of
young people who attacked the statue of Lenin in the city of Nowa
Huta. The demonstrators dispersed after pleas for moderation from a
Solidarity deputy who promised to propose dismantling of the
monument to parliament.
</TEXT>
