<HEAD>Walesa Predicts End to Warsaw Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 14, `Foreign Secretary ...' to UPDATE with aid package
spread over five years. Picks up graf 15, `Walesa, a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on his first visit
to Britain predicted Wednesday that the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
alliance will eventually be dismantled.
   On his arrival from Poland, Walesa told a news conference at
Heathrow Airport that he expected Eastern bloc defense budgets to
decline gradually as democratic reforms are enacted.
   The global arms race will slow, and the seven-nation Warsaw Pact
``will be dissolved eventually ... as the process of common sense
prevails,'' he said through an interpreter.
   The Warsaw Pact was created in 1955 as a mutual defense alliance
among the Soviet Union and its Eastern European satellites.
   ``It's ridiculous to destroy the earth eight times over, and
they are still thinking of a ninth,'' Walesa added. ``As Europe
becomes integrated economically, it becomes even more ridiculous.''
   Western European nations have agreed to form an economic union
by the end of 1992.
   In Washington on Wednesday, Secretary of State James A. Baker
III said the upcoming U.S.-Soviet summit should leave the
superpowers ``better prepared to make substantial progress'' on a
treaty to slash long-range nuclear weapons.
   However, he emphasized anew that no such agreement would be
reached during the two-day meeting. He also said he expected no
pact on conventional forces to emerge from the meeting between
President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev on Saturday
and Sunday off the Mediterranean island of Malta.
   In his comments, Walesa said he would like to see the 12-nation
European Economic Community expanded to embrace all of Europe.
   ``Together we can find solutions we are proud of,'' he said.
   The Nobel Peace Prize-winning labor leader said his recent trip
to the United States proved to Americans that they should invest in
Poland and now he was bringing his appeal to Britain.
   The U.S. House of Representatives has approved a three-year,
$864.5 million aid program for Poland.
   After his tour of the United States, Canada and Venezuela,
Walesa returned to Poland on Thursday before flying out again on a
four-day trip to Britain. Solidarity took control of the Polish
government in August, creating the first non-Communist government
in the East bloc since the Communists consolidated power after
World War II.
   Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd announced Wednesday that Britain
will double its aid package to Poland to $77 million over a
five-year period and give $64 million more to an International
Monetary Fund to rebuild the Polish economy.
   Walesa, a guest of the Trade Unions Congress federation, later
Wednesday attended a private dinner to mark the 40th anniversary of
the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions.
   The 46-year-old former shipyard electrician is to meet Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher at her official residence on Saturday.
</TEXT>
