<FIRST>r a AM-SnuffFilm     11-29 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snuff Film,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guilty Pleas Entered in Child Pornography Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Richmond man accused of using a
computer bulletin board to ask about acquiring young boys for a
pornographic ``snuff'' film pleaded guilty Wednesday to conspiracy
to kidnap and soliciting to produce child pornography.
   The defendant, Dean A. Lambey, faces a maximum penalty of life
imprisonment plus 10 years and $500,000 in fines for both charges.
   Lambey, 34, and Daniel T. Depew, 28, of Alexandria, were charged
in U.S. District Court in August following a six-month undercover
police operation that began, according to court documents, when
Lambey contacted an undercover police officer in San Jose, Calif.,
through a computer bulletin board system and asked about young boys
for a pornographic ``snuff'' film.
   A ``snuff'' film is one in which someone is actually killed.
   In March, Lambey suggested that he and the undercover officers
produce their own child pornography film, buying a child for
$12,000 from an out-of-state source, according to an account of the
case given The Associated Press in August by an official who
insisted on anonymity.
   More than 100 FBI agents and San Jose, Calif., police were
involved in the investigation, U.S. Attorney Henry E. Hudson said
in August, with agents keeping the suspects under surveillance 24
hours a day.
</TEXT>
