<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Amazon     11-29 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Amazon,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supercomputer Foresees End of Amazon Rain Forest in 50-100 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study by the Brazilian Space
Research Institute shows the entire Amazon rain forest could be
wiped out in 50 to 100 years if deforestation continues at the
present rate.
   Carlos Nobre, an engineer and meteorologist with the institute,
said Wednesday the findings were the result of a year-long study at
the University of Maryland using a supercomputer belonging to NASA.
   Nobre said he used mathematical formulas to project the effects
of deforestation, which he estimates destroys 14,000 square miles
of rain forest a year.
   The computer predicted the huge wilderness could dry up and turn
into a vast, scrub-covered savanna, he said.
   ``The advance of pasture land would profoundly change the
landscape and the way of life in the region,'' the scientist said
at the institute in Sao Jose dos Campos, 200 miles southwest of Rio.
   Nobre said the destruction of trees to clear land for planting
and grazing reduces the forest's capacity to retain water.
   As a result, temperatures will rise, rainfall will diminish and
the soil will become poorer, he said. Even the water level in
rivers will fall, reducing the hydroelectric potential.
   When that happens, Nobre said, the rain forest would succumb to
a long dry season and turn into a savanna, covered with scrub trees
and grass.
   The 2 million-square-mile Brazilian Amazon is the world's
largest wilderness. Independent studies show 12 percent of it has
been destroyed, mostly by small farmers and cattle ranchers using
slash-and-burn techniques. The government claims the correct figure
is 5 percent.
   Scientists say destruction of the rain forest adds to the
greenhouse effect, which traps the sun's rays and causes global
warming.
   The Brazilian government, under fire from environmentalists,
recently announced that burnings in the Amazon were far less than
in previous years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0223 </DOCNO>
