<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bowles     11-29 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bowles,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dorothy Bowles, Widow of Former Ambassador to India, Dead at 86</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ESSEX, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Stebbins Bowles, who won an
international reputation as a friendly and independent-minded
diplomat during her late husband's tours as U.S. ambassador to
India, has died after a brief illness.
   Her husband, Chester Bowles, was a principal foreign policy
advisor to President Kennedy and served as Ambassador to India
twice, first from 1951 to 1958, then from 1963 to 1969.
   Mrs. Bowles, who died Tuesday, was widely known in India. She
delighted in Indian culture and raised eyebrows among other
Americans when she began to wear a sari, the traditional,
wrap-around Indian dress.
   She often wore a sari in Connecticut, and wore one to her
husband's funeral.
   Bowles, who died in 1986, also served one term as Connecticut
governor and represented the state in Congress. He once said his
1934 marriage to Dorothy Stebbins, then a psychiatric social
worker, was ``the most important event in shaping my later lfe.''
   In Essex, where she lived for 50 years, Mrs. Bowles was active
in local politics and brought many famous guests to the Connecticut
River town.
   ``It was a household where you could find Adlai Stevenson or
Eleanor Roosevelt or some prizefighter or some neighbor who just
happened to drop in, and usually a large number of children,'' said
Doug Bennet, president of National Public Radio and a former member
of the Bowles' embassy staff.
   ``It was one of the most exciting places I've ever been in my
life,'' he said.
   Gov. William A. O'Neill, in a statement Wednesday, said, ``I
consider myself extremely fortunate to have been Steb's friend and
I will miss her greatly.''
</TEXT>
