<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Probe 1stLd-Writethru a0683 11-29 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Probe, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0683,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Probing Charges That Shuttle Parts Not Properly Inspected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT Morton-Thiokol to Thiokol.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury convened Wednesday
to study an engineer's allegations that equipment for the space
shuttles did not get proper inspections after the explosion that
killed the seven Challenger astronauts.
   U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson said he expects the grand jury to
complete its work by Friday and that he is prohibited from
commenting on anything the panel is examining.
   However, a spokesman for the Thiokol Corp., formerly
Morton-Thiokol, at Ogden, Utah, Steve Lawson, said the company had
been asked to provide information about instrumentation in
redesigned solid fuel booster rocket motors used starting with the
Discovery flight Sept. 30, 1988.
   Lawson, whose company makes solid fuel boosters for the
shuttles, said he could not provide details on what type of
information had been requested. He said the instruments fulfilled
NASA requirements.
   A Thiokol engineer, Dan Joos, has said there was improper
testing of booster parts. He and employees of at least one Thiokol
subcontractor reportedly were subpoenaed to appear before the grand
jury.
   Joos had said that instruments that measure stresses on the
184-foot-long boosters were not properly inspected and could be
giving engineers false information. He said that could lead to
failures of the booster rockets.
   NASA suspended shuttle flights and overhauled engines and
spacecraft after the failure of a booster rocket seal caused the
Challenger explosion.
   Royce Mitchell, manager of the solid rocket motor office at
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, said his office was
cooperating in the investigation of Joos' charges.
   Jack Lee, Marshall's director, said NASA engineers at Huntsville
investigated Joos' allegations and concluded there were ``no safety
issues involved'' that would require suspending shuttle flights.
   The Rogers Commission that investigated the Challenger tragedy
found that Marshall engineers had pushed for the Challenger launch
while ignoring booster problems.
   J.R. Thompson, NASA's deputy administrator and Marshall director
during the booster redesign work, said he was unaware of Joos'
concerns or the grand jury probe.
   ``I don't know what they're talking about because all flights we
have made since Challenger have gone exceptionally well,'' he said
in Washington.
   Porter Bridwell, manager of Marshall's shuttle projects office,
said his engineers and NASA's inspector general began looking into
Joos' concerns about a month ago. He said they felt sure they
``weren't related to safety issues.''
</TEXT>
