<DOCNO> AP891129-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Politics     11-29 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Politics,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Challenger Formally Nominated to Run Against Thatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Anthony Meyer, a rank-and-file member of the
governing Conservatives, was nominated for party leader Wednesday
in the first challenge to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher since
she took over the party's top post 14 years ago.
   The challenge comes at a time of sagging popularity for Mrs.
Thatcher's leadership. Opinion polls published Sunday showed the
Conservatives trailing opposition Labor by as much as 14 points.
   However, Meyer, who handed in his nomination papers Wednesday
evening, said he had ``no idea'' how much support he would get.
   ``All I want to do is to give people the opportunity to vote,''
he told reporters. ``It is for them to make up their own minds.''
   Mrs. Thatcher ousted former Prime Minister Edward Heath as party
leader 14 years ago.
   The 64-year-old prime minister has led the Conservatives to
three successive election victories since 1979. She is the
longest-serving British prime minister this century.
   Nominations for the party leadership close at noon Thursday. The
results of voting by the 375 Conservatives in the 650-member House
of Commons are due to be announced Tuesday.
   Conservative lawmakers vote annually on their leader, but Mrs.
Thatcher has been endorsed unopposed since defeating Heath in 1975.
   Mrs. Thatcher complained Monday that the challenge to her
leadership was causing ``damaging'' uncertainty.
   Labor moved ahead of the Conservatives in the polls in the
spring amid widespread dissatisfaction over rising inflation and
intended changes in the National Health Service.
   
   When Meyer, a 69-year-old former diplomat, announced his
candidacy last week, he said he would withdraw if a more senior
party member would run against Mrs. Thatcher. But none has come
forward.
   Under party rules, the identities of Meyer's nominator and
seconder are not disclosed.
   Under a complicated voting formula, Mrs. Thatcher needs 57
percent of the votes cast to win outright. If she fails, other
candidates are expected to enter the race for a second ballot.
   Meyer opposes the sale of state-owned water utilities. He wants
better pensions for war widows and believes Mrs. Thatcher should be
more enthusiastic about European economic integration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos     11-29 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Turned To Nancy Reagan For Legal Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon after Ferdinand Marcos was deposed as
Philippine leader in 1986, his wife appealed to Nancy Reagan for
White House intervention in their legal affairs, according to
government documents made public Wednesday.
   In a ``Dearest Nancy'' letter dated Sept. 11, 1986, Imelda
Marcos asked Mrs. Reagan to help her avoid iving a deposition in a
civil racketeering lawsuit brought in a California court by the
Philippine government against the Marcoses.
   ``I understand that a `suggestion' from the `White House' or the
`State Depart.' could prevent these indignities to an ally and
friend,'' Mrs. Marcos wrote.
   Whether Mrs. Reagan responded is not known, but Mrs. Marcos
later did give the deposition, invoking her Fifth Amendment rights.
The Philippine case, which is still pending, seeks to recover money
allegedly stolen from the Philippine government by the Marcoses for
personal use.
   Mark Weinberg, a spokesman for the Reagans in Los Angeles, said
Wednesday that it was the Reagans' ``long-standing practice not to
comment on pending legal matters.''
   The letter was contained in the government's response papers to
numerous pretrial motions brought by Mrs. Marcos' lawyers in her
pending criminal indictment.
   Mrs. Marcos has pleaded innocent to charges that she and her
late husband siphoned nearly $200 million from the Philippine
treasury and funneled it into this country for the purchase of New
York real estate and art. She is scheduled to go on trial in
Manhattan's federal court March 14.
   The government papers also revealed that prosecutors
investigated charges that Marcos embezzled $15 million in U.S.
government funds that had been designated for use by the Philippine
government. The money, from the U.S. Agency for International
Development, allegedly was deposited into a Swiss bank account
controlled by Marcos.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella said Wednesday that the
embezzlement allegations were not contained in the racketeering
indictment brought against the Marcoses in October 1988.
   Mrs. Marcos' letter was included to undercut her contention that
she and her husband were ``kidnapped'' from the Philippines by the
U.S. government in February 1986 after Marcos was ousted as leader.
   In the letter, Mrs. Marcos thanks the Reagans for their
hospitality.
   LaBella said Mrs. Marcos's abduction allegation was ``an absurd
claim ... She transforms history into fairy tale.''
   ``Marcos does not acknowledge that the United States government
evacuated her amidst crowds of anti-Marcos demonstrators, but
contends, instead that the United States government ousted her from
power through force and deception,'' LaBella said in his papers.
   Mrs. Marcos is seeking to have the charges against her dropped
because of the abduction claim.
   The government papers also revealed that the Marcoses declined
to provide any tax information to the United States government in
1986 and 1987 because they claimed they were brought to the country
against their will.
   In addition to Mrs. Marcos' letter, the prosecutor included a
letter from Ferdinand Marcos to President Reagan, which had
previously been made public.
   In that letter, dated June 9, 1988, Marcos, who died in
September at the couple's home in exile in Honolulu, asks the
president to block the criminal indictment against the Marcoses and
then thanked the president for his hospitality over the last two
years.
   Marcos's letter, which was typewritten and addressed to ``Mr.
President,'' was much more formal than Mrs. Marcos's appeal to Mrs.
Reagan, in which she describes the pain and humiliation of the
couple's legal problems.
   ``I don't think I have enough strength left to bear up with all
these,'' she wrote. ``Therefore I ask your invaluable help to
prevent a `deposition' on me and with a clear conscience, I am
optimistic of justice and your understanding.''
   The letter was signed, ``Much, much love, Imelda.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
