<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Kennedy     11-29 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Kennedy,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Denies Congressman Kennedy Prison Access</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., was refused
permission to visit the so-called Birmingham Six, six prisoners
serving life sentences for IRA bombings in 1974, the Home Office
said Wednesday.
   Kennedy, eldest son of the late Sen. Robert Kennedy, said he was
``very distressed'' his request, made through the British Embassy
in Washington, was denied.
   A world campaign is under way for release of the six prisoners,
who claim they were beaten into confessing and convicted on faulty
forensic evidence.
   The bombings killed 22 people in Birmingham, England. The Irish
Republican Army, which is fighting to rid Northern Ireland of
British rule, claimed responsibility.
   The Home Office said Kennedy's request was denied because he was
not on the prisoners' approved list of visitors. It said logistics
also presented a problem because the six are in three separate
prisons.
   Kennedy met with relatives of the six and campaigners for their
release at Shannon Airport in the Irish Republic.
   He said the Human Rights Caucus in Congress would hold a full
hearing on the case early next year.
</TEXT>
