<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ActressSlain-Cabot     11-29 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Slain-Cabot,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of B-Movie Actress Gets Suspended Sentence in Her Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of B-movie actress Susan Cabot was
given a three-year suspended sentence and placed on probation
Wednesday for the beating death of his mother.
   Timothy Scott Roman originally was charged with murder in the
1986 bludgeoning death of Miss Cabot, 59, who appeared in such
1950s films as ``Machine Gun Kelly'' with Charles Bronson and
``Tomahawk'' with Rock Hudson.
   The sentencing of Roman ended an unusual pair of trials marked
by testimony that Roman, born a dwarf, suffered brain damage from
growth drugs and allegations Roman was the illegitimate son of
Jordan's King Hussein.
   Roman, 25, of Encino was convicted last month of involuntary
manslaughter in a second trial, conducted without a jury before
Superior Court Judge Darlene Schempp. The first trial ended in a
mistrial when Roman's attorney became ill.
   ``The case is a real tragic one. It's hard to walk out and say
you're happy with the result,'' said Roman's second attorney,
Michael White. ``He loved his mother and ... is relieved in the
knowledge he doesn't have to go to jail and can get on and live his
life.''
   Miss Cabot's body was found Dec. 10, 1986, after Roman called
police to the dilapidated Encino home they had shared. She had been
beaten with a barbell.
   Roman initially told officers that he had been beaten
unconscious by a man dressed as a Ninja warrior and awoke to find
his mother dead. But in court he admitted he had fabricated the
story and pleaded innocent by reason of insanity.
   In the second trial, Roman testified his mother's mental state
had badly deteriorated and that she had initiated the violence by
swinging the barbell at him. He said he didn't remember what had
happened next.
   The involuntary manslaughter charge carried a maximum four-year
prison term, but Schempp handed down the three-year prison term,
which she then suspended.
   Roman's defense attorney in the first trial, Chester Smith,
argued part of the insanity defense was based on side effects Roman
suffered from experiments with drugs undertaken to boost his growth.
   Smith, in arguing his client was at risk in jail, said Roman
might be the illegitimate son of King Hussein and could have been a
terrorist target.
   Susan Cabot briefly dated King Hussein in the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
