<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LaborOutlook     11-29 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Labor Outlook,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Board: Small Labor Pool Big Problem Facing U.S. Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shrinking labor pool will be the biggest
problem confronting U.S. businesses in the coming year, according
to a report by the Conference Board.
   The business-research group said Tuesday its Human Resources
Outlook Panel, comprising 10 corporate executives and labor
analysts, predicted that many companies, faced with a continuing
labor shortage, will be forced to hire workers they would not have
hired in the past, such as unskilled workers.
   ``The old days of creaming the country's labor pool for the very
best candidates are over,'' said Audrey Freedman, management
counsellor at the Conference Board. ``Companies will be
increasingly seeking ways to bring people in rather than screening
them out of jobs in the coming decade.''
   The job pool has become smaller as more people are employed and
fewer are looking for work. Women and immigrants are expected to be
the largest group of new job candidates in the 1990s, the
Conference Board said.
   Many large firms have begun seeking employees from foreign
countries and are devoting more time and money toward recruiting,
training and retraining workers, the business-supported research
organization said.
   The Conference Board panel, which meets annual to issue its
labor and economic forecast, said the economy would again escape a
recession in 1990. It projected that the unemployment rate would
average 5.3 percent next year, little changed from its recent
levels.
   Wages would rise an average 5 percent in 1990 and that inflation
will average 4.5 percent, also near its current levels, the panel
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
