<FIRST>r f PM-BuildingContracts     11-29 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Building Contracts,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Down 6 Percent in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction fell 6 percent
in October as contracts for highway and bridge building declined
sharply, according to a survey.
   New contracts fell 6 percent in October to an annual rate of
$262.6 billion, said the survey released Tuesday by the F.W. Dodge
Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co. Its seasonally
adjusted Dodge Index dipped to 167 in October from 178 in September.
   The October decline set back construction contracting to the
level that has prevailed for most of the past two years, the Dodge
Group said.
   ``October's return to the 1988-89 `plateau' of contracting shows
that the basics haven't changed much,'' said George A. Christie,
vice president and chief economist for the consulting group.
   ``Commercial overbuilding and public austerity are conditions
that the construction industry must endure while waiting for lower
interest rates to revive the housing market,'' he said.
   While contracting for highway and bridge construction fell
sharply in October and nonresidential building also declined,
homebuilding activity was stable, the report said.
   Residential building held steady at $121.5 billion as hotel and
motel contracting gained, multi-family projects declined and
single-family homebuilding was steady.
</TEXT>
