<FIRST>r f PM-LincolnS&amp;L-Wall     11-29 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L-Wall,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulator Wall Doesn't Plan to Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrift regulator M. Danny Wall does not plan
to heed the latest call for his resignation, his spokesman said.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, called for
Wall's departure Monday but said he might not be to blame for the
problems of the savings and loan industry.
   Wall declined to respond to Mitchell's statement but his
spokesman, William Fulwider, said Tuesday the senator's complaint
``is hardly grounds for asking for his resignation.''
   ``He has no plans to resign,'' Fulwider said.
   Meanwhile, the leaders of three advocacy groups said they will
demand today that Wall quit. They are Jim Davidson, chairman of the
National Taxpayers Union; Joan B. Claybrook, president of Public
Citizen, a group founded by consumer activist Ralph Nader, and Alan
L. Keyes, president of Citizens Against Government Waste.
   They will be joined by Bert Ely, an Alexandria, Va., analyst
frequently at odds with Wall over estimates of the S&amp;L industry's
losses.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, has written to President Bush suggesting that Wall step
aside. The president's response has been less than warm support.
   ``If part of the savings and loan problem proves to be
management or regulation people that aren't aggressive enough, the
answer will be yes,'' Bush said when asked about Gonzalez' letter.
   Gonzalez' committee has been investigating the collapse of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif., expected to
become the nation's largest S&amp;L failure at a cost to taxpayers of
$2 billion.
   The panel charges that Wall ignored a recommendation to seize
Lincoln and stem its losses two years before the thrift was taken
over.
   Wall maintains that there was insufficient evidence to legally
take that action. Nevertheless, pressure has been building for him
to quit.
   The Wall Street Journal called for his resignation in an
editorial this week. And, according to industry sources who spoke
on condition of anonymity, White House advisers led by counsel C.
Boyden Gray are pushing for Wall's ouster.
   However, an administration source, who also spoke on condition
of anonymity, said Wall enjoys some support within the Treasury
Department, which counts on his vote on the five-member board
governing the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., an independent
agency which insures bank and S&amp;L deposits.
   Under S&amp;L legislation passed in August, Wall's term extends
until July 1, 1991. He previously served as chairman of the Federal
Home Loan Bank Board, but under the new law's regulatory
reorganization, he now serves as director of the Office of Thrift
Supervision, an arm of the Treasury Department.
</TEXT>
