<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BritishAirways     11-29 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-British Airways,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways Chairman Calls For Open Skies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of British Airways says he has no
plans for further attempts to buy an interest in United Airlines
but said his company still wants to become the first ``truly global
airline.''
   British Airways Chairman Lord King said Tuesday the United
States and the European Community should merge into one trading
bloc, beginning with open skies for airlines on both sides of the
Atlantic.
   King criticized two bills in Congress that would give
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner increased power to stop
foreign control of U.S. carriers. Skinner also opposes the
legislation, saying he already has enough power to limit foreign
involvement in U.S. aviation.
   King, speaking on the eve of British-U.S. talks over the
possible revision of bilateral air service agreements, said that
despite his call for open skies, he won't advocate any further
opening of routes or investments to U.S. carriers in Europe without
reciprocal benefits.
   ``I am not advocating and will not practice unilateral
commercial disarmament,'' King told a group of U.S. and British
business executives.
   Asked after the speech if he still had an interest in buying
into UAL Corp., parent company of United Airlines, after a deal for
an employee-management buyout of the airline fell through, King
said: ``Not in the foreseeable future.''
   British Airways would have gained a 15 percent interest in the
new UAL.
   King said, however, that British Airways would continue to
``widen and deepen'' its marketing agreements with United and
possibly make similar agreements with other U.S. carriers.
   ``We shall continue to pursue our ambition to be the first
truely global airline,'' he said.
   King said the United deal, which failed to get the needed
financing, was skewed ``by the need to restrict the level of
(foreign) participation to what would be acceptable to the U.S.
government.''
   U.S. law allows no more than 25 percent foreign interest in the
voting stock of an American carrier.
   King said that even though 27 percent of British Airways is
owned by Americans, it likely would not have been allowed to
acquire more than 15 percent of a U.S. airline.
   He noted that Skinner forced a reduction of KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines interest in the takeover of Northwest Airlines' parent
company, NWA Inc.
   King said he would continue to encourage his government to
resist U.S. carriers' efforts to gain additional services to
Manchester and other British cities unless British Airways is
allowed to serve more U.S. cities.
   ``Disparity in market strength has enabled the U.S. to trade
limited access to the American market for larger access to the
European,'' he said.
   But after 1992, when 12 European markets unite, conditions will
change, he said.
   ``Do not expect the nations of Europe to continue to accept such
an unequal state of affairs,'' King said.
   He said European states are expected to open all of their routes
to all airlines within the European community, and the United
States could be part of the community.
   But he added, ``If Europe is to be open to U.S. airlines, the
United States must be opened to European airlines.''
</TEXT>
