<DOCNO> AP891129-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FamilyMedia     11-29 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Media,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Health Magazine Aimed at Older Audience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new magazine on science and health topics
geared toward people over age 50 is planned for next spring from
Family Media Inc., the publisher of such magazines as Discover and
Health.
   Family Media says the digest-sized magazine will be called
Breakthroughs in Health and Science. It plans to publish the
magazine every other month with a circulation projected at 400,000.
   Meanwhile, the editor-in-chief of Health, Dianne Partie Lange,
said Tuesday she has resigned as a result of a series of recent
changes affecting her magazine.
   Among the changes are a planned 27 percent reduction in Health's
circulation rate base, cutting the frequency of publication to 10
times a year from 12 and the appointment of two editorial directors
to oversee Family Media's 11 magazines.
   Ms. Lange said she had not been consulted in advance about the
moves.
   ``The magazine I was recruited to produce is not the magazine
the company wants to continue with,'' Ms. Lange said. She had been
editor since April 1988.
   Breakthroughs is being designed to appeal to older consumers
interested in ``noteworthy advances in health, medicine, psychology
and other sciences,'' the company said.
   Gregory Dunn, group president of Family Media Publications, said
Tuesday that advertisers are starting to realize the potential of
the growing group of older consumers although few have begun
spending much to reach them.
   He said the launch of Breakthroughs should put Family Media in a
position to benefit over the next few years as appreciation for the
market builds.
   A number of publishers have shown an interest in developing
magazines for older readers or giving advertisers a chance to buy
space only in issues of their magazines that go to older
subscribers.
   Dunn said Science Digest, with a circulation of 250,000, would
be folded into Breakthroughs. Older subscribers to Health would be
encouraged to switch to Breakthroughs as well.
   The last issue of Science Digest probably will be published in
March with Breakthroughs starting in May, Dunn said.
   Health will continue to feature stories on food, nutrition,
fitness, medicine, fashion and beauty, targeting younger women, he
said.
   But Family Media said that because Health will be aimed at a
younger readership, its rate base will be cut to 800,000 in
February 1990 from 1.1 million.
   The decision to publish Health and another monthly, Savvy Woman,
only 10 times a year brings them in line with five other Family
Media magazines _ Golf Illustrated, Homeowner, Model, Taxi and Your
Family, which Family Media previously disclosed would be launched
in January in doctor's waiting rooms.
   Family Media also named two editorial directors for its
magazines.
   Paul Hoffman, 33, editor of Discover, will serve as editorial
director of of 1001 Home Ideas, Health, Homeowner and Breakthroughs.
   Neil Amdur, 49, editor of World Tennis, will be editorial
director for Golf Illustrated, Savvy Woman, Taxi, Model and Your
Family.
   Ms. Lange said her decision to resign was ``the culmination'' of
those and other recent decisions by Family Media management.
   ``When I was recruited, I was told this was to be serious
contender in health marketplace,'' Ms. Lange said.
   She said her editorial staff produced such a magazine, but that
Family Media appeared unwilling to spend enough on promotion and
distribution.
   Ms. Lange, 44, said she is ``exploring possibilities'' in the
wake of Monday's abrupt resignation. She was an editorial executive
at Self magazine for nine years before taking the top editorial
post at Health.
</TEXT>
