<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 0808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Jaguar     11-29 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Jaguar,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford's Jaguar Acquisition Won't Be Opposed by FTC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co.'s acquisition of the British
luxury car maker Jaguar PLC won't be opposed by the Federal Trade
Commission.
   The FTC and the Justice Department agreed on Nov. 21 to waive
the remainder of a 30-day waiting period begun after Ford and
Jaguar announced the acquisition plan Nov. 2, said John Sipple,
chief of the FTC's premerger notification office.
   ``We still have the option to take action, but it is rare,''
Sipple said in a telephone interview from his office in Washington.
   He said he was unaware of any other government agency dealing
with Ford's move.
   On Nov. 2, Ford and Jaguar announced an agreement that the No. 2
U.S. automaker would buy the British company for about $2.5
billion. But before any such purchase, Jaguar shareholders must
rescind a bylaw that limits any individual or company from owning
more than 15 percent of the shares.
   Michael Cook, a spokesman for Jaguar's U.S. importing and
marketing company, said Tuesday that vote is set for Friday in
London. The Jaguar board has endorsed waiving its ``golden share''
rule and is supporting the Ford acquisition.
   The Jaguar acquisition raised some eyebrows on Wall Street.
   Immediately after it was announced, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. put
some of Ford's securities on its CreditWatch list for a possible
downgrade in credit rating. On Tuesday, S&amp;P removed the securities
from that list and affirmed their ratings as being in categories
that are among the highest used by the firm.
   Moody's Investor Service Inc., the other major securities-rating
firm in New York, took no immediate action after the announcement.
</TEXT>
