<FIRST>r f PM-Prime-SouthwestBank     11-29 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime-Southwest Bank,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southwest Bank Retreats On Prime Rate Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southwest Bank, which made headlines by
trimming its prime lending rate three weeks ago, has quietly raised
the rate back to 10.5 percent from 10 percent.
   Southwest had stood alone in lowering the key interest rate,
which reflects a bank's cost of borrowing money and is used in
calculating business and consumer loans.
   The bank, which raised its prime on Tuesday, said it reversed
its earlier decision due to recent moves by the the Federal Reserve
to keep interest rates firm.
   The Fed, performing a quick about-face, had drained money from
the nation's banking system on Monday, driving the so-called
federal funds rate upward. The fed funds rate is the interest on
overnight loans between banks and is closely watched as an
indicator of the central bank's policy on interest rates.
   ``It looks like the Fed doesn't intend to move the rate lower,''
said I.A. Long, Southwest's chairman-emeritus, who has made his
reputation by repeatedly being the first banker in the country to
cut the prime.
</TEXT>
