<FIRST>u f PM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING f0037 to restore dropped 1st Ld-Writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with comments from UAE officials;
editing thruout</HEAD>
<HEAD>OPEC Deal Expected To Prop Up Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC's latest production deal should help
slow a decline in oil prices in the first half of 1990 by partially
succeeding in reducing cheating on quotas by the cartel's 13
members, analysts say.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' oil ministers
on Tuesday signed a pact under which their daily production ceiling
will rise to 22 million barrels from 20.5 million barrels in the
current quarter.
   The group's $18-a-barrel target price becomes a ``minimum
reference price.''
   The producers' output is actually up to 23.5 million barrels a
day, and the new accord should bring it down to some 22.8 million
barrels a day, analysts say.
   That means prices for North Sea Brent Blend, for example, likely
will drop to $17 a barrel instead of to $16 a barrel, in the
spring, when demand for oil usually slackens, analysts say.
   The spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, was $18.15 a barrel Wednesday morning,
down from $18.30 a barrel late Tuesday.
   OPEC's price of crude oil stood at $17.74 a barrel, said the
cartel's secretary-general, Subroto.
   ``We feel that if it deviates too much from the minimum
reference price, then we will meet,'' Subroto told a news
conference.
   In the meantime, OPEC's eight-member monitoring committee plans
to meet in March ``in order to assess the market,'' the ministers
said in a communique.
   Leading oil ministers were upeat about the pact.
   Hisham Nazer, Saudi Arabia's influential oil minister, told
reporters that prices ``will steadily go up after the market
ascertains the durability of the agreement. There is more
discipline now, there is more commitment to the quota and the
production ceiling.''
   The deal should cut production by up to 1.3 million barrels a
day, he said.
   Fergus MacLeod, an oil analyst with the London investment firm
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., agreed: ``It looks better than most
people thought was possible.''
   The ministers came up with a partial solution to demands from
Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates for bigger portions of the
production. The two have been producing about double their current
quotas.
   Kuwait agreed Tuesday to a quota of 1.5 million barrels a day,
up from its previous quota of 1.15 million barrels a day, but below
its current output of 2 million barrels a day.
   The United Arab Emirates officially agreed to a steady daily
quota of 1.095 million barrels.
   But United Arab Emirates oil minister Mana Saeed Otaiba said his
country got behind-the-scenes clearance from OPEC to produce 2
million barrels a day. That would be less than the country's
current output, which Otaiba pegged at 2.6 million barrels a day.
   Otaiba also warned that the U.A.E.'s output would surpass 2
million barrels a day if there were excesses by other OPEC members.
   ``Agreement and understanding was reached with the oil ministers
to allow the United Arab Emirates to produce 2 million barrels
daily,'' Otaiba was quoted as saying by Abu Dhabi's official news
agency WAM.
   But OPEC's overall producion still will be well above the
expected demand of 21.5 million barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
