<HEAD>Report: Commodities Probe Widens to S&amp;P 500 Pit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal investigation into illegal commodity
trading has been broadened to include a fifth trading pit, Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, a report published
today said.
   The Chicago Sun-Times, citing unidentified sources close to the
invetigation, said that at least seven brokers in the trading pit
have been subpoenaed as part of the probe that has resulted in the
indictments of 47 traders and one clerk.
   At least two others were expected to receive subpoenas to appear
before a federal grand jury this week, the sources said.
   Until this week the investigation had been confined to traders
in the Merc's Japanese yen and Swiss Franc pits and the Chicago
Board of Trade's soybean and U.S. Treasury Bond pits.
   Investigators either at the Merc or the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission first raised questions about trading in the
Standard &amp; Poor's pit and alerted the U.S. Attorney's office, which
took over the case, the newspaper said.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas declined comment Tuesday, as did
authorities of the Merc and the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission.
