<FIRST>d f BC-InsurerInsolvency     11-29 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Insurer Insolvency,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Declares Life Insurance Company Insolvent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State regulators have declared Pacific
Standard Life Insurance Co. insolvent by $54 million and have
ordered the company to stop conducting business.
   The California Department of Insurance said Tuesday that the
company was being run ``in a manner hazardous to its policyholders,
creditors and the public.''
   Pacific Standard, which has sold $7 billion worth of life and
indemnity insurance nationwide, acknowledged it was insolvent but
said the shortfall was less than claimed by the state.
   The company on Tuesday laid off 30 percent of its 155 employees.
It also imposed a moratorium to prevent customers from cashing out
their policies for six months, but will continue to pay annuities
and death benefits.
   Pacific Standard was acquired six years ago by Southmark Corp.,
a Dallas real estate syndicator that filed for Chapter 11 federal
bankruptcy protection in June.
   A prelimiarny estimates showed that Pacific Standard has assets
of $533 million and liabilities of $574 million, said Deputy
Insurance Commissioner Don Rosen.
   Susan Ridell, Pacific Standard's chief financial officer, said
the company's financial woes stemmed from heavy investments in
high-yield, high-risk ``junk'' bonds under former management.
</TEXT>
