<FIRST>u f PM-Shearson     11-29 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shearson,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Announces Management Reshuffle, Corporate Realignment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. announced today a
corporate realignment and management reshuffle that included the
reassignment of company president Jeffrey B. Lane to a lesser
position.
   The move reflected the continuing turmoil at the nation's
second-largest investment firm, which over the past month announced
layoffs of hundreds of workers and a sharp reduction in stockbroker
commissions.
   Peter A. Cohen, Shearson's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in a statement today that the company was dividing its
businesses into four groups: Capital Markets, Investment and
Merchant Banking, Private Client and Subsidiary Activities.
   Other big Wall Street firms have made similar realignments in
recent years.
   Lane was reassigned to head the Subsidiary Activities Group,
which will include Shearson's money management businesses including
its Boston Co. division, Cohen said.
   Robert S. Fuld Jr., who currently heads Shearson's taxable
fixed-income division, was seen as replacing Lane as Cohen's
second-in-command, although Fuld was not given the title of
Shearson's president.
   Fuld was named president of Shearson's Capital Markets Group,
which will include the company's worldwide capital markets
activities. He will also oversee Shearson's administrative side.
   Shearson, which is 61 percent-owned by American Express Co.,
also announced it was disbanding its chief policy-making committee,
the 11-member policy group, but was creating a business development
committee to ``help identify future directions for the firm.''
   Today's announcement was expected. Shearson said earlier this
month that it was in the process of reshuffling its businesses.
   Last week, Shearson also said it would cut broker commissions by
1 percent to 2 percent in 1990, and on Nov. 7, it said it had begun
laying off employees in a cutback that could total 2 percent by the
end of the year.
   Analysts have said the changes at Shearson stem from American
Express' desire to reduce its stake in the investment firm, but
wants Shearson to first improve its profitability.
   The company is also trying to stave off a possible lowering of
its credit rating by Moody's Investors Service.
   In the third quarter, Shearson said it earned $66 million, but
most of that came from a one-time $77 million pretax gain from the
sale of its Lehman Management Co. and investment banking fees from
the merger of Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.
   Shearson also announced today that the Investment and Merchant
Banking Group will be headed by Sherman R. Lewis Jr., and that
Hardwick Simmons will serve as president of the Private Client
Group, which is Shearson's brokerage operations.
   Lewis will also oversee Shearson's human resources department,
the company said.
</TEXT>
