<FIRST>r f PM-Shuttle-Probe 1stLd-Writethru f0032 11-29 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Probing Charges of Shuttle Parts Not Properly Inspected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with grand jury convening; Picks
up 6th graf pvs, He said ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury convened today to
investigate a Thiokol Corp. engineer's allegations of improper
inspections of shuttle parts since the Challenger disaster.
   U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson said he could not comment on the
probe or any other matter the grand jury, holding its regular
session, might look into. He said he expects the panel to complete
its work by Friday.
   Steve Lawson, a spokesman for Utah-based Thiokol, said Tuesday
the company was asked to provide information about instrumentation
in the redesigned rocket motors that were used beginning with the
Discovery flight on Sept. 30, 1988.
   A quality control engineer for Thiokol, Dan Joos, said Tuesday
he wrote a memo to his superiors citing improper inspection
procedures in some equipment used on shuttle missions. Joos, who
has been subpoenaed to appear before the grand jury, said his
superiors forwarded the memo NASA.
   He said Challenger and the three subsequent shuttles may have
operated with inaccurate equipment because of improper inspections.
   He said up to 50 percent of the data measured on shuttle flights
may be inaccurate _ which means ``we could lose another shuttle
today.''
   Royce Mitchell, manager of the solid rocket booster program at
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, said the grand jury
probe probably would be confined to the first three shuttle flights
after the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger explosion.
   Several hundred changes were made to the shuttle solid rocket
boosters after the Challenger exploded.
   One of the major parts of the booster that was redesigned was
the field joint blamed in the Challenger accident.
   The joints are formed when the huge booster segments are stacked
at the Kennedy Space Center in Cape Canaveral, Fla. Cold launch
temperatures prevented O-rings from sealing the joints, allowing
gas to escape.
   A Thiokol spokesman, Rocky Raab, said Tuesday night that the
government ``has requested Thiokol Corporation to provide
additional information relating to the redesigned solid rocket
motors used in the space shuttle program.
   ``The information deals with instrumentation used on the first
three flights using the redesigned solid rocket motors
(post-Challenger flights.) The instrumentation and the motors on
which it was used were flown successfully and fulfilled NASA's
mission requirements.''
   Raab said he did not know who requested the information and said
he was not familiar with Joos.
   ``We know as little about it as you do at the moment,'' he said.
``This was all the information we were able to gather this
afternoon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Penney     11-29 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Penney,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney's Chief Operating Officer Retiring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Miller, chief operating officer of J.C.
Penney's store and catalog division, is retiring after 37 years
with the retailer, and board vice chairman Robert Gill will take
the job starting March 1, it was announced Wednesday.
   Gill currently is in charge of finance, credit, consumer banking
services, auditing, business services and insurance operations for
J.C. Penney Co. Inc.
   He started as a buyer trainee in 1953 and has been a merchandise
manager, director of merchandise operations and director of
corporate personnel. He was elected a vice president in 1969, a
senior vice president in 1981 and a vice chairman of the board in
1982.
   Miller joined Penney as a sales clerk in 1953 and advanced to
district manager by 1969. He was appointed director of regional
coordination in 1972 and elected a regional vice president in 1976.
He became president of J.C. Penney Stores and Catalog in 1983 and
the same year was elected to the board of directors. He assumed his
present position running Penney store and catalog operations in
1987.
   In other organizational changes, the board of directors elected
Robert Northam and Richard Erickson executive vice presidents,
effective Feb. 1. Ted Spurlock was elected a senior vice president,
effective Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
