<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Cooper Adv03   11-29 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Cooper, Adv 03,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 3 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kenneth Cooper Pumps Money Out of Pumping Iron</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Kenneth Cooper is keeping the aerobics
movement alive with a bottom-line pitch to executives: ``Good
fitness is good business.''
   Cooper helped start the fitness boom more than 20 years ago with
his best-selling book, ``Aerobics,'' and he has not let the profits
of the boom slip through his well-exercised fingers.
   Cooper has developed five health centers on 30 acres in one of
Dallas's most pricey neighborhoods. Some of the city's best-known
executives and celebrities pay $900 a year here to grunt, growl and
trudge their way to fitness.
   The complex includes a hotel for the health-conscious, exercise
facilities, a research institute and a clinic Cooper aims to make
``the Mayo Clinic of preventive medicine.''
   Treadmills, exercise bicycles and rowing machines are found
throughout the colonial-style complex. Outside, a mile-long
rubberized track winds around the landscaped grounds, over
picturesque footbridges and through groves of trees.
   Cooper says that many corporations foot the bill for their
executives' membership _ both as a perk to attract quality
management and in the belief healthy executives are better
executives.
   President Bush and former Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach
have worked out at the complex. Still, Cooper said, ``That doesn't
mean we don't have the flight attendants (and) busboys.''
   Health club members provide fodder for studies conducted at the
Cooper's Institute for Aerobics Research. After each workout
members use computer terminals to record their performances, which
become raw data for institute researchers.
   The institute's research has led to more than 600 books,
monographs and articles, including Cooper's highly publicized,
15-year study released this month showing even a modest amount of
exercise can prolong life.
   It all was ``a great big gamble'' in 1970, when Cooper quit as
the Air Force senior flight surgeon to follow his dream of creating
``the preventive medicine center of the world.''
   No bank would lend him the money to get started, despite the
success of his 1968 book ``Aerobics,'' so Cooper borrowed $1.2
million from Tyler Corp. to buy a mansion and 22 acres on Dallas's
prestigious Preston Road. Since then _ while writing eight more
books and signing contracts for three more _ Cooper has pumped at
least $11 million into construction and the purchase of an adjacent
church to house the non-profit research institute.
   He says the institute is the reason for the rest of the
operation. Other divisions are:
   _ The Cooper Clinic, where nine doctors practice Cooper's
preaching of preventive medicine. A physical, complete with
nutritional screening and a treadmill stress test, takes at least
six hours and costs $850. Add cancer screening and the cost is
$1,159.
   _ The in-residence programs: four-, seven- or 13-day stays where
participants learn to be healthy. In addition to a physical, the
program includes visits to restaurants and grocery stores where
clients learn how to order and shop to avoid unhealthy food. The
cost runs from $1,595 for the four-day program to $4,695 for a
13-day stay in a private suite.
   Cooper defends the cost, some of which can be borne by insurance
companies, saying other programs offer less for more money.
   _The guest lodge, besides providing housing for the in-residence
programs in its two buildings, also is an operating hotel with the
usual services and amenities.
   There are other programs offered, including training for several
government agencies such as the Internal Revenue Service and the
Bureau of Prisons.
   The budget is $12 million a year. Cooper said the center is
profitable, but wouldn't say how profitable.
   Michael Evans was one of the first to sign on at the Aerobics
Center, which opened 19 years ago.
   ``I came out here so I can stay fit so I can work more
effectively,'' said Evans, a 62-year-old insurance executive who
credits exercise for keeping him from triple-bypass heart surgery
and helping him stand the stress of a mid-career job change.
   ``This place has a sense of urgency,'' he said, pointing out
that there are no after-jogging cocktails or partying to negate the
good done by the exercise. ``Everybody's here for their own
well-being, not just that country club appearance.''
   While Cooper likes to mention how George Bush ran around the
center's track with a pack of Secret Service agents, another
well-known member brought the center unwanted notoriety.
   On May 1, 1985, CBS television sportscaster Frank Glieber was
walking around the center's track when he suffered a fatal heart
attack.
   Cooper says Glieber, whom he described as a close friend, ``had
let himself go.'' But Cooper also noted joggers have logged 7
million miles on the Aerobic Center tracks, and Glieber's death and
two ``non-fatal cardiac events'' were the only emergencies.
   The death of another jogging guru, Jim Fixx, in 1984, plus
Glieber's attack, led Cooper to write ``Running Without Fear.''
   ``There is no panacea,'' he says. ``We have to keep this thing
in perspective.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Dec. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
