<FIRST>s f BC-RoachWar Adv03   11-29 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Roach War, Adv 03,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 3 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pest Pursuers Battle Over Cockroach Eradication Methods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of Combat and Raid have locked
antennae over the lucrative cockroach-killing market, trading
charges in advertising and federal court.
   Raid maker S.C. Johnson &amp; Co. has been in the business longer,
giving it an advantage over the larger American Cyanamid Co., which
introduced its Combat line only in 1985.
   Even so, American Cyanamid is posing a serious threat to S.C.
Johnson, or Johnson Wax as the privately owned Racine, Wis.-based
company is usually known.
   Cyanamid fired a double-barreled blast in U.S. District Court,
accusing Johnson Wax in separate lawsuits of false advertising and
trademark infringement.
   Johnson Wax counter-sued, charging that Cyanamid's advertising
made its own false claims. Both are asking for corrective
television commercials and damages.
   While the legal battles go on, Cyanamid's Combat has garnered
more than 12 percent of the half-billion-dollar home insecticide
market, making it second to Johnson's Raid, which has about 47
percent, according to industry estimates.
   ``Johnson Wax seems to be the one that's scrambling to do
whatever it can to defend its market-share position,'' said Harvey
Stober, a Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. analyst.
   Stober said Johnson Wax's zeal may be leading it to excesses in
advertising and packaging. ``Everyone,'' he said, ``wants to be the
bigger roach killer.''
   The court cases are pending before U.S. District Judge John
Bissell. The judge dealt Wayne, N.J.-based Cyanamid a preliminary
blow in August. Another hearing is set for January.
   The story begins April 26, when Johnson Wax unveiled its Raid
Max line in a media splash at the Chicago Academy of Sciences.
Johnson Wax has said it would spend $100 million to advertise the
line, its first since Raid hit the market in 1956. The line
includes an aerosol spray killer, fogger and bait trap. Combat has
the same line-up.
   Two days after the introduction, Cyanamid launched its first
suit, accusing Johnson Wax of violating a Cyanamid trademark for
its ``Maxforce'' line, directed at exterminators and not home users.
   In court papers, the company said Maxforce products this year
would bring in $3 million. Advertising cost $1 million.
   ``Cyanamid's claim that RAID Max is likely to be confused with
MAXFORCE is, in my judgment, something no competent marketing
person would say to his peers and expect to be believed,'' said
Raid's product manager, Ravichandra K. Saligram, in an affidavit.
   To a point, Bissell agreed. In an opinion filed Aug. 30, he
refused to issue a temporary ban on the use of ``Max,'' saying
there was no compelling need for such an order in advance of a
fuller hearing.
   But even as lawyers were arguing the question on Aug. 28 before
Bissell, Cyanamid came to court with another suit.
   Johnson Wax advertisements aired last spring falsely claimed
that Raid fumigators _ bombs that release a cloud of smoke lethal
to cockroaches _ killed Combat survivors; sought out roaches while
Combat was passive; went ``everywhere;'' outkilled Combat; and
worked three hours after use, Cyanamid charged.
   Actually, Combat's maker said, Combat leaves no survivors and
kills remote roaches when they cannibalize infected victims.
Moreover, it said, the fumigators don't live up to the claims.
   Combat ads, meanwhile, had been running in August. And now it
was Johnson Wax's turn.
   In its own filing, the Wisconsin company said the Combat
commercials falsely claimed the fumigator's odor could be smelled.
   ``In fact, the user smells only the pleasant scent of aromatic
ingredients in the product,'' said the papers.
   Cyanamid also falsely claimed roaches don't come back to a home
treated by Combat, and that Combat was more powerful than a
fumigator, Johnson Wax said.
   Cyanamid last month sent out a wave of attorneys to question
Johnson Wax's ad people, researchers and testers.
   Bissell will hold a hearing in January on the dispute, said
Cyanamid attorney Donald Robinson.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Dec. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
