<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Little Changed In Quiet Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders awaited news of new
export sales.
   In the absence of significant new foreign sales of U.S. grain,
talk among traders turned to this weekend's superpower summit
meeting and the prospects that it could lead to more grain sales to
the Soviet Union.
   ``They have more than a passing interest in the Bush-Gorbachev
talks,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department
Inc., a brokers' advisory service in Chicago.
   Hopes for future export sales of wheat were supported by a
prediction from a U.S. Agriculture Department official that the
Soviets may re-enter the U.S. wheat market in January.
   But the official, Frank Gomme, a USDA food grains marketing
specialist, also said China's wheat import needs were filled
through March.
   Contracts for spring and summer deliveries of wheat gained
slightly in reaction to Tuesday's National Weather Service
forecasts for below-normal precipitation in the great plains this
winter.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent lower to 1 cent
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a
bushel; corn futures were { cent lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.33} a bushel; oats were { cent lower across the
board with December at $1.43\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to
3\ cents higher with January at $5.79} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, led by limit losses in the pork-belly market
in reaction to news that the USDA had accepted offers on 920,000
pounds of pork bellies for export to Poland at 78.84 cents to 80.45
cents a pound.
   Live cattle futures were .42 cent lower to .05 cent higher with
December at 75.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .38 cent lower
to .05 cent higher with November at 83.60 cents a pound; live hogs
were .25 cent lower to .05 cent higher with December at 50.60 cents
a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to the limit 2 cents
lower with February at 60.55 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
