<HEAD>London Stocks Finish Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices finished generally higher in thin trading
Wednesday on London's Stock Exchange with few substantive
developments to affect the overall market.
   Traders said shares in financial and insurance sectors sold
well, with some insurance stocks invigorated by takeover
speculation.
   ``People are gearing themselves into a cautionary mode,'' one
trader said. ``It must be because they think the market is going
down and the only sector for dividend growth is financials.''
   Lingering uncertainty over the direction of British interest
rates has subdued buying interest, dealers said.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
had gained 13.6 points, or 0.6 percent, to 2,255.6.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 13.4 points
at 1,781.7. Volume a sketchy 418.3 million shares, compared with
437.6 million shares at Tuesday's close.
   London dealers complained that Wall Street provided little
leadership during the afternoon and movements in New York were
largely shrugged off.
