<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Hanson     11-29 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Hanson,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Net Earnings Fall 54 Percent at Britain's Hanson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hanson PLC, a British industrial conglomerate
with large U.S. holdings, said Wednesday its fourth-quarter profit
fell about 54 percent as a result of one-time factors, while
operating profit was higher.
   Hanson's net profit, according to British accounting principles,
fell to $318 million from $685 million in the quarter ended Sept.
30. The decline came because of a tax charge in the 1989 quarter
and large one-time gains on asset sales made in the 1988 quarter,
Hanson said. Profit before taxes and one-time items rose to $520
million from $444 million.
   Earnings per American depository receipt on a fully diluted
basis rose to 44 cents a share from 39 cents a share, according to
British accounting principles. In Britain, earnings per ADR are
calculated on pre-tax profits, before tax and extraordinary
one-time items.
   Sales in the quarter rose to $3.04 billion from $2.95 billion a
year earlier.
   For the full fiscal year, net income fell to $1.78 billion from
$1.81 billion because of decreased gains from asset sales. Profit
before taxes and one-time items rose to $1.72 billion from $1.42
billion.
   Earnings per American depository receipt on a fully diluted
basis rose to $1.49 a share from $1.28. Yearly sales fell to $11.3
billion from $11.9 billion.
   Lord Hanson, the chairman, said Hanson ended the year with $8.5
billion in cash and a substantial borrowing capacity, putting it in
a ``commanding position'' to make more acquisitions when they
become available at realistic prices.
   Hanson's U.S. properties include SCM Chemicals, Jacuzzi,
Farberware, Endicott Johnson and Frye footwear, Universal Gym, Gold
Fields Mining and minority interests in Smith-Corona typewriters
and Newmont Mining. British properties include Imperial Tobacco and
Consolidated Gold Fields, which it acquired earlier this year for
$5.7 billion, Britain's largest takeover ever.
   Dollar figures for the 1989 and 1988 periods were converted from
British pounds at the Sept. 30 rate of $1.615 to the pound.
   Each ADR represents five British shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
