<HEAD>Cyclops ESOP Falls Through</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MT. LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyclops Industries Inc. said it has
ended plans to sell its specialty steel unit to its employees under
a stock ownership plan.
   The company declined to comment on why negotiations, which began
last June, failed.
   However, a spokesman for the United Steelworkers union said
Tuesday that Cyclops had turned down the employees final $50
million offer for Cytemp Specialty Steel Division.
   Virgil Colucci, president of United Steelworkers Local 178, said
bankers balked at providing all of the money for the buyout but
that employees still held out hope something could be worked out.
   James F. Will, Cyclops president and chief executive officer,
said, ``We have not totally broken off discussions with the
proposed ESOP, but a transaction with this group appears unlikely.''
   The division's 1,200 employees produce alloys, high-performance
stainless and other steels at plants in Titusville, Bridgeville and
Pittsburgh.
