trading sessions.
   Analysts said the stock and bond markets largely ignored reports
on third-quarter Gross National Product and corporate profits.
   Larry Wachtel, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
said investors are focusing on the current quarter.
   ``As far as the market is concerned, that is dated material,''
Wachtel said. ``We now know the economy is floundering and
corporate profits are floundering.''
   The Commerce Department reported today that the economy grew at
an annual rate of 2.7 percent in the third quarter, slightly higher
than the 2.5 percent forecast last month.
   A second report showed that corporate profits were down 7.2
percent in the July-September period.
   Analysts said the data was not likely to prompt any action by
the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates to stimulate the
economy.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.35 to 190.99.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
0.66 to 374.44.
