<FIRST>r f BC-GreatWestern     11-29 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Great Western,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Western Predicts Surprise Big Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Western Financial Corp., the
nation's second largest thrift holding company, estimates it will
lose $75 million in the fourth quarter as a result of its decision
to raise reserves for troubled real estate loans.
   The company said Tuesday that it will add as much as $200
million to its reserves to cover problem loans in 22 states.
   The projected quarterly loss, which amounts to 60 cents a share,
would be the first in seven years for Great Western, which has
assets of $37 billion and is considered to be one of the nation's
healthiest and conservative savings and loan companies.
   For the first nine months this year, Great Western had net
income of $177 million, or $1.37 a share. During the 1988 fourth
quarter, the company earned $59.7 million, or 47 cents a share.
   Analysts had expected Great Western, whose principal subsidiary
is Great Western Bank, to show some problems with loans. But they
said the write-downs were greater than expected.
   ``Great Western is one of the Rolls-Royces of the business,''
said Jonathan Gray, of Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. in New York.
``It's not a case where you expect to see any engine trouble, or
even any sputtering.''
</TEXT>
