<FIRST>r f BC-LIN-McCaw 1stLd-Writhethru f0138 11-29 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-LIN-McCaw, 1st Ld-Writhethru, f0138,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Board Defers Action on Revised McCaw Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT to LIN board sted McCaw.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. said Wednesday its board
deferred taking a position on a revised $3.4 billion offer from
McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. for a controlling interest in
the company.
   LIN has already reached an agreement with BellSouth Corp., the
regional telephone company based in Atlanta, for a merger of their
cellular interests.
   That proposal is being presented to LIN shareholders for a vote
on Jan. 12.
   The New York-based cellular concern, which also owns seven
television stations and a specialty publishing business, said its
board will continue its evaluation of McCaw's offer and expects to
``come to a determination in the near term based on all then
relevant information and developmnets.''
   ``Pending such determination, the board continues to recommend
that stockholders not tender common stock to McCaw at this time,''
the statement said.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular telephone company, has
offered $150 a share for 22.5 million shares of LIN stock, an
amount that would lift its stake in LIN to 51.2 percent.
   It has also asked that LIN submit its offer to shareholders for
a vote at the same time as they vote on the LIN-BellSouth deal.
   If it refuses, McCaw has threatened to mount a proxy fight for
control of the LIN board at the Jan. 12 meeting.
   The LIN board set the close of business Dec. 8 as the record
date for determining the stockholders entitled to participate in
McCaw's consent solicitation to replace a majority of the board
should McCaw decide to pursue that course of action.
</TEXT>
