<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a lackluster session
marked by lack of significant supply-and-demand developments.
   Much of the attention was focused on U.S.-Soviet relations and
the chances that this weekend's superpower summit could lead to
more sales of U.S. wheat to the Soviet Union.
   Hopes for future export sales of wheat were supported by a USDA
official's prediction that the Soviets may re-enter the U.S. wheat
market in January.
   But some traders took it as a bearish sign that Soviet
legislators had adjourned for the year without liberalizing
emigration policies.
   The United States has tied Soviet emigration policies to trade,
indicating it may grant the Soviet Union most-favored-nation trade
status if the Soviets relax emigration restrictions.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.05} a bushel; corn
futures were { cent to 2 cents higher with December at $2.34} a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent lower with December at $1.42} a
bushel; soybeans were } cent lower to 3{ cents higher with January
at $5.79 a bushel.
