<FIRST>r f AM-AT&amp;T-Mexico     11-29 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T-Mexico,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Announces New Services for Mexican Border Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. said
Wednesday it was giving the Mexican economy a ``vote of
confidence'' by upgrading its offerings of products and services to
U.S. maquiladora factories in northern Mexico.
   The maquiladoras are border assembly plants permitted under a
tariff-reduction agreement between the countries that provide jobs
to Mexicans and low-cost assembly to American companies.
   AT&amp;T's upgraded offerings include 800 toll-free service, private
lines, office phones and switches, facsimile machines and computers.
   AT&amp;T's announcement comes on the heels of a U.S. trade mission
to Mexico last week that included Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher and John Hinds, president of AT&amp;T International.
   ``We're very encouraged by what President (Carlos) Salinas and
his team have accomplished and the track they're on,'' Hinds said
in an interview.
   Hinds said AT&amp;T hopes to offer upgraded products and services
throughout Mexico in coming months, working with Mexico's telephone
administrations, Telmex and Telnor, as well as the Secretariat of
Communications and Transportation.
   MCI Communications Corp. is negotiating with Telmex on upgrading
service offerings, spokeswoman Jane Levene said. MCI currently
offers basic long-distance and telex services.
</TEXT>
