<FIRST>r f AM-Bloomingdale's     11-29 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bloomingdale's,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloomingdale's Chief Trying to Drum Up Buyout Backing in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloomingdale's Chairman Marvin Traub, seeking
financial support for his proposed buyout of the widely known
department store chain, on Wednesday said he has had ``serious''
talks with Japanese retailers.
   One major Japanese retailer, however, said it turned down an
offer from Traub.
   Traub also indicated the Bloomingdale's name may be affiliated
with retailing in Japan in the future.
   ``I am excited, as a longtime retailer, with opportunities to do
retail business in Japan,'' he told reporters. ``I will be very
pleased to have Bloomingdale's cooperate with premium retailers in
Japan to successfully exploit our name and reputation.''
   Traub did not reveal details of his negotiations in Japan. The
17 Bloomingdale's stores have been put up for sale by Campeau
Corp., a Canadian-based conglomerate burdened with $11.5 billion in
debt.
   The Bloomingdale's chairman said he had been negotiating with
four Japanese groups about backing a management buyout, but he
declined to identify them.
   ``We are having serious, constructive conversations with parties
in Japan,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the Osaka-based Hankyu Department Store told The
Associated Press that it had turned down an offer from Traub.
Spokesman Katsuhiro Hayashi said Hankyu President Shoji Fukumitsu
had met with Traub on Tuesday at Traub's request in Osaka.
   The spokesman gave no details of the offer rejected by
Fukumitsu, whose company had sales of $2.6 billion last year.
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, the leading Japanese economic
newspaper, reported that Traub asked Hankyu to finance $250 million
out of $1.2 billion to $1.3 billion needed for the management
buyout.
   Officials of Tokyu Department Store, another major retailer
mentioned in press reports as a possible investor in
Bloomingdale's, declined to comment.
   Parties to the proposed buyout, Traub told reporters, were about
75 Bloomingdale's executives willing to put up their own money, a
group of ``first-class Japanese retailers'' and financial
institutions in the United States, Japan and Europe.
   Other potential bidders are believed to be interested in the New
York-based Bloomingdale's. Crown American Corp., a privately held
company that is among the leading developers of U.S. shopping
malls, has said it may go after Bloomingdale's.
   Traub, who started working for Bloomingdale's in 1950 and has
been its head since 1978, said he expected the management buyout to
be settled by mid-December, and the process to be completed in
early 1990.
   ``We think the chance of our success is good,'' he said.
</TEXT>
