<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-29 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell in generally lackluster
trading today amid continued uncertainty about interest rates.
   Analysts said computerized trading strategies helped push stock
prices lower in the final hour of trading.
   Stocks came under pressure from the opening as investors took
profits after the market's recent gains. The Dow Jones industrial
average has gained nearly 70 points in the last five trading
sessions.
   Analysts said the stock and bond markets largely ignored reports
on third-quarter Gross National Product and corporate profits.
   Larry Wachtel, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
said investors were focusing on the current quarter.
   ``As far as the market is concerned, that is dated material,''
Wachtel said. ``We now know the economy is floundering and
corporate profits are floundering.''
   The Commerce Department reported that the economy grew at an
annual rate of 2.7 percent in the third quarter, slightly higher
than the 2.5 percent forecast last month.
   A second report showed that corporate profits were down 7.2
percent in the July-September period.
   Analysts said interest rate worries continued to plague the
market after the Federal Reserve both added and drained reserves
from the banking system in recent days.
   Many assumed the Fed's action last week pointed to an easing of
interest rates. But the central bank confused the market with this
week's draining move that sent short-term interest rates higher.
   Bank stocks came under pressure today after Southwest Bank of
St. Louis announced it was raising its prime rate back to 10.5
percent from 10 percent after cutting it three weeks ago.
   Some analysts said, however, that the market's sluggishness was
merely a pause after the recent runup in stock prices and before
the start of a pre-Christmas rally.
   ``It's two days overdue,'' said Ralph Bloch, chief market
analyst with Raymond, James &amp; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Bloch said the recent stock gains were reminiscent of the
October market when a handful of blue-chip issues led the market
higher before prices plunged on October 13.
</TEXT>
