<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAW-Chrysler     11-29 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW-Chrysler,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Defends Plant Closing; UAW Sees Possible Strained Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. executives on Wednesday
defended the planned closing of a Detroit car assembly plant, a
move United Auto Workers union leaders say could worsen labor
relations with the nation's No. 3 automaker.
   The executives and UAW leaders met during their annual weeklong
gathering for exploring ways to ease tensions.
   Much of the discussion Wednesday centered on the planned Feb. 2
closing of the Jefferson Avenue assembly plant in Detroit, where
Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon subcompact cars are made.
   Union members contend the closing, which will result in layoffs
of about 1,700 workers, violates local and national contracts.
Chrysler maintains the closing is permitted because of slumping
sales of the Omni and Horizon.
   Chrysler is building a new assembly plant next to the Jefferson
Avenue factory and it will employ many of the people now making
Omni and Horizon cars. But training for those workers won't begin
until Fall 1991.
   ``We're a little upset at being the last person to know of the
closing of the Jefferson plant,'' said Robert Bowling, president of
UAW Local 110 in St. Louis. ``The press knew before we did, and we
don't think that's right.
   ``(UAW President) Owen Bieber said it pretty well this morning.
He told them that he didn't appreciate it.''
   The company announced on Nov. 3, shortly after a story about the
closing appeared in The Wall Street Journal, that it was halting
production at the Jefferson Avenue factory and trimming production
at its car plant in St. Louis.
   Anthony St. John, Chrysler's vice president for labor relations,
said the first 2{ days of the meeting were constructive, as union
and company officials talked about joint training programs.
   ``Today, there was some initial tension because there was some
concern over the way the Jefferson situation had been handled,'' he
said Wednesday. ``There was a lot of frustration there from an
employee's standpoint.''
   St. John also said Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald told
union members that the Jefferson Avenue plant had fallen victim to
slow cars sales.
   ``Basically, one-shift production is 470 units a day and (daily)
sales orders were averaging about 220, indicating that we were
losing money on each vehicle,'' St. John said.
   Bowling said Greenwald told the union leaders that Chrysler
would try to better handle announcements such as the Jefferson
Avenue plant closing. Bowling said he would be satisfied if the
company kept its commitments.
   Upper-level Chrysler and UAW officials have been gathering for
similar annual meetings since 1986 and Chrysler Chairman Lee
Iacocca has spoken at the previous ones.
   Iacocca skipped this year's opportunity to address union
representatives, saying there was a longstanding previous
commitment.
   The meeting began eight days after hundreds of angry UAW members
paraded outside Chrysler headquarters in the Detroit enclave of
Highland Park, protesting the planned Jefferson Avenue closing.
   Contract talks between the union and the nation's Big Three
automakers _ General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler _
begin next summer. Union contracts with the companies expire at
midnight, Sept. 14, 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891129-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-29 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Price Slide Steepens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices fell sharply Wednesday on New York's Commodity
Exchange, steepening a slide that represents either a temporary
setback in a bull market or gold's retreat from its highest point
in nearly a year.
   ``I think the verdict is still out on that one,'' said John
Jonat, a trader with Deak International Inc., a New York-based
dealer of precious metals and foreign currencies.
   On other futures markets Wednesday, pork-belly futures fell the
limit for the second straight day; energy futures advanced; and
grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $3.90 to $4 lower on the Comex with the
contract for delivery in December down $4 at $409.50 a troy ounce.
Silver fell 9.5 cents to 9.7 cents with December settling at $5.60
a troy ounce.
   The December gold contract has dropped more than $10 since
Friday, when it peaked at $419.70, the highest Comex gold price
since mid-December.
   Jonat said he was surprised gold fell so sharply after Tuesday's
very slight loss, which he had taken as a sign that a wave of
profit-taking had passed.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``I'm reluctant to say the path is going
to be down.''
   Analyst Don Tierney of Stanley Bell &amp; Co., a New York-based
futures brokerage, blamed the decline on selling ahead of the first
notice day for the December gold contract.
   Under Comex rules, Thursday is the first day for traders to
declare their intention to deliver gold against the December
contract. A relatively large number of delivery notices are
expected, and traders on the ``buy'' side of December contracts
must sell contracts to avoid taking physical delivery.
   ``The market has been in a little bit of a nervous condition
ahead of this delivery position,'' Tierney said. ``After the
pressure is out of the way from the first day of deliveries, the
market will then resume its trend.''
   Pork-belly futures prices slammed down the 2-cents-a-pound daily
limit for the second straight day on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange after the government announced it had accepted bids for
920,000 pounds of pork bellies to be shipped to Poland as part of a
food aid package.
   The announcement follows last week's announcement of a
280,000-pound government purchase, bringing to 1.2 million pounds
the amount of bellies the government has bought to ship to Poland.
   The market's reaction reflected disappointment that the
government is not moving more quickly toward obtaining the total of
22 million pounds that it is expected to buy.
   ``At this pace, it would take forever to fill up a cargo to send
over there,'' said Charles Levitt, senior livestock analyst with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   Live cattle futures settled .07 cent to .72 cent lower with
December at 75.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .32 cent lower
to .17 cent higher with November at 83.72 cents a pound; live hogs
were .15 cent to .63 cent lower with December at 50.52 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.98 cents to 2 cents lower with
February at 60.55 cents a pound.
   Energy futures rose moderately on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, reflecting sentiments that the market had overreacted
Tuesday to OPEC's decision to raise its crude-oil output on Jan. 1
to 22 million barrels per day from 20.5 million.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 15 cents
higher with January at $19.40 a barrel; heating oil was .30 cent to
.59 cent higher with December at 60.61 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .19 cent to .35 cent higher with December at 49.72
cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished mixed on the Chicago
Board of Trade in a lackluster session.
   Wheat futures settled 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with
December at $4.05} a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents higher
with December at $2.34} a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent lower
with December at $1.42} a bushel; soybeans were { cent lower to 3{
cents higher with January at $5.79\ a bushel.
