<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-29 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices rebounded Wednesday in
a technical reaction to Tuesday's selloff.
   Forecasts of continuing cold weather in the Northeast spurred
buying of wholesale home heating oil.
   Despite the rebound, the renewed buying in the energy futures
pits was restrained because traders still were downcast about the
new OPEC production agreement. The cartel's higher output ceiling
is expected to weigh on prices.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, made up less than half of Tuesday's
38-cent loss. It rose 15 cents to close at $19.40 per 42-gallon
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Contracts for delivery
in February through April finished with smaller gains.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the New York Merc,
No.2 heating oil for December delivery rose 0.30 cent to 60.61
cents a gallon after falling 0.61 cent on Tuesday. The January
through March contracts ended with larger increases.
   Mary Haskins, a Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. analyst, said
expectations of an extended cold snap on the East Coast and in
other parts of the country probably boosted heating oil demand
slightly. For much of the autumn, unusually mild temperatures
caused a buildup in heating oil stocks in the Northeast.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery finished 0.19
cent higher at 49.72 cents a gallon, erasing a small portion of
Tuesday's drop of 1.36 cents. Contracts for later delivery posted
larger gains.
   Energy market analysts said traders still were preoccupied with
the outcome of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries'
winter conference.
   At a meeting in Vienna, ministers from the cartel's 13 members
agreed to raise their self-imposed daily production limit to 22
million barrels for the first half of next year from the current
20.5 million barrels.
   Other than the OPEC developments, there was little news for
traders to act on. The energy markets had slumped Tuesday on word
of the OPEC agreement. The selling may have been overdone and
Wednesday's modest recovery was described by traders as a technical
correction.
</TEXT>
