<FIRST>u f BC-AirFares 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Air Fares, 1st Ld-Writethru,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta, Pan Am Raising Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS graf to UPDATE with United, others postponing increases;
SUBS last graf pvs to conform; No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines has announced plans to raise
economy and first-class fares, while Pan Am Corp. said it would
increase the price of discount tickets.
   Pan Am said Tuesday it plans to raise its MaxSaver fares, the
most deeply discounted advance-purchase fares, by $10 to $20 round
trip starting Dec. 16. The MaxSavers would be increased by $10 on
flights of less than 1,000 miles and $20 on longer trips.
   ``I would think the other airlines would follow Pan Am because
we're seeing costs increase pretty sharply,'' said Edward J.
Starkman, an airline analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   ``It's going to be a carrier-by-carrier decision,'' he said.
``They're going to have to look at their advance bookings and
decide.''
   Passenger traffic normally begins increasing at this time of
year, a peak holiday travel season.
   Last week, in a bid to bolster sagging revenues, a number of
major carriers led by United Airlines said they plan to raise fares
on most domestic routes and eliminate discount fares used mainly by
business travelers. The increases didn't apply to the popular
MaxSavers, however.
   Atlanta-based Delta, which announced its move Tuesday, is the
last major airline to follow United's lead. Under the change,
first-class, one-way fares will increase by $8, while full-fare and
some discounted coach prices will go up by $5.
   United decided Wednesday to postpone the fare hikes until Dec.
8, spokeswoman Sara Dornacker said. They originally were scheduled
to take effect Thursday. Other carriers, including American
Airlines, also said they were postponing the increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
