<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing-Engineers     11-29 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Engineers,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Engineers Call in Mediator, Machinists File Grievance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal mediator was called Wednesday into
contract talks between The Boeing Co. and its engineers, while the
machinists union that ended a strike only 10 days ago filed a
grievance against the aerospace giant.
   Negotiators for the second-largest union at Boeing, the Seattle
Professional Engineering Employees Association, contacted a federal
mediator after receiving a ``disappointing'' money offer from
Boeing on Monday, union general counsel Dan Mahoney said Wednesday.
   ``Their view of an acceptable offer doesn't harmonize with
SPEEA's view,'' Mahoney said. ``This is always the way it is; you
never flat-out accept what they lay on the table. To expedite
whatever movement there might be, we thought it was wise to get the
mediator in there to talk to both parties.''
   Mediator Ben Youtsey started moving between company and union
negotiating teams Wednesday morning.
   Non-economic and some economic issues had been resolved, but a
number of money disagreements remained, including the ``entire wage
offer,'' Mahoney said. He declined to elaborate.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder also refused to discuss details of
the offer Wednesday.
   ``At this point in negotiations it's not uncommon for a mediator
to come in to assist in reaching a final agreement,'' Binder said.
   SPEEA executive director and chief negotiator Walt Baer said
Wednesday he hoped to conclude talks within the next few days and
mail an offer to members.
   SPEEA has two contracts under negotiation, covering a total of
about 27,800 workers. The contracts expire Friday, but have been
extended until new contracts are reached.
   Machinists, who comprise the largest union at Boeing, used
federal mediator Doug Hammond for much of their talks with Boeing
negotiators and Hammond proposed the compromise package finally
accepted by both sides, bringing the 48-day strike to an end on
Nov. 20.
   The machinists contract affects some 57,800 Boeing workers.
   But the machinists' union, District Lodge 751 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
filed a grievance with Boeing Wednesday complaining the company
violated strike settlement and collective bargaining agreements by
reassigning 838 employees to lower-ranked and lower-paying posts as
they returned to work because of the strike.
   The union asks that each employee be returned to the work
location, shift, labor grade and job classification that he or she
held on the day of work prior to the strike, and that all employees
be compensated for any loss of benefits and wages.
   Binder acknowledged receipt of the grievance but said Boeing
maintains no employees ``received any reduction in pay or
anything.''
   He declined to discuss the issue further.
   The 27,800 engineers, scientists and technical aides covered
under SPEEA contracts at Boeing have never gone out on strike.
Ninety-five percent of them work in the Seattle area.
   SPEEA and Boeing negotiators have been meeting every week day
sinc Nov. 2, plus last weekend.
   SPEEA had asked for a salary adjustment of 35 percent over three
years, including 14 percent in the first six months. But Mahoney
said the union had made some reductions since presenting its first
proposal.
   Pay for Boeing engineers and scientists averages about $39,000
annually, while technical aides earn an average of $29,000.
   The machinists won annual wage increases of 4 percent, 3 percent
and 3 percent, plus bonuses of 10 percent, 5 percent and 4 percent,
and a cost-of-living adjustment equal to almost 100 percent of
inflation.
</TEXT>
