<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Varity-K-H     11-29 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Varity-K-H,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockholders Approve Varity Acquisition of Former Fruehauf Corp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Varity Corp.'s proposed $579 million acquisition
of K-H Corp., formerly Fruehauf Corp., was approved by K-H
stockholders Wednesday, the company said.
   The sale is the last stage in the dismantling of Fruehauf to pay
debt from a leveraged buyout arranged to fight off a 1986 takeover
attempt.
   K-H's main holding is Kelsey-Hayes Co., a producer of aluminum
wheels and anti-lock braking systems.
   Fruehauf changed its name to K-H on Aug. 4 after selling
maritime operations and the truck-trailer manufacturing business
that had been its mainstay. The trailer business continues as
Fruehauf Trailer Corp., a Terex Corp. subsidiary.
   K-H Corp. will become a wholly owned subsidiary of Varity,
formerly Massey-Ferguson, a Toronto-based maker of farm and
industrial machinery.
   The transaction could be completed Thursday or Friday, K-H
spokesman David Hladik said.
   Fruehauf borrowed $1.5 billion in 1986 in a restructuring
arranged in conjunction with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. to fend off a
hostile takeover attempt by investor Asher Edelman.
   Weighed down with debt, the company ran into ill-timed reverses
in the truck trailer business, including increased competition and
a surge in materials costs, such as the price of aluminum, Hladik
said.
   ``We ended up selling off all our assets to pay off the debt,''
he said.
   Those included a fleet of 5,000 leased trailers, a financial
subsidiary and an aerospace unit.
   The trailer and maritime operations _ including two shipyards
and a heavy crane and cargo handling equipment division _ were sold
to Terex on July 14 for $232.5 million.
   ``The sale of the trailer operation was more or less the end of
Fruehauf,'' Hladik said.
   Varity agreed to acquire K-H for about $579 million. That
included $41.3 million in cash, the transfer of 37.8 million worth
of new Varity common shares to K-H stockholders, and assumption of
$436.8 million in K-H debt by Varity.
   K-H employs about 7,000 people. It has seven plants in Michigan,
three in Ohio, two in California, one each in Indiana, Kentucky and
Missouri and four in Canada, Hladik said.
</TEXT>
