<FIRST>r f BC-Toyota-US     11-29 0117</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toyota-US,0123</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Starts Auto Engine Production at U.S. Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. said its U.S. auto plant on
Thursday began producing engines for the company's popular Camry
models, which in the future will be exported to Japan.
   Toyota, Japan's largest automaker, said in a release Thursday
that annual production at Toyota Motor Manufacturing U.S.A. Inc. at
Georgetown, Ky., will be increased to 300,000 units in 1992.
   Toyota's Kentucky plant employs 3,000 workers and currently
produces 200,000 Camry sedans a year, the company said.
   A total of 40,000 right-hand-drive vehicles and 100,000 engines,
produced at the $1.1 billion plant, will be shipped to Japan
beginning in 1992, as previously planned, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
